<HEAD>`Sunrise Wind' Bodes Ill For Farming Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POST, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tough year for farmers is in the wind _ that is, if an old Comanche Indian legend holds true. According to the legend, the wind direction at precisely sunrise on the day after the first day of spring will tell what kind of weather and farming conditions the next year will hold for the region. If the wind, called <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> ` na <PERSON> Yuna </PERSON>' e in Comanche, comes from the east or northeast, good harvests should follow; if it blows from the north or northwest, conditions will be A west or southwest wind does n't bode well, and a south wind is just plain bad news. Records on the annual ceremony are said to show a 92 percent success rate since 1906, the first year settlers gathered to see what the winds had in store. `` Chief'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkles </PERSON>, who has been performing the ceremony for 15 years, began his dance Tuesday with supplications to <LOCATION> Wakantanka </LOCATION>, the Father Spirit, and <PERSON> Mikeana </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mother </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, as well as the winds. `` The <LOCATION> Mother </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> is revered because she gives us food to eat,'' he said. `` Wakantanka is the Great Father above _ we seek his blessings.'' As he spoke, a southerly wind blew so hard that Indian dancers from an <ORGANIZATION> Amarillo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Explorer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> had to shield a ceremonial fire as it was ignited. The gusts died down as sunrise neared. Seconds before <PERSON> Runkles </PERSON> caught the first glimpse of the sun over the distant horizon, a gust whisked in from the north, then reversed direction at the moment of sunrise, giving an official reading of west-southwest _ bad news for farmers. Despite the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>' claims of predictive accuracy, however, farmers do n't necessarily need to worry. Last year, smoke from Runkles' fire indicated a south wind and poor conditions, but <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> farmers ended up with one of the best cotton harvests on record.
