<HEAD>High School Sing Reaches Screen With Patti LaBelle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in report for Thursday AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Above a pawn shop in downtown <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> rips into a group of lackadaisical <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> high school students. In her first major dramatic role, the pop star is playing an inspirational teacher in a movie musical based on Sing, the annual song-and-dance competition in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>'s schools. The legendary program at such schools as Erasmus Hall gave rise to such talents as Barbra Streisand and <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON>. But with the urban decay of the past decade, only a dozen schools now take part. The struggle to preserve that old <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> spirit has inspired the film, `` SING,'' with a plot centered on education board plans to close a beloved high school where generations of immigrants got their start. With songs from the writer of `` Footloose'' and `` Fame'' and a tempestuous love story between a street-smart Italian kid and a Jewish princess, the Tri-Star Pictures production now shooting in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> is scheduled for release in February 1989. `` I'm hooked on it. I'm one of those people who think about community and pulling together and family,'' said <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON>, the rhythm and blues artist who first hit the pop charts in the 1960s with the <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bells </ORGANIZATION> and later in the'70s with the trio <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON>. She has appeared in two previous films, `` A Soldier's Story'' and the TV movie `` Unnatural Causes.'' In `` SING,'' she plays Mrs. <PERSON> Devere </PERSON>, an adviser who shakes her junior class students out of apathy. `` She's very uplifting to the kids,'' <PERSON> Labelle </PERSON> said between takes of her chart-targeted big number, `` Total Concentration,'' in which she demonstrates how to put over a song. Producer <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Zadan </PERSON> and screenwriter-lyricist <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitchford </PERSON>, who won an Academy Award for `` Fame,'' said they created the part with <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> in mind and waited until she found time to do it. `` There's a real honesty there, nothing phony about her. In her own way she's lived through what this teacher has gone through,'' said <PERSON> Pitchford </PERSON>. <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> has charmed the crew by introducing them to her own home cooking _ fried chicken and potato salad. But she's not sure about life as an actress. `` I'm not a Cher. I do n't know if I'd have enough patience to do another movie,'' she said, complaining about the number of retakes. `` It hurts enough some times that you want to cry. I like to perform live.'' However, director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON>, who co-produced Streisand's landmark `` Broadway Album'' and is making his first feature film, said <PERSON> LaBelle </PERSON> looked great in the first rushes Co-stars include <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracco </PERSON> who played <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Berenger </PERSON>'s wife in `` Someone to Watch Over Me,'' <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasser </PERSON> of `` <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>'' fame and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicenzo </PERSON> who was <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>'s boss in `` About Last Night.'' The young lovers are <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Steen </PERSON>. For co-producer <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Meron </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and Sing alumnus, the project is a labor of love. `` In the high school I went to, Sing no longer exists,'' <PERSON> Meron </PERSON> lamented. `` <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> is one of the oldest communities in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and the way those communities found to express themselves was through music and dance.'' To research the film, the production team talked with veteran teachers in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and attended a Sing performance at <ORGANIZATION> Midwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> where faculty member <PERSON> Bella </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillis </PERSON> launched the program in 1947. Sing competitions involved reviews or skits created and staged by a committee from each class. The musical skits were judged on sing night when freshmen, sophomores, juniors and seniors got to strut their stuff. In the 1950s and'60s, when Sing was at its peak, the competitions were fierce. Lyricist <PERSON> Pitchford </PERSON> also found inspiration in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where he's been working with the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on the Broadway-bound musical, `` Carrie. `` After ` Fame' the last thing I wanted to do was another high school film set in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> about kids who sing and dance,'' he said. `` But <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> has tradition and history we can only approximate in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The closest thing to that kind of longevity is in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> settlements like <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. Sing became a metaphor for that tradition. `` I developed an enormous affection for Sing and the neighborhoods of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and a real despair for the passing of this tradition.''
