<FIRST>r i PM-Cyprus-Archaeology     03-24 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyprus-Archaeology,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyprus' Civilization May Be 1,500 Years Older Than Believed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKROTIRI, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New discoveries by American archaeologists indicate that humans could have settled on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> around 9000 B.C., 1,500 years earlier than previously thought. The finds also indicate that some species of ancient animals survived here at least 1,000 years after they were believed to have become extinct. If proven correct, the discoveries mean that <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> was one of the earliest human settlements north of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, along with the island of <LOCATION> Corsica </LOCATION>, also in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. `` If these dates are corroborated, the site will have provided by far the earliest archaeological evidence for island colonization anywhere in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>,'' Dr. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Swiny </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Cyprus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, reported in a recent lecture. Scientists had previously dated man's arrival on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> around 7500 B.C. But archaelogists digging on a slope near the sprawling British air base at <LOCATION> Akrotiri </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>' south coast recently found pygmy hippopotamus and dwarf elephant bones, some mixed with shells, flint and ash. Archaelogists believe the flint, an early cutting tool, was used to slice meat from the animals. The ash indicated cooking fires. Carbon dating placed the remains at around 9000 B.C., a millenium after those species of animals were believed to have died out. <PERSON> Swiny </PERSON> said that the animals, common to many <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> islands thousands of years ago, were wiped out by climatic changes during the last Ice Age that ended around 12,000 years ago. `` We thought ... these animals died out because of natural causes _ they could n't get enough food or enough water,'' <PERSON> Swiny </PERSON> said in an interview after the lecture. `` But now it looks as if man was also responsible for wiping them out.'' The <LOCATION> Akrotiri </LOCATION> excavation is sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oriental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsors the <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> institute. The dig is under the direction of Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, who currently is in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. The original discovery was made in 1980 by a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> security officer at <LOCATION> Akrotiri </LOCATION>, Maj. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Pile </PERSON>, then a lieutenant, while he was training his men to seek out unusual objects. Underground excavation at the site, eight miles south of the port city of <LOCATION> Limassol </LOCATION>, started last July and will continue this summer. <PERSON> Swiny </PERSON> said the actual age of the site will remain questionable until results of further tests are obtained. The finds are only some of the important discoveries unearthed by American archaeologists in the last few years on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, the center of trade routes between <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> for centuries. The island is studded with relics of a history that spans more than 10,000 years, during which more than a dozen civilizations, including Achaean Greeks, Egyptians, Romans, Armenians, Venetians and Ottoman Turks left their imprint. Americans are involved in six of the 20 digs currently being made in the Greek-controlled southern part of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The Cyprus American institute provides logistical help at one sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Waltham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, at the Late Bronze Age town of <LOCATION> Kalavasos-Ayios </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dhimitrios </LOCATION>, 18 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Limassol </LOCATION>. It was one of the biggest Bronze Age settlements on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and a center for the island's ancient copper trade. <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> is the Phoenician word for copper. Last summer archaelogists uncovered the remains of a 13th century B.C. building, covering more than 10,764 square feet and once at least two stories high, that was apparently destroyed by fire. `` It's the biggest and most important building at the site and one of the biggest of that period in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> South </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, the dig's co-director. `` We also found some inscriptions which are very rare to the period in Cypro-Minoan script,'' she added. Cypro-Minoan, which resembles the script used in <LOCATION> Minoan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> 4,000 years ago, has never been deciphered. The presence of these inscriptions and the huge storage capacity of the building, known as Building X, suggest it was either a palace or a town hall. The storage room, more than 60 feet long and 24 feet wide, consists of an outer wall and six stone pillars that once supported the roof. The shards of at least 47 jars, some once as tall as six feet, have been found. All apparently had been smashed in the fire. But six intact jars were later discovered in pits below the floor. <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> discovered a tomb, considered one of the richest and best preserved ever found on <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, while digging an exploratory trench out from the building. The oval-shaped tomb contained the skeletons of three young women, a child about 3 years old and three infants. They apparently had social status and wealth. The women had been buried with gold and silver jewelry, bronze and bone artifacts, containers of wine with small cups inside and cylindrical ivory cosmetic boxes.
