<FIRST>r a PM-ProstateTreatment     03-24 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prostate Treatment,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enlarged Prostates Treated Without Hospital Stay, Researcher
Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental treatment for enlarged prostate glands shows promise as an outpatient alternative to surgery that hospitalizes about 400,000 American men a year, researchers say. An enlarged prostate makes urination difficult by constricting the urinary tract, and the experimental procedure widens the narrowed portion by inflating a balloon, said <PERSON> Flavio </PERSON> <PERSON> Castaneda </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. Test results show complete or significant resolution of the urination problem in about 80 percent of patients with the most common type of enlargement, he said. The half-hour procedure is done with only a local anesthetic and without an overnight stay in the hospital, he said. Standard surgery requires general anesthesia or a spinal injection that numbs the lower part of the body, and a hospital stay of several days. The prostate is a walnut-sized gland that surrounds the urine-carrying urethra. In older men, it frequently enlarges and puts pressure on the urethra, making urination more difficult. The experimental technique is to be described Thursday by <PERSON> Castaneda </PERSON>'s colleague, <PERSON> Wilfrido </PERSON> <PERSON> Castaneda-Zuniga </PERSON>, at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiovascular </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Interventional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. More than 60 patients have been treated with the experimental procedure, called balloon urethroplasty, at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Castaneda </PERSON> said in a recent telephone interview The patient takes a tranquilizer and the urethra is numbed with local anesthetic. A thin, flexible tube with the balloon on its tip is inserted into the urethra and guided to the narrowed portion, where the balloon is inflated. For the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> patients, the urination problem was erased or significantly eased in almost 80 percent of cases in which most enlargement was from the side lobes of the prostate, rather than the middle lobe, <PERSON> Castanada </PERSON> said. Most patients have predominant enlargement of side lobes, he said. When the main problem was the middle lobe, the success rate dropped to about 30 percent to 40 percent, he said. No recurrence of symptoms has been seen in any patient helped by the procedure, he said. Forty-eight have been followed for more than six months after the procedure, including one followed for three years, he said. `` We're at this point unable to know how long it -LRB- symptom relief -RRB- will last on the average,'' <PERSON> Castaneda </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Cockett </PERSON>, professor and chairman of the urology department at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, called the concept interesting. But he said more patients must be studied, and for periods longer than at least a year following the procedure, to better assess its effectiveness. Removing prostate tissue with standard surgery relieves symptoms for some 15 years, said <PERSON> Cockett </PERSON>, who is secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In another presentation at the meeting Thursday, participants are to discuss an experimental alternative to removing gallbladders. About 500,000 gallbladders are removed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> annually. Gallstones are the most frequent reason, said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, director of cardiovascular and interventional radiology at the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia-Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In two patients, Italian scientists have instead guided a flexible tube through the skin and into the gallbladder, used it to remove gallstones and injected a solution to turn the gallbladder into scar tissue. `` I still think it needs a lot of work, but it's exciting,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. He noted that machines called lithotripters, now used to pulverize kidney stones, are also being studied for destroying gallstones. It is too early to tell how lithotripters and the surgical technique tried in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> will fit in to future management of gallbladder disease, he said.
</TEXT>
