<HEAD>Congress Moving to Cut Timbering in Alaska Rain Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is chopping away at the huge timber harvests in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> rain forest, the nation's largest national forest and the timber cutting programs's biggest money loser The panel gave voice vote approval Wednesday to legislation pushed by hard-lobbying conservation groups to scrap the 1980 law guaranteeing that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> gets at least $ 40 million a year to spend on Tongass timber sales. The money, much of it for logging roads to ancient stands of huge trees, was mandated as part of the compromise that apportioned public lands in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> for various uses, including commercial development and wilderness. The compromise gave protected wilderness status to 5.4 million acres of the 17.9 million acre <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION>, which has the nation's largest populations of bald eagles and grizzly bears The 1980 law, in what backers said represented economic guarantees for southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, set a goal of commercially harvesting 450 billion board feet of Tongass trees every 10 years from non-wilderness sections. No other national forest has a congressionally mandated harvest goal or gets its appropriations without the year-by-year review <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gives to spending requests for other federal forests. Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, D-Minn., said that because of low demand and falling prices for wood pulp from <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION>, taxpayers have lost 99 cents for each $ 1 in sales, with some old trees going for $ 2 apiece <PERSON> Vento </PERSON> called the 1980 law `` a mandate to overcut ... one of the world's only temperate rain forests.'' `` We're changing the entire environment when we cut 400 - and 500-year-old trees,'' he said Approved by the committee was a package put together by Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., to scrap the 1980 timbering guarantees and assure that the Tongass is subject to the same timber-harvest planning practices applied to all other national forests The bill would put a five-year moratorium on commercial logging in about 1.7 million acres considered by the <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to be prime fish and wildlife habitat threatened by timbering. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s plan also would require the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to renegotiate its long-term contracts to supply Tongass timber to two large mills owned by <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific-Ketchikan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pulp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. About two-thirds of the Tongass production goes to these mills, which convert it to pulp, principally for export to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Critics say the 50-year contracts, executed in the 1950s, give the companies a regional monopoly and too large a voice in <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> management decisions for the Tongass. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the Tongass now is `` almost a scandalous operation.'' `` We have a process that is not driven by rational forest management,'' he said. `` We have cuttings driven by a political bargain.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s only <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member and the ranking Republican on <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION>, opposed <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s plan because `` it basically shuts down the mills. ... We're talking about 6,000 jobs.'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the committee was being unduly influenced by conservation groups such as the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, which have made the <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> and a proposal to drill for oil in the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> their major Capitol Hill battlegrounds in 1988. Young called the environmental groups `` special interests'' and said, `` The national environmental community is jerking our string.''
