<HEAD>Yields Up on Two-Year Treasury Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Yields on two-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes have risen in the government's latest auction to the highest level in two months. The average yield in Wednesday's auction was 7.39 percent, up from 7.16 percent at the last auction on Feb. 24. It was the highest rate since two-year notes averaged 7.4 percent on Jan. 27. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 7 -RRB- percent, with each $ 10,000 in face value selling for $ 9,997.30. A total of $ 8.53 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling $ 25.08 billion.
