<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Workers,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Reviews Federal-State Roles in Protecting Fired Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> never intended to outlaw state rules against retaliatory firings when it gave the federal government the authority to protect union workers, the lawyer for a Southern Illinois woman says. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that lower courts erred in ruling that <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> could not penalize a company for firing a union employee who filed a workers' compensation claim. He asked the court to overturn the decision and rule in favor of <PERSON> Jonna </PERSON> <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union member dismissed from her job at the <ORGANIZATION> Norge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chef </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Herrin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` The right of -LRB- state -RRB- action is available to both union and non-union employees alike,'' <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> told the court in oral arguments Wednesday. `` That right is independent of the rights enjoyed under a collective bargaining agreement.'' <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> is one of 21 states with laws against retaliatory firings. But a lawyer for <ORGANIZATION> Norge </ORGANIZATION> said the federal Labor-Management Relations Act makes enforcement of union contracts _ through the decisions of an arbitrator _ the province of the federal government. `` If independent state laws were enacted that flew in the teeth of a labor contract, they were pre-empted,'' attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told the court. `` Permitting the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> law to stand would be an incentive to undermine collective bargaining.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> conceded that states may act on health and safety matters but said Mrs. <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON>'s firing was a contract issue covered by federal labor law. According to court records, the woman notified the Herrin-based Norge in late 1984 that she was injured on the job and asked the company to pay her medical bills, as provided for by the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> workers' compensation law. <PERSON> Norge </PERSON> fired Mrs. <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> a week later, contending she filed a false claim. However, the Machinists' contract with <ORGANIZATION> Norge </ORGANIZATION> contained a provision protecting workers from dismissal without just cause, and the union filed a grievance the day she was fired. An arbitrator later ordered her reinstatement with back pay. But in the interim, Mrs. <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> filed a circuit court lawsuit contending the dismissal violated <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> law and seeking additional compensation. The relief available through the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> court was greater than what she could receive through arbitration, which did not include punitive damages and compensation for lost overtime. Norge shifted the case to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, where a judge threw out Mrs. <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON>'s lawsuit, ruling that state law was pre-empted by the arbitration remedy provided by federal labor law. The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> upheld the dismissal in June 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is expected to rule on the appeal in July. The State and <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said 21 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have laws protecting workers who file compensation claims. It identified the states as <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>.
