<HEAD>Disabled Drivers Claim Out-Of-State Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Disabled motorists suffer from a patchwork of state regulations that leaves them vulnerable to parking tickets when they drive to other states, say advocates of a national parking symbol for the disabled. `` It is ludicrous for us to remove one barrier to the handicapped by offering handicapped parking spots, only to erect another by refusing an out-of-state resident the right to park there,'' Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Wednesday `` If a person is disabled in one state, does not logic dictate that the same person is disabled in another state?'' he asked. <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> has drafted legislation that would require states to use a national handicapped access symbol and have reciprocity with all other states. States that do not comply would have federal highway safety funds withheld. A measure to withhold 2 percent of a non-complying state's highway safety funds was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last year The House has not acted. <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said he raised the issue after being contacted by <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON> <PERSON> DeGiovanni </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, who started a campaign against the system three years ago after she was ticketed in <LOCATION> Lynn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, while parked in a handicapped zone. `` When states are allowed to ticket people for merely exercising their right to a handicapped parking space, it discourages handicapped people from going out,'' Mrs. <PERSON> DeGiovanni </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on surface transportation. She called the current system `` ridiculous'' and discriminatory. There are 6.5 million disabled Americans who use special parking permits. Only 15 states honor handicapped parking permits from every state, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> study conducted last year.
