<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stage for congressional warfare has been set by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee's vote to kill funding for the Trident submarine in the 1989 budget and use the $ 1.4 billion savings to build two more Aegis destroyers. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> seapower subcommittee voted in closed session Tuesday for the funding switch, conceived by the panel's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>. Word of the vote came Wednesday from Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., who vowed to fight it and predicted Trident funding would <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>'s district includes the Electric Boat shipyard, the division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that builds Tridents. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> promised to defend the change when the full committee looks at the fiscal 1989 budget next week. The subcommittee vote reflects congressional opposition to an administration plan to sell two Aegis DDG-51 destroyers to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> and others fear the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would lose technological secrets as a result. Under the subcommittee plan, the government would order five Aegis warships in 1989 instead of the three requested by the administration. The two extra destroyers would be deployed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> control, protecting Japanese security interests while keeping the Aegis technology under wraps. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is `` very leery'' about selling the warships to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> because of revelations last year that <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> sold submarine technology secrets to the Soviets. But <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON> said the Pentagon has confidence in the Japanese government. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has held many of our secrets, so we do n't seem them as a security risk at all,'' he said. `` Toshiba is a company, not the government.'' The request from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for two Aegis ships has not been formally made, but is expected, <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials had no immediate response to the <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> plan, but any suggestion to eliminate a Trident would likely be attacked by the Pentagon. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> quit as secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> last month in part because <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> refused to allow him to cut the Trident from the budget. <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, who is not a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the seapower panel deleted funding for the Trident two years ago, but funding was later restored by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` While I am clearly disappointed by the decision of the seapower subcommittee, the subcommittee's decision is only the first step in a lengthy and complex budget process,'' <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that he would fight to keep the Trident out and the two extra Aegis ships in. He said the program, which traditionally calls for one new Trident each year, would be continued in the 1990 budget. Electric Boat is the sole builder of the 18,750-ton submarine, which is armed with 24 long-range, multiwarhead missiles. The subs are built at the company's yards in <LOCATION> Groton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingstown </LOCATION>, R.I. The 8,300-ton Aegis destroyer, equipped with 90 missiles, is being built by Bath Iron Works in Bath, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Ingalls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pascagoula </LOCATION>, Miss.
