<FIRST>r a PM-StrokeOperation Bjt   03-24 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroke Operation, Bjt,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds High Complication Rate In Common Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A common operation intended to prevent stroke causes death or serious stroke in 10 percent of the elderly patients who undergo it, a study published today concludes. The study, based on a large survey of the operation called carotid endartectomy, also found that two-thirds of the operations were judged to be unnecessary or of questionable value. The researchers concluded that the operation is substantially overused. In areas where the complication rate is as high as the average found in the survey, the surgery should never be done `` because the risks would almost certainly outweigh the benefits,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> doctors in their study published in the New England Journal of Medicine. They recommended that the procedure be limited to hospitals and doctors that have low complication rates. `` If you look for very hard-nosed proof of the operation, it's hard to show that what we are doing is the right thing,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Skillman </PERSON>, a vascular surgeon at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Beth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> `` There are a lot of indications, as this paper suggests, that a lot of people are being operated on who do n't need the surgery at all.'' The number of the operations grew from 85,000 in 1982 to 107,000 in 1985. However, in 1986 it dropped to 83,000, apparently as a result of growing criticism of the surgery. `` It's my hope that with the publicity, it may be that people are asking for second opinions,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyken </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who was one of the first to question the wide use of the operation. The surgery is performed on the carotid arteries in an effort to prevent strokes. These arteries run up both sides of the neck. If they become plugged, the flow of blood to the head is interrupted, and some of the brain may die, resulting in permanent damage. In the surgery, doctors open the arteries and clean out plaque that partially obstructs them. `` You ought to have the operation if it is truly indicated for you and if you have a surgeon with a record for complications that is very good,'' said Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, one of the Rand researchers. `` Our guess is that if those two prescriptions were followed, there would indeed be a lot less operations done.'' The study reviewed the records of 1,302 randomly selected <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients who had the surgery in three different parts of the country. A panel of experts judged that one-third of the operations were justified, another third were questionable, while the rest were clearly unnecessary. In most cases, the Rand researchers considered the operation appropriate only if patients suffered warning symptoms, had significant clogging of the carotid arteries and were in good enough health to withstand the surgery. In the survey, more than 3 percent of the patients died as a result of their surgery, while more than 6 percent suffered strokes during or immediately after the operations. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said that when the operation is studied at big medical centers, the combined death and stroke rate is usually under 3 percent. Other studies have shown that if people have small strokes that cause momentary dizziness, brief blindness or other passing symptoms, they face a 10 percent annual risk of major strokes. If they have narrowed carotid arteries but no warning signs, their annual stroke risk is about 3 percent. Despite the findings, however, experts said that some patients probably benefit from the operation. `` I do n't think it suggests at all that the operation should n't be done,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> J.M </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Robarts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. `` It suggests, though, that a more critical view of who should have the operation is required of our profession.''
</TEXT>
