<FIRST>r a PM-AnimalFarm Bjt   03-24 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Animal Farm, Bjt,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Hospital In Dispute Over An Animal Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> the dog, <PERSON> Merlin </PERSON> the goat and scores of rabbits, chickens, finches and mice have been declared fauna non grata at the state hospital where they have helped soothe and socialize mental patients. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> is the recreational therapist responsible for the animal farm known since 1970 as the <ORGANIZATION> Stress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Learning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Creedmoor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The hospital has ordered the program to shut down and the animals off the grounds by Friday. `` At this point what I'm doing is putting myself in the position of willing insubordination,'' said <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON>, 48. He said the hospital administration engaged in `` a sham and a dupe job'' by investigating his program. `` We have many concerns,'' hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Amatulli </PERSON> said Wednesday. Chief among them are <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> and his unorthodox approach to protocol in that most bureaucratic of institutions, a state mental hospital. <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> says his eight patients _ down from 16 a few months ago _ feed, groom, exercise and care for about 60 animals. `` It opens them up to wonder. ... It makes them come alive,'' he said of the patients. `` There's an incredible sense of purpose and achievement because they know that these animals are dependent on them.'' `` It's just a really beautiful program,'' said photographer <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, who has been documenting the animal farm on the Queens hospital grounds for 11 months. `` It's just so beautiful to see how not only the animals are nurtured, but the patients are nurtured.'' <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> contends that hospital director <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstock </PERSON> targeted the animal program for elimination shortly after he took over at <LOCATION> Creedmore </LOCATION> about nine months ago. <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Weinstock </PERSON> asked him for information about the patients in the program, which he provided, and then asked him for budgetary and other information. <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> said he refused to provide the information because by that time, he was convinced the hospital only wanted to shut down his program. Among other things, he said, the administration confiscated the stress center's van, which he said was needed to transport both animals and patients. Recently, he said, he and his patients were ordered reassigned and he was told to get rid of the animals. He said he reacted `` maybe arrogantly, maybe defiantly,'' and refused. Ms. <PERSON> Amatulli </PERSON> denied that the hospital set out to destroy <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON>' program. <PERSON> Weinstock </PERSON> merely wanted to evaluate its effectiveness and costs, she said, and had no choice but to suspend the program when <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> refused to cooperate. <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Creedmoor </LOCATION> pays $ 200 a year for the program, and that he pays about $ 2,000 annually out of his own pocket for many of its costs. Many thousands of dollars worth of goods and services are donated, he said. <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> has his supporters outside the hospital who have rallied around him every time he has run afoul of the hospital administration. State Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Padavan </PERSON>, who acknowledges `` pulling <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>'s fat out of the fire for about 10 years,'' said problems with the program mainly involve <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON>' refusal to accommodate bureaucratic procedures, many required by law. <PERSON> Padavan </PERSON> said he will meet with <PERSON> Weinstock </PERSON> in about two weeks to see if he can work out a compromise that will save the program. `` The bottom line is that -LRB- <PERSON> Stebbins </PERSON> -RRB- gets very good results,'' said <PERSON> Padavan </PERSON>. `` Unfortunately, he listens to the beat of a different drummer.''
</TEXT>
