<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are some highlights of the fiscal 1989 budget approved Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. _ TOTAL SPENDING: The budget envisions $ 1.098 trillion in government spending in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 Total new budget authority, which would stretch past the end of the fiscal year, would be $ 1.232 trillion. The totals are roughly the same as in President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s proposed budget. _ REVENUES: The government would collect $ 964 billion in taxes and other revenues, based on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration estimates That includes $ 14 billion in new taxes already enacted into law for next year, beyond which no new levies are anticipated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year. _ DEFICIT: $ 134 billion in red ink would be added to the national debt, under the goal of $ 136 billion in the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law _ PROGRAMS ELIMINATED: None The president had proposed abolishing several subsidies, including <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, urban mass transit, and some urban and rural development programs. _ DOMESTIC SPENDING INCREASES: Budget increases for AIDS research, airline safety, education, science and space, anti-drug programs, and a pot of $ 100 million for possible boosts in Medicaid and other entitlement programs _ FEDERAL PAY: Federal civilian and military employees would get a 3 percent pay increase <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had requested 4.3 percent for the military and 2 percent for the civil service. _ DEFENSE SPENDING: $ 294 billion, $ 8.6 billion over the current year but short of the amount needed to keep pace with inflation _ FOREIGN AID: $ 16.1 billion
</TEXT>
