<FIRST>r w PM-Honda-Discrimination     03-24 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honda-Discrimination,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks, Women To Receive $6 Million In Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 370 blacks and women who were rejected for jobs at <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will be receiving checks from the company averaging $ 16,200 to settle a discrimination complaint. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, a spokesman for the automaker, stressed that all the workers involved had been hired over the past few years and that the $ 6 million settlement had not been prompted by anyone suing the company for alleged discrimination. `` The matters in this agreement were not raised by any individual at <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Manufacturing,'' <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said Wednesday in a telephone interview from company headquarters in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. `` They were raised by the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>. No one went to the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>.'' Nevertheless, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> reached agreement in a settlement signed by the commission Tuesday and announced by both parties Wednesday. `` I think the very fact that it has been reached in good faith and announced indicates that both sides feel it is a fair, just and reasonable agreement,'' <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said. The settlement `` provides $ 6 million in monetary relief and seniority adjustments to the approximately 370 specifically identified black and female individuals who applied for jobs at <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> between 1983 and 1986,'' <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said in a statement. `` It's a significant, large sum that fits into what we considered a just settlement,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>'s systemic investigations division that had worked on the case since September 1984. In addition to the $ 6 million in back pay, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> also was required to provide jobs for all those people by Feb. 29, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. `` They've all been hired in the last couple of years, and they're still working here,'' <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said. `` We have not been required to hire any additional people as a result of this agreement, and we have not hired anyone any earlier than required by our production needs.'' The settlement was among the larger monetary agreements reached in cases where no lawsuit was involved, but the $ 6 million is dwarfed by some other <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> cases, commission spokeswoman <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said. `` We settled a similar charge in 1983 with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> for $ 42 million,'' Ms. <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said. There was no litigation in that race and sex discrimination case, which involved hundreds of people. In a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> age discrimination case that did involve a lawsuit, the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> settled Feb. 3 for $ 17.2 million shortly before a jury was to return a verdict, she said. The case involved about 100 people. The agreement is the second EEOC-Honda settlement in less than a year. The two parties reached agreement in June 1987 on an age discrimination investigation that provided back pay totaling $ 461,610. That case involved 85 people. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> declined to say whether additional discrimination investigations against <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> were pending. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> also agreed in the new settlement: _ To expand its recruitment area to cover <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> and expand specific recruitment efforts for blacks; _ To change promotion procedures and make a commitment to promote additional black and female production workers; _ To teach <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> managers about <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> employs about 5,900 people at manufacturing plants near <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Anna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said he expects the employees to number about 8,600 by 1991 when the company completes a $ 600 million expansion of an engine plant in <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> and a $ 380 million new auto plant in East Liberty, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
