<FIRST>u i AM-NicaraguaTalks 4thLd-Writethru a0449 03-24 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua Talks, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0449,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Sign 60-Day Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with President Ortega comments,
more details of agreement; background. EDITS to TRIM and conform.
No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leftist Sandinista government and U.S.-supported Contra rebels signed an agreement Wednesday for a 60-day cease-fire to start April 1, both sides announced in a joint communique. It was the first concrete step toward ending a six-year-old war that has killed more than 40,000 people. Both sides scheduled a meeting in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the capital, for April 6 to start negotiations on a definitive truce. `` I think, I hope and I believe that we have made a start, a firm start to end this war that is killing ... sons of the same country, sons of the same mothers,'' said Contra leader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said he hoped a regional peace plan signed last August by the presidents of five Central American nations would `` bury once and for all the military confrontation'' and `` end the hate and strengthen the brotherhood of Nicaraguans.'' `` As president of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, I hope this peace plan becomes a reality,'' said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, who had arrived unexpectedly for the announcement. Within the first 15 days of the 60-day truce, the rebels agreed to move into specified zones in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Delegations from both sides scheduled a meeting in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> on Monday to work out those zones. The issue of the rebels laying down their arms will be discussed at the April 6 talks. The Contras agreed to accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization. That would exclude military aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has been supporting the Contras since the war began in 1982. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Wednesday, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> tried to revive his stalled effort to get <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to resume aid to the Contras, which ended Feb. 29. <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION>, announced the details of the agreement after Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, the Roman Catholic archbishop of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, offered a brief prayer asking that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> be blessed for `` all it has suffered.'' Both men attended the three days of talks as observers and signed the agreement as witnesses. Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the defense minister and head of the Sandinista delegation, signed for the government and <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> signed for the Contras. The Sandinistas agreed to release 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday and said the rest of the 1,500 jailed rebels would be released at a date to be worked out at the April 6 meeting. The 1,800 former National Guardsmen in prison will be released after a final truce agreement is reached. The army was called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> under the late President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>, who was overthrown by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in July 1979. The government also said it would guarantee freedom of expression without restrictions, in accordance with the regional peace plan. Many press liberties were barred for almost six years under a state-of-emergency decree. The Nicaraguan government said it would grant gradual amnesty and allow all political exiles to return to the country without fear of persecution. It agreed to discuss the issue of military service in a national dialogue with the internal opposition. The meeting at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, a town on the Costa Rican border, was the first time the two sides met on Nicaraguan soil. Both Contras and <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON> earlier had agreed to a battlefield truce while the negotiations, which began Monday, took place. A reported Contra breach apparently did not affect the talks. The <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicaragua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said earlier that Contras ambushed an army truck at 2 p.m. Tuesday near <LOCATION> Mulukuku </LOCATION>, in the northern province of <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION>, killing two soldiers. It did not appear affect the negotiations. Contra spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> told reporters earlier that `` there could be isolated'' truce violations, `` but there is a clear will from both sides to respect that decision.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> again held military exercises staged as what officials called a show of force against Nicaraguan aggression. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the withdrawal would be `` gradual.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said they expected it to come next week. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops were sent to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> as the request of the Honduran president, who charged that <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> soldiers had penetrated Honduran territory chasing Contra rebels as part of a major military offensive. The Contras maintain base camps in Honduran territory. At the time, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> said it had forced 2,000 Contras out of its territory. Contra forces number an estimated 10,000 troops. At the start of the talks, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> had said they would only discuss a cease-fire. Two previous rounds of talks ended in stalemate when the government maintained that position while the Contras insisted on broadening discussions to include political reform within <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. But they agreed to discuss political issues with the rebels on Monday after signing an agreement with eight opposition parties in Nicaraguan. The national dialogue as well as the cease-fire are included in the regional peace plan signed by the presidents of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The peace plan seeks to end civil wars in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. It also calls for amnesties, democratic reforms and an end to logistical and strategic support for insurgencies.
