<HEAD>AIDS Study Finds 15 Percent Of Incoming Inmates Test Positive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 15 percent of inmates entering state prison from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> have tested positive for the AIDS virus, officials say. The finding, from anonymous blood tests of 500 inmates over two weeks early this year or late last year, will prompt further anonymous tests, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Slocum </PERSON>, a spokesman for state Health Commissioner Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON>. The blood tests were part of a state program to check more than 100,000 blood samples statewide in an attempt to determine how far acquired immune deficiency syndrome has spread, <PERSON> Slocum </PERSON> said Wednesday. The blood samples are being collected at prisons, where all entering inmates are tested, as well as at family planning clinics, tuberculosis clinics and other health centers, he said. About 70 percent of the prison system's 41,559 inmates come from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, which has the nation's highest concentration of AIDS victims. The inmate test results were disclosed after state Sen. <PERSON> Israel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> and Corrections Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, and called for the prison system to offer AIDS tests to inmates about to be released. <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> told him that tests had indicated between 15 percent and 20 percent of the inmates might be carrying the AIDS virus. The senator said that with about 16,000 inmates being released annually, there could be 2,400 or more who are infected and do n't know it <PERSON> Slocum </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> was making `` a crude extrapolation based on very limited data'' that might not give a clear picture of the prison system as a whole. <PERSON> Slocum </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> must have been basing his projections on what <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> had told him about blood tests from inmates entering the system at Downstate state prison in <LOCATION> Dutchess </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, about 50 miles north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Corrections spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON> said inmates are now tested for the virus only on a doctor's orders for diagnostic purposes. <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON> said that as of the end of last year there had been 597 confirmed cases of AIDS among inmates. Of those, 346 died in prison, 152 had been released and 99 remained in custody. <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON> and Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> have resisted calls for mandatory AIDS testing of inmates and have thus far refused to permit voluntary testing in prisons. <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> said he would propose legislation to require it. <PERSON> Slocum </PERSON> said inmates about to be released are given counseling about AIDS. Some researchers have estimated that up to 50 percent of those testing positive for the virus will develop the deadly disease, which cripples the body's immune system and leaves victims susceptible to infections and cancer. Most cases of AIDS have appeared in homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers. By March 21, 57,024 AIDS cases were reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and 31,836 victims have died.
