<HEAD>Text Of Cease-Fire Agreement Between The Sandinistas And Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is an abridged version of the text of a cease-fire agreement signed Wednesday night by <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> and Contra leaders. It was translated from Spanish by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 An agreement between the constitutional government of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and the Nicaraguan Resistance -LRB- Contras -RRB-: 1. To cease offensive military operations throughout the national territory for a period of 60 days beginning April 1, 1988. During this period will occur negotiations to achieve a definitive cease-fire, and its effective implementation will be carried out jointly with the other commitments contemplated -LRB- in this accord -RRB- for the purpose of ending the war. Both parties agree to meet again at the highest levels April 6 to continue the definitive cease-fire negotiations. 2. During the first 15 days, the resistance forces will locate themselves in zones whose areas, size and modus operandi will be mutually determined through special commissions meeting in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> beginning Monday, March 28, 1988. 3. The Nicaraguan goverment will decree a general amnesty for persons tried and convicted of violating public security law as well as for ex-members of <ORGANIZATION> Somoza </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> imprisoned since July 19, 1979. In the case of the former, the amnesty will be gradual ... During Holy Week, on Palm Sunday, it will begin with the release of the first 100 prisoners. Later, when it has been verified that the forces of the Nicaraguan Resistance have entered the mutually agreed upon zones, 50 percent of the prisoners will be released. The remaining 50 percent will be released at a later date at the moment when the definitive cease-fire is signed ... The release of the prisoners mentioned in the second part of the first paragraph of section three will begin with the signing of the definitive cease-fire depending on prior decision of the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> ... 4. To guarantee food and basic supplies for the irregular forces -LRB- the Contras -RRB-, exclusively humanitarian aid will be solicited and received ... and will be channeled through neutral organizations. 5. The Nicaraguan government will guarantee unrestricted freedom of expression ... 6. When the Nicaraguan Resistance Forces are concentrated in mutually accepted zones, they will send to the national dialogue -LRB- with the internal political opposition -RRB- as many as eight delegates. In the national dialogue, among other topics, issues related to military service will be treated. 7. It is guaranteed that all individuals who for political or any other reasons have left the country can return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and incorporate themselves into the political, economic and social life without any conditions other than those laid down in the laws of the republic. They will not be tried, punished or prosecuted for any political-military activities in which they might have engaged. 8. The consititutional government of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> certifies that the individuals who will have been reintegrated into normal civilian life will be able to participate, under equal conditions and guarantees, in the Central American parliamentry elections and the municipal elections, on the dates scheduled for them, as well as in nationl general elections on the dates which have been determined in the poltical constitution. 9. For the purpose of verifying the compliance with this agreement, a verification commision will be formed with the participation of ... Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo -LRB- <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Roman Catholic leader -RRB-, and the secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION>, his excellency Ambassador <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> In addition, both parties agree to prolong to April 1, 1988, the cessation of offensive militry operations agreed to by both parties on March 21. Signed,
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 For the Nicaraguan Government: Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> <PERSON> Saavedra </PERSON>, minister of defense. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wischnewski </PERSON>, adviser. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichler </PERSON>, adviser.
