<HEAD>U.N. General Assembly Slaps United States For PLO Eviction Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> members to vote against a resolution condemning a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attempt to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observer mission were <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> The non-binding resolution was approved 148-2 on Wednesday, a day after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> filed suit in federal court seeking to close the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> townhouse where the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has its offices. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> vowed to fight the attempted closure, mandated by an anti-terrorism law passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution calls on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to obey the international <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters treaty, which permits foreign missions to operate and calls for arbitration of any dispute with the host country. `` What pride do you have in throwing your guests out?'' shouted <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> envoy <PERSON> Zehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Labib </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON> after the vote. `` Is this the message the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation wants to bring to the world? That guests have no respect, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has no respect, international law has no respect?'' he asked. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government said it will not take any physical steps against the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> until the issue has been settled in court. `` Let me assure you, we will not disregard the summons by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON>. `` But we will tell the court this is a dispute between the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and that the only forum where such a dispute can be settled is found in section 21 of the Headquarters agreement.'' Israeli Ambassador <PERSON> Johanan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bein </PERSON> rose to denounce the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> for, as he put it, seeking the protection of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> charter as it pursues a goal contrary to that charter: the destruction of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, since its inception, has been the principal terrorist organization of our time. It has systematically targeted and murdered innocent civilians,'' said <PERSON> Bein </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which has retained former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Ramsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> as its counsel, has 20 days from the filing of the lawsuit on Tuesday to respond. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> announced it will file a brief in support of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s defense motion. It retained attorney <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Highet </PERSON>, who is also president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION>. Sixty-five American organizations and citizens filed suit on Wednesday in federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> challenging the Anti-Terrorism Act. They included former <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> hostage Rev. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON>, author <PERSON> Studs </PERSON> <PERSON> Terkel </PERSON> and actor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Asner </PERSON>, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Arab-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The lawsuit argues that the law infringes on the constitutional right of Americans to hear all sides of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> controversy by barring the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> from public debate. A March 29 hearing date was set in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. Wednesday's vote was the third time the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> condemned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> legal attempts to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission. The world body also condemned the Anti-Terrorism Law last December after it was passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and rebuked the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on March 2 after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> announced that it would seek to close the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission.
