<HEAD>In-Vitro Babies Gather for Birthday Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24 of March 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Australian company that developed an in-vitro fertilization technique celebrated its second anniversary with a party attended by some of its success stories. Fifty-four babies and toddlers, all from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area, gathered with their families at a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> party Wednesday. All were conceived through the programs of the IVF <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> company, which has fertility clinics at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION> and another in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. `` All we see are positive pregnancy tests in ultrasound scans,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stangel </PERSON>, the program's medical director. `` We never get to see the babies.'' Nurses, doctors and other members of the medical team handed out stuffed koala bears to the children, and a birthday cake was rolled out with 168 blazing candles to represent the number of babies born using the IVF <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> technique. The oldest on hand Wednesday was 16-month-old <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>. The youngest was 5-week-old <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiddo </PERSON>, who slept through the party. The IVF technique involves removing mature eggs from a woman's ovary, fertilizing them with sperm in a petri dish and implanting them in the woman's uterus Multiple births are more common in such pregnancies, with between 15 and 20 percent of IVF <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> births being twins. The procedure costs $ 5,000, usually covered by medical insurance.
