<HEAD>Army Helicopters Patrolling Yerevan to Ensure Order; Calm Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Witnesses in the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> today said <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopters circled the skies to guard against unrest after the government described Armenian claims to an area in neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> as intolerable. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> dissident <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said a correspondent for an unofficial human rights journal had called from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to say that helicopters were patrolling the city, but that there was no widespread disorder reported. <PERSON> Regyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarkisyan </PERSON>, a senior editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <PERSON> Kommunist </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, confirmed in a telephone interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that there were helicopters overhead, but described the city as calm. He said most Armenians were showing patience in awaiting resolution of the contentious national issue. Armenians want the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> because more than three-quarters of the population in the region is Armenian. The annexation appeal was rejected by the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in early February, which triggered massive demonstrations in the region that is smaller than the state of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. The unrest spread to <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> in late February, when hundreds of thousands of Armenians marched through the streets bearing banners linking the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> issue with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s social reforms. The <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> demonstrations subsided after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealed for calm and promised a party review of the annexation question. But the issue touched off rioting in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> on Feb. 28, when at least 32 people were killed in a rampage by ethnic extremists. Soviet officials reported earlier this week that 197 people were injured in the <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> rioting and that more than 400 have been arrested or charged in murders, rapes, looting and other violent acts. Armenian activists claim the casualties were much higher and predominently among Armenians at the hands of enraged Azeris, the dominant population of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sarkisyan </PERSON>, the newspaper editor, said soldiers were deployed around <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to ensure order today, but no outbreaks of unrest had occurred to his knowledge since a government statement on the issue was made public Wednesday night. The demonstrations had subsided until early this week, when reports in the party daily Pravda said the annexation drive had a `` clear anti-socialist spirit.'' Activists in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> said about 7,000 people protested that report, and one of the journalists whose name had been attached to it disavowed it. As recently as March 17, party officials in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> appealed for permission to join the Armenian republic. Activists in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> had called for another show of support for the annexation appeal with demonstrations and strikes beginning Saturday, when a self-appointed committee of activists and officials plans to meet and discuss a future course of action. <PERSON> Sarkisyan </PERSON>, a 32-year-old candidate for membership in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said he supports the proposal for returning <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but does n't expect the matter to be resolved soon. `` I believe that some day it will be united with <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but in the nearest days I do n't expect this to happen. It is a very complicated issue, and I think most people understand that now,'' he said. He said he did not expect a large turnout at the demonstrations or widespread participation in the strikes called for by activists, although Moscow-based dissidents say they've been told thousands plan to show their support for the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> appeal by taking to the streets. The Soviet government on Wednesday rejected as `` intolerable'' the Armenian campaign for annexation, indicating it would not bend to the pressures brought to bear by demonstrations and strikes. The meeting, attended by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> and other senior party officials, was held after carefully orchestrated appeals by subordinate legislative bodies in 13 Soviet republics _ all but <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nominal parliament, considered it `` intolerable when it is attempted to resolve complicated national-territorial issues through pressure on state authorities, in an atmosphere when emotions and passions are whipped up.'' The statement did not categorically deny the appeal, but declared that such issues would be resolved on the basis of economic concerns rather than ethnic differences.
