<HEAD>Defense Grills Ex-Wedtech Exec</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A convicted former <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> executive, who has confessed to stealing $ 1.5 million from the bankrupt defense contractor, admitted he has not had to give back any of his illegal earnings. Under cross examination by the defense at the racketeering trial of Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and six others Wednesday, <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> was asked about his plea bargain with federal prosecutors. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRossa </PERSON> got <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> to admit he sought to avoid a racketeering charge `` which could carry up to 20 years in prison and forfeiting your assets.'' `` And you told your lawyer you did n't want that, right?'' asked <PERSON> LaRossa </PERSON>, `` and that is one of the things they negotiated and got for you, is n't that right?'' `` Yes,'' said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, who later admitted his lawyer also got `` one of the most lenient judges'' to take his guilty plea. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> is among four ex-Wedtech officials who have admitted bribing public officials and other state and federal crimes in a plea bargain for leniency. All are cooperating witnesses for the prosecution. None have yet been sentenced. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> faces a maximum 15 years in prison after pleading guilty to federal charges of bribe conspiracy and mail fraud. He also faces an additional seven years after pleading guilty to state larceny and bribery charges. <PERSON> LaRossa </PERSON> also got <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> to admit that `` not a penny'' of his assets have been seized or forfeited despite his numerous guilty pleas. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, his eldest son, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> and four others are charged with turning <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> defense contractor, into a vehicle for paying millions of dollars in bribes to obtain government no-bid contracts. <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, currently in bankruptcy proceedings, grew from a small machine shop into a $ 100-million-a-year business through a series of no-bid contracts set aside for companies controlled by minority group members. Earlier, <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> claimed attorneys at the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ellenoff </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Plesent </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lehrer </PERSON> were aware of another <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> scheme to make it appear the company was minority controlled in order to qualify for no-bid contracts. He said the lawyers knew the agreement to sell majority control of the stock to <LOCATION> Mariotta </LOCATION>, who is of Hispanic descent, was `` a sham.'' `` So they participated in your fraud, is what you are telling us, right?'' asked <PERSON> LaRossa </PERSON>. `` Yes,'' replied <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> after a short pause. <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION>, a partner in the firm, later issued a statement calling <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>'s testimony `` untrue.'' `` Neither he nor anybody else from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> advised anybody at this firm that Mr. <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> had agreed not to buy shares of stock pursuant to the purchase agreement,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION>, noting that <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> previously testified he and other <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> officials concealed other illegal activities from the law firm and `` if there was such an agreement with Mr. <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON>, it too was concealed.''
