<HEAD>Main Points Of Peace Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Highlights of the cease-fire agreement signed Wednesday night by the Sandinista government and Contra rebels:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ A 60-day cease-fire begins April 1, with a temporary truce that began Monday remaining in effect until then _ Two sides meet in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> April 6 for talks on a permanent truce _ Rebels move into specified zones in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> during the first 15 days of April Zones to be determined through special commissions at meetings beginning in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> on Monday. _ Government will grant gradual amnesty and allow all political exiles to return to the country without fear of persecution It will release 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday. Half the remaining 1,400 jailed rebels are to be released when the rebels are in specified zones, the other half when a permanent truce is in place. _ 1,800 former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> in prison since the 1979 Sandinista revolution to be released after a final truce agreement is signed _ Contras will accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization That excludes military aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. _ Government guarantees freedom of expression without restrictions, in accordance with a regional peace plan signed last August by President <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the presidents of four other Central American countries _ Contras are guaranteed representation in Sandinista talks with internal opposition and participation in the electoral process _ A verification commission will be formed with the assistance of Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Roman Catholic leader, and the secretary general of the Organinization of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Ambassador <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>
