<HEAD>Soviet TV Viewers Learn of Summit Two Hours Into Newscast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Only after Soviet television broadcast a 1 -LCB- - hour speech by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on agriculture and news on a territorial dispute did viewers learn President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will meet their leader in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in May The brief announcement came about 11 p.m. Wednesday, two hours into the news program `` Vremya,'' or Time, which has an estimated audience of 150 million. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, announced the summit in a one-paragraph dispatch issued more than 2 -LCB- hours earlier. `` Vremya'' showed videotape of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meeting Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> outside the White House earlier in the day. An announcer said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> reported that the superpowers settled on the dates of May 29 through June 2 for the meeting, his fourth summit with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and first trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The five-day visit will mark the first trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by an <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president since <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s 1974 summer meeting with <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. `` Vremya'' customarily lasts an hour or less, but its lead item Wednesday was a long speech by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, at the opening of a collective farmers congress. His remarks, which lasted 1 hour and 40 minutes, apparently were broadcast in their entirety. The evening newscast also reported that the Soviet government rejected as `` intolerable'' a campaign by <LOCATION> Armenian </LOCATION> activists to annex <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a predominantly Armenian area of neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. That campaign fueled ethnic strife that led to rioting in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> on Feb. 28. Officials say 32 people died. State-run media had no initial comment about the summit, whose projected centerpiece is the signing of a treaty now being negotiated that would reduce long-range nuclear weapons on both sides by 30 percent to 50 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> gave no details in its dispatch beyond the time and place fixed for the meeting.
