<HEAD>Possible Water Shortage Already Causing Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A critical water shortage east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> threatens to pit suburban homeowners against city dwellers as officials consider the most severe water conservation measures since a 1977 drought. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> engineers said Wednesday that low precipitation since October means river runoffs from snow melt will be 40 percent below normal statewide between April and July _ and even lower if spring rainfall is below average. East Bay Municipal Utility District reservoirs that are half-full now could be one-quarter full by September unless there are major storms during the next two months, officials said. The district board declared a `` water shortage emergency'' Tuesday and warned that as of June 1, they may ration water to their 1.1 million customers for the first time in a decade. The district, however, already is divided over whether to allow more water in warmer, drier areas such as the affluent <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> than in the often foggy and rainy inner-cities should rationing becomes necessary. `` We are the hot weather part of the district. Our needs are different than the cooler parts of the district,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Danville </LOCATION>, a middle-class community about 10 miles east of <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>. Utility board directors from urban <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> argued it would be unfair for the suburbs, with their sprawling lawns and gardens, to receive an extra share. If a voluntary conservation plan approved by the district fails, the agency may impose water restrictions of up to 25 percent for homes and businesses in inland counties like <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> from May through September. During the drought 11 years ago, water customers were charged up to ten times the normal rate for excessive water use. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and coastal counties face possible water shortages next year, but are in better shape than the inland counties because they have more water sources and have received more storms.
