<HEAD>Government Shells Rebel Positions In Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government shelled positions held by guerrillas in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, killing 295 rebels and regaining control of a town, an army statement said. Government troops moving toward rebel-held <PERSON> Nasir </PERSON> town in the southern upper Nile region found the bodies of 250 rebels killed from shelling, according to the Wednesday statement. It said that at the outskirts of <PERSON> Nasir </PERSON>, the soldiers killed 45 other rebels. Two government troops were killed and eight wounded before the army took over full control of the area, it said. It did not say when the operation took place. In other clashes, the statement said soldiers killed 19 rebels in an army attack Saturday on the rebels' Bekwy camp, near <LOCATION> Mundari </LOCATION> town in the <LOCATION> Equatoria </LOCATION> region. In another operation near the border with <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, government and rebel troops fought Saturday and a number of rebels were killed and wounded. The statement had no casualty numbers. The rebels began their insurrection in 1983 and are demanding more autonomy and administrative and economic reforms.
