Rochon </PERSON>, attorney <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Peszko </PERSON> said in an affidavit the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> took advantage of her emotional state after a lovers' quarrel and pressured her to make statements she feared were inaccurate. She said she did not want those statements used against <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>. `` They wanted me to sign statements they prepared, but I refused,'' she said. `` I did not and do not intend to hurt <PERSON> Don </PERSON>, whom I love, and I was misled by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s frequently saying that all they wanted to do was help <PERSON> Don </PERSON> by my saying what they wanted to hear.'' `` I was so tired, hungry and upset, I do not know what I told them or whether what they wrote down is accurate,'' she said. `` They were often suggesting things and leading me in certain directions, and much of what is in the statements they have may well be inaccurate.'' Two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> apparently tried to persuade Ms. <PERSON> Peszko </PERSON> to say that <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> first hit her during an argument March 4 at an apartment they shared in <LOCATION> Pennsauken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, then broke his own nose to convince investigators both had been acting violently, <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Peszko </PERSON> filed simple assault charges against each other in <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, then dropped them. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the questioning followed normal procedures taken any time allegations of impropriety or criminal wrongdoing are leveled against an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> employee.
