<HEAD>Soviets Launch Satellite Bound for Mir Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today launched a satellite with supplies for the Mir space station, whose crew is trying to set a record for time in orbit, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The official news agency said the Progress-35 cargo satellite was carrying food and other supplies, but it did not provide details. Data transmitted from space indicated the satellite was functioning normally, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. It was the second supply mission since cosmonauts <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Musa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON> blasted off Dec. 21 to replace <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Romanenko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON> on the Mir spacecraft. <PERSON> Romanenko </PERSON> had spent 326 days in space and thus holds the record for the longest manned space mission. Soviet space officials say <PERSON> Titov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Manarov </PERSON> will stay aboard the Mir for a year in an effort to break <PERSON> Romanenko </PERSON>'s record. The account of the launch did not say when the link between the Mir and the cargo spacecraft was expected.
