killed; ADDS byline. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `An Israeli ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> warplanes divebombed Palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of this southern port city today for the second day, killing nine people and wounding five, police said. A police spokesman said six <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> fighter-bombers hit the bases six times in 55 minutes with 30 rockets and bombs, starting at 1 p.m. The bases were manned by <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fatah-Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and the Moscow-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, police said. It was the third Israeli strike against Palestinian bases in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in a week and the fifth this year. Forty-seven people have been killed and 6 wounded in Israeli air strikes on guerrilla bases in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year. An Israeli army statement identified the targets as buildings used by the guerrillas to store weapons and equipment. The statement said <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> pilots returned safely and reported accurate hits on the targets. Smoke and dust engulfed the villages of <LOCATION> Bekasta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Majdelyoun </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Saliyeh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abra </PERSON> after the raids, and ambulances raced to the scene. All but <PERSON> Abra </PERSON> had been bombed by Israeli jets Wednesday. A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity under standing regulations, said guerrillas sealed off the villages on the southern and eastern edges of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The villages were once populated by Christians. But they fled in April 1985 when leftist Moslem militiamen drove right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> irregulars, allied with the Israelis, out of the region. Police said seven people were killed and 15 wounded when 12 Israeli jet fighters raided six <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> guerrilla bases in the <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION> region in Wednesday's attack. Five were manned by <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s fighters and one by the Moscow-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the Liberation of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. The front, led by <PERSON> Nayef </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawatmeh </PERSON>, is part of <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>, whose real name is <PERSON> Sabri </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Banna </PERSON>, broke away from the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in 1974 to found his own group. He tops the list of terrorists wanted by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Western European countries. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s group, in a statement issued after Wednesday's raids, threatened to `` severely strike back against the Zionist enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the right time and place.
