<HEAD>Attempt To Give Sight To Girl Born Without Visible Eyes Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Optic surgeons built eye sockets and an eyelid for a 7-year-old girl born with her eyes completely covered by skin, but they say they have failed in a long-shot attempt to give her sight. `` The surgery was unsuccessful,'' Dr. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON>, an ophthalmologist who operated on <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON> <PERSON> Erdogan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, said late Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Surgeons hoped to implant a cornea in the little girl's right eye Wednesday, but after three incisions guided by an ultrasonic scan they found no iris or pupil, <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> said. The eye appeared to be all sclera, or white. <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON>'s left eye is so deformed it is beyond sight, he said. <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> said doctors might make one more attempt to find the right part of the eye using magnetic resonance imaging but that it is highly unlikely the girl will ever see even partially. `` We are a long, long way from the needed technology,'' said a corneal transplant specialist, Dr. <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugar </PERSON>. `` I do n't think I'll see it in my lifetime. The man who brought <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON> to this country for surgery two years ago, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> restaurateur <PERSON> Ismet </PERSON> <PERSON> Deletioglu </PERSON>, said he accepted <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON>'s verdict but could n't stop hoping. `` The hope has to be there,'' <PERSON> Deletioglu </PERSON> said. `` It's part of humanity, you know.'' <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON> suffers from a rare condition callyed cryptophthalmos, or hidden eye, in which the eyes are below the skin, <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> said. She has a nose and a mouth `` and that's it for her face,'' he said. <PERSON> Cryptopthalmos </PERSON> in both eyes is so rare that there are only three or four accounts of it in medical literature, <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> said. Removal of the skin that had covered the girl's eyes revealed that the retina of her right eye could detect light, he said. But even if Wednesday's implant had succeeded, he said, she would have been able to make out only vague forms. <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> had built sockets for both eyes and used tissue from the girl's mouth to construct a right eyelid. He is repeating the procedure for the left eye. <PERSON> Putterman </PERSON> said cosmetic surgery probably will continue to make <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON>'s face appear more normal and that an artificial eye will be inserted in her right eye socket in the next three or four weeks. He said he plans to remove the badly scarred left eye and replace it with an artificial one in about five months. <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Guldane </PERSON> <PERSON> Erdogan </PERSON>, 44, was silent for a few moments when she was told that her daughter probably would never see. Then, through an interpreter, she thanked the doctors. `` I'm so thankful that these two gentlemen took the courage to even try,'' she said. She also said she was glad that the cosmetic surgery would eventually make her daughter's appearance normal. <PERSON> Deletioglu </PERSON>, 44, who is from <LOCATION> Antioch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, read of the girl's plight in a Turkish newspaper He has housed <PERSON> Dilek </PERSON> and her mother in his home for the past two years and has held fund-raising events for the medical expenses.
