<HEAD>Other Airlines Reluctant to Follow Northwest Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after the 5th to update with passenger
reaction. A longer version moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' bold step in banning smoking on most of its flights is not expected to be followed soon by other major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines, industry analysts say. Northwest, the nation's fifth-largest airline, announced Wednesday it will prohibit smoking on all its domestic flights except those to and from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and on some foreign routes. The ban makes <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, Minn.-based Northwest the first major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline to mandate a smoke-free environment, surpassing federal regulations that on April 23 outlaw smoking on all domestic flights less than two hours. `` It does run the risk of some loss of business,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cammisa </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indicators </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based newsletter. `` I guess they -LRB- Northwest officials -RRB- really stuck their neck out.'' Wall Street seemed unimpressed by <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s move. The airline's stock closed on Wall Street at $ 45.75 a share, down 12 -LCB- cents from Tuesday. Several smokers waiting to depart on <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> flights Wednesday from Minneapolis-St. <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> said they do n't object to the smoking `` It's probably a good idea,'' said <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> real estate broker. `` I can get by without smoking.'' Some Northwest flight attendants who are smokers said the new policy might help them quit smoking, the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The new policy, `` Northwest Clears the Air,'' takes effect April 23 with the new federal regulations. It applies to flights within the contiguous 48 states and to and from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five hours, the airline said. About 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic flights and about 20 percent of all domestic flights last more than the two-hour federal duration. Northwest flights to and from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and overseas will offer smoking sections because those flights `` carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the issue,'' the airline said. A.B. <PERSON> Magary </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s marketing chief, said the ban accedes to passenger and employee requests. The policy is not risk-free, he said, but `` we believe more nonsmokers will switch to Northwest than smokers will leave.'' That was n't the case for <ORGANIZATION> Muse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, a regional carrier that failed to establish itself as the only non-smoking airline in 1985. Its research showed the policy diverted as many as 35 percent of potential fliers. Surveys showed customers find `` price, convenience and service more important than non-smoking'' in an airline, <PERSON> Muse </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Shari </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said at the time. The policy ended when <PERSON> Muse </PERSON> was sold to <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. No 2 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is watching <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s lead but, `` We have no plans to follow that move,'' said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>. Its surveys indicate a significant number of people want to smoke on planes. American and other big airlines contacted Wednesday said their no-smoking policies would meet the new federal law, which mandates civil fines of as much as $ 1,000 for smoking, $ 2,000 for tampering with lavatory smoke alarms. `` We are ready to implement our no-smoking policy ... in line with the federal law,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline. Airline analyst <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said he did not expect other carriers to match Northwest's policy. `` It's a gutsy move and most airlines do n't make gutsy moves,'' he said. `` It could alienate some people.'' The alienated include <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smoker </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION>, which on April 22 offers smoking flights and the same fares as <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> to such cities as <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Using leased planes from Las Vegas-based <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the club hopes to serve 63 cities from five hubs with 60 planes in