<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> says he intends to continue working within the Southern Baptist Convention, though he says his group is taking on the appearance of a separate denomination. The alliance represents a moderate group within the 14.7 million-member convention, which is dominated by fundamentalists. `` We are not a fringe group, we are not an avant garde faction of the Southern Baptist Convention,'' the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomason </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` The great majority of <ORGANIZATION> SBA </ORGANIZATION> members are denominational loyalists.'' <PERSON> Thomason </PERSON> said, however, that the alliance may appear to be headed toward denominational status because of its publishing activities and its discussions concerning the possible need for a new seminary or divinity school. `` Whenever we take specific steps like that, we are acting independently of the institutions of the Southern Baptist Convention and that gives the appearance of independence, but it is not our desire to forge a permanent split with the <ORGANIZATION> SBC </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Thomason </PERSON> said. Nevertheless, he said, the alliance has to be an `` advocate for groups and causes we feel are disenfranchised. ... If this means acting independently of the existing agencies and channels of <ORGANIZATION> SBC </ORGANIZATION> life, then for the time being, we are willing to do that.'' <PERSON> Thomason </PERSON> is pastor of the 561-member <ORGANIZATION> Northminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, the third church to join the alliance after its formation in February 1987. The alliance has grown from 22 founders to more than 25,000 members, including 40 churches in 11 states and more than 2,000 individual members. The fundamentalists have gained control of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy by electing their presidential candidates for the past nine years. The president has broad appointive powers, naming hundreds of people annually to various Baptist institutions, including the boards of the six seminaries and the five major operating agencies of the denomination. While both groups generally are conservative, they disagree on key issues, including biblical inerrancy and ordination of women. Fundamentalists, who oppose ordination of women, say the Bible is without factual error, not only in matters of faith but also in science and history. Moderates maintain there is room for interpretation, especially in non-religious areas.
