<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia-Reform     03-24 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia-Reform,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calls For End To State Interference In Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s ruling body today called for the first time for a `` radical'' reduction of state interference in the economy as a way to solve the nation's worst economic and political crisis in history. The lengthy statement from the Presidency also urged new regulations on joint ventures with foreign partners, more private business in the nation's economy and changes in the tax policy which would stimulate economic growth. The unusual statement, carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency, marked the first time <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s ruling body had called for changes in the running of the economy of this nonaligned communist nation. The statement appeared designed to give guidance to the government for tackling the economic and political problems expected to arise when a wage and price freeze imposed last November expires in May. There have been increasing calls for the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to relinquish control of the economy. With the current annual inflation rate of around 170 percent and a foreign debt exceeding $ 20 billion, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is faced with its worst economic and political crisis in history. The Presidency demanded that `` a program of measures and activities'' be made by the federal government to strengthen market forces and called for `` radical reduction of state regulations ... in order to overcome the dominating role of the politics over the economy.'' The statement said the implementation of this program is of `` prime interest'' and should be monitored by the presidencies of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics and two autonomous provinces. Critics of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s unique system of self-management, whereby factories, farms and offices are nominally run by the workers, say the system is hampered by interference from the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The government last year imposed a series of price and wage freezes in an attempt to control inflation and stabilize sinking living standards. However, 1987 saw a record 1,500 strikes as workers protested low wages. The government of Yugoslav premier <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON> has recently faced sharp criticism even in the state-run press for its economic policies. There have been repeated calls for the premier and his cabinet to step down _ something that has never happened in communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. The statement by the Presidency said such calls `` represent an unacceptable political campaign'' that hurts the government's domestic and foreign activities The Presidency demanded, without specifying, an `` urgent'' passing of new joint venture laws. According to current law provisions, foreign companies can own no more than 51 percent shares in their joint ventures with Yugoslav enterprises and have no right to manage the companies. The current law attracted little investment by foreign partners since the unstable economic situation in this <LOCATION> Balkan </LOCATION> country frightens off possible investors. According to a draft of a new joint venture law, which has been waiting for a long time to be passed by the parliament, foreign partners may be allowed to hold up to 99.9 percent of shares in joint ventures and the right to manage such companies. The ruling body also called for `` substantial'' reduction of administrative curbs on private business and changes in the income tax policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
