back to Zeebrugge and restores dropped word `the' in 2nd graf.
Picks up 3rd graf, `Coast guards ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FELIXSTOWE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A blaze erupted today in the engine room of a British ferry shortly after it left the Belgian port of <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> with 348 people aboard, but tugs towed the ship to port and no one was injured. P and O, owners of the 18,000-ton Nordic, said the two-hour fire wrecked the ferry's power system. Coast guards called a major alert after the Nordic, on a six-hour English Channel crossing from <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> to the English port of <LOCATION> Felixstowe </LOCATION>, reported fire aboard 30 minutes before it had been due to dock. The Nordic, surrounded by a flotilla of tugs and life boats, was stranded for several hours five miles off the coast before tugs got the vessel under tow and brought it to <LOCATION> Felixstowe </LOCATION>, in southeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` Three life boats were dispatched and a helicopter was put on standby,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman at the nearby port of <LOCATION> Harwich </LOCATION>. A P and O spokesman said the fire was put out by automatic firefighting equipment and the crew. The fire was confined to the engine room. `` Everyone on board was very calm and there was no danger to anyone,'' said P and O spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamming </PERSON>. Last March, another P and O ferry, the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, capsized after leaving <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION>, killing 193 people.
