hormal </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dojaila </PERSON>, three of the Kurdish towns captured last week. The Iranians claimed the poison gas attacks killed 5,000 Kurdish civilians and injured 5,000. Western reporters flown to <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION> by the Iranians this week reported seeing hundreds of dead civilians there with no obvious wounds. The correspondents reported that many people had died of asphyxiation in their homes. Survivors were seen suffering from burns consistent with poison gas. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charled </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> charged in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Wednesday that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> had used chemical weapons, banned under a 1925 <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement, and urged the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to mount an international protest. Declaring the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> action `` a particularly grave violation'' of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> protocol, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said there was evidence the Iraqis had also fired chemical shells into <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The Iranian news agency said earlier this week that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes had dropped chemical bombs, believed to contain mustard or phosgene gas, on eight towns in northwest <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, causing scores of civilian casualties.
