<SECOND>PM-Washington-AIDS,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Health Officials Start To Implement New AIDS
Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Landmark AIDS legislation described by sponsors as a model for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has gone into effect in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, aimed at protecting the disease's victims and stopping its spread. The measure, funded by an appropriation of more than $ 5 million, will tackle the killer disease through education, testing, counseling, civil rights protection, and prosecution of people who intentionally spread acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Gov. <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> signed the bill Wednesday and it took effect immediately. `` We must recognize that AIDS is only beginning to take its toll on human life and in costs to our society. By acting now, especially with a strong public education program, we hope to save many of our citizens' lives,'' the governor said. Key provisions of the measure are: _ A 10-year prison sentence for intentionally spreading the AIDS virus _ Mandatory AIDS education in grades 5 through 12 and availability in colleges and trade schools Mandatory AIDS training for all public school personnel, emergency services crews and health professionals. _ Mandatory testing and counseling for all convicted of sex crimes, prostitution or intravenous drug use Violent prison inmates would be tested at the request of the prison and approval of the local health officer. _ A procedure is created for confronting, examining, detaining and confining infected individuals who refuse to modify their behavior so they do n't pose a threat to others Due process protections are provided. _ Regional service networks will be set up in the six most populous counties by Oct. 1 _ Those who carry the AIDS virus, or who are perceived to have it, will be protected from discrimination <PERSON> Jule </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said he already had followed the bill's directive and created a new Office on AIDS. He said he began to confer with county health officials on setting up regional AIDS service centers across <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Those centers will do the mandatory and voluntary AIDS testing, counseling, public education, and outreach to `` street kids'' and other target populations. They also will plan and coordinate services to AIDS patients, develop volunteer networks and notify partners of infected people. `` This bill will make an enormous difference,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Holm </PERSON> of the Privacy Lobby and the gay rights <ORGANIZATION> Dorian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've taken a step toward making it safe to know your antibody status, whether you're at risk, and safe to seek public health -LRB- services -RRB-. `` In this state we've finally said civil rights and public health go hand-in-hand.'' `` The important thing is that we did get a statewide policy on AIDS,'' said state Sen. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Deccio </PERSON>, co-sponsor of the measure. `` It's the first omnibus bill of its kind in the country, so I guess it's the best available.''
</TEXT>
