<HEAD>Train Collision Kills 12, Injures At Least 40</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with 12 reported killed, 40 injured. ADDS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 quotes from survivors and report that one train ran signal. ADDS byline. No pickup.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two passenger trains collided head-on today in a <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> suburb, killing 12 people and injuring more than 40, the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said. It was <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s fourth fatal train accident in three months. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s second official news agency, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said only seven were dead, including five Japanese, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> soldier and a railway worker. It said 40 to 50 people were hospitalized. The Japanese Embassy confirmed that a 193-member Japanese high school tour group was on one of the trains. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, which arranged the tour, reported two Japanese killed and 29 injured. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said 11 Japanese were killed. The cause of the collision in the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Fengbang </LOCATION> was not immediately clear, said <PERSON> Fu </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenghao </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>'s public relations division. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION>, however, said one of the trains ignored a stop signal when it left the <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> station. The crash occurred at about 2 p.m. when northbound train No. 311, leaving <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Hangzhou </LOCATION>, collided with southbound train No. 208 arriving from <LOCATION> Changsha </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fu </PERSON> said. No. 311's first two cars and the luggage car of No. 208 were knocked off the tracks, he said. Television footage by Japanese camera crews broadcast in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> showed the luggage car resting on one end of the other train's engine The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the two first-class passenger cars behind the No. 311 engine were crushed together by the force of the collision. The news service said <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> had rain and heavy fog today but did not say if this was believed to have contributed to the accident. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said the No. 311 train `` rolled out of the <LOCATION> Kuangxiang </LOCATION> station, ignoring the prohibiting signal, and collided with the No. 208 train that was entering the station.'' <PERSON> Kengo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobayashi </PERSON> of the Japanese Embassy in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> said two people from a high school in southern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kochi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prefecture </LOCATION> were among the dead, and 29 others were injured. Fu confirmed that Japanese students were among the dead and injured but said the number was not yet determined. `` We have n't heard any information about other nationalities,'' he added. `` We were playing cards and suddenly there was a loud bang, and things went flying all over the floor,'' said an unidentified male student interviewed in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` There was a huge bump, and then one of our teachers came into the car and told us to get out,'' said another student. `` We broke the windows and climbed out.'' The train tracks were blocked seven hours after the accident, <PERSON> Fu </PERSON> said. He said soldiers, police and medical workers took the dead and injured to nearby hospitals and that investigators were at the scene trying to determine the cause. <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> Vice Mayor <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ju </PERSON> also went to the scene, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. In January, three separate train accidents killed 141 people. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s minister of railways resigned this month to take responsibility for those accidents. This year's train accidents, together with a plane crash outside Chungking in January that killed all 108 people aboard, have prompted severe calls by the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government for greater attention to safety.
