<HEAD>Joined Barges Slam Into Pensacola Fishing Pier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pair of barges loaded with a flammable liquid today slammed into the end of the Pensacola Fishing Pier, a former bridge billed as the world's longest fishing pier. The barges were wedged into the L-shaped vehicular turnaround at the tip of the pier, formerly a highway bridge across <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> connecting <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> and Gulf Breeze. The bridge was divided into two sections, each becoming fishing piers. The <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> pier is 1.5 miles long. `` The wind caught it and blew him into the bridge -LRB- pier -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Grey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jewett </PERSON>, risk manager for <LOCATION> Escambia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which owns the pier. `` It destroyed the end of the pier, a turnaround. It's not reparable.'' The pier is only 75 feet away from the new <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>. Officials said they planned to block traffic on the new, four-lane bridge while attempts were made to pull the barges, which were tied together along with a towboat, from the pier. The barges were loaded with benzine, a colorless, flammable liquid used as a motor fuel and solvent in dry cleaning. None of the benzine apparently leaked, but officials were worried about possible fire or explosion. `` It's not the benzine, it's the vapor,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, an engineering technician for the county. `` It would go with one spark.'' One of the barges was pushed into the shipping channel, blocking navigation traffic.
</TEXT>
