<FIRST>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0425 03-24 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pell Predicts Committee Action Early Next Week On INF</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new to update with vote; Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
I
would hope.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations Committee today rejected a move by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> to require new intelligence studies of what <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> says are Soviet missiles unaccounted for by the U.S.-Soviet treaty on medium-range atomic weapons. The committee voted 15-2 against <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' amendment to the treaty which would have required President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to certify the accuracy of the Soviet claims that there are 650 SS-20 missiles. The declared weapons will have to be destroyed after the treaty takes effect. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, argued that up to 300 more SS-20s are `` hidden,'' and he cited <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reports which he said support his claim. But Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash., said, `` I do n't believe President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would have signed this treaty'' if he believed the Soviets had successfully hidden a large force of SS-20 missiles The vote was the latest decision in which the panel decided by large bipartisan majorities to reject attempts by <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.D. </LOCATION>, another conservative critic, to change the treaty. Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the committee, said the panel was headed toward overwhelming approval of the pact. `` I would hope _ and I think _ that we will continue to show strong bipartisan support,'' said <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> after the panel voted by lopsided margins Wednesday to reject amendments by <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> had originally proposed 36 amendments and <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> offered three more, despite appeals from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to approve the treaty without changes. After it became apparent he had few votes on his side, <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said he planned to drop most of his amendments. <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> announced that the committee will finish voting on all amendments by Tuesday afternoon next week and will then decide on the treaty itself. When the measure finally reaches the floor, overwhelming approval is expected with no more than 10 to 12 of the 100 senators expected to vote against it. Ratification requires a two-thirds vote. The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, signed Dec. 8 by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, requires the elimination within three years of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. It includes on-site inspection among its strict verification provisions. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> dropped many of his amendments after he came under fire from fellow Republicans, some of whom claimed he was trying to delay a final <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote until after the next summit meeting between <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. That meeting has now been set for May 29-June 2 in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the White House announced Wednesday. Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., said: `` We're just in a delay, stall situation which I find disagreeable ... If you do n't have the votes and just try to overload it with amendments, that is n't fair. Meantime, <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> and other Democrats tried to work out some type of compromise between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> over the chief remaining hurdle, a dispute about the legal power to interpret treaties. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said in a floor speech that it will be necessary to add a reservation or an understanding which spells out the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` This matter is not going to be resolved, in my judgment, by any exchange of letters, because a future administration can say, ` we do n't agree with that interpretation at all,''' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asserts that the executive branch can unilaterally change the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intepretation of a treaty, a view disputed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The fight arises from a difference in how to interpret the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. As it worked through the treaty, the panel:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Voted down, 12-3, a <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> proposal to change the treaty and allow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to deploy non-nuclear cruise missiles The treaty bans all cruise missiles, whether equipped with nuclear or conventional warheads, because there is no effective way to verify which warheads are on the missile. _ Voted down, 12-2, a Helms amendment which would include the Soviets' Scud B missile as one of the banned weapons The missile is not now banned because it has a shorter range than 300 miles, but <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> claimed Scud B missiles sold by the Soviets to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been fired at ranges which would fall within the INF ranges. _ Rejected, 13-2, a <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> plan that would prohibit either side from testing missiles in the INF range _ Defeated, 15-2, a Pressler amendment which would block the treaty from taking effect until <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> certifies that there is parity in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact forces The Soviets have a large advantage in some categories of non-nuclear weapons and <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> and other treaty critics say the elimination of medium-range atomic missiles will take away a major <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> deterrent to a Soviet attack.
