<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A philosophy student who outraged people with his threat to publicly kill a puppy to demonstrate the brutality of war said today the whole thing was a prank. `` It was a prankish threat to kill one mythical animal,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Read </PERSON>. But he said his threat to burn to death a 10-week-old dog at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin-Madison </ORGANIZATION> campus Monday served its purpose in getting attention. The threat drew protest calls to the <ORGANIZATION> Dane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and local radio stations. `` People panicked to save the life of one mythical puppy while thousands -LRB- of people -RRB- were dying'' elsewhere, Read said. The student said he opposed cruelty to animals and never intended to carry out his threat, despite earlier claims he was serious that prompted humane society officials and university police to investigate. Police said Wednesday they would consider seeking an injunction against Read's plan to kill the dog. Earlier, <PERSON> Read </PERSON> said burning the puppy would be `` an exhibition of what suffering and cruelty is all about,'' he said. `` I think our attitudes about war and human suffering are complacency and numbness. This is one thing that will combat that numbness.'' Read, 26, is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Nihilist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, a campus organization the university said does not have its official recognition. He said the group, organized two years ago, has about 12 active members who advocate nihilism, a belief that existing social institutions need destroying to make room for a new order. The group announced the puppy-burning plan Tuesday. Radio stations, humane societies and police said Wednesday they were flooded with telephone calls. Read said he anticipated the reaction. `` I'm quite pleased,'' he said. `` I'm the most reviled character in town.'' He said he had <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in mind when he conceived of the idea of burning the dog to demonstrate suffering. He said people living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> lead sheltered, comfortable lives and avoid thinking about the horrors occurring in other nations. `` I want them to get down and wallow in the filth, which is truth,'' he said. Shock is the best method of making people aware of ugliness, he said, calling peaceful protest a waste of time. His organization has distributed obscene posters on the campus, including one portraying <PERSON> Adolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> pointing a gun and reading: `` I love you.''
