 The federal judge in the Iran-Contra case indicated Thursday that trial of a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lawsuit that accuses former government officials of collaborating with Colombian drug dealers may be postponed. The civil lawsuit is set for trial June 26. The 29 defendants in the case include <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, two businessmen who have been charged with conpiracy and theft in the Iran-Contra case. <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, were arraigned before Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. During the proceedings, <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, told <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> about a potential conflict in scheduling between the Iran-Contra case and the case in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s federal court. `` It will not go forward,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. `` A criminal case takes precedence. This case has got to take priority.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said: `` I've canceled every case I have and I've canceled my vacation. <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> are accused of helping <PERSON> North </PERSON> and <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, two former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides, secretly sell weapons to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and divert the profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lawsuit was filed by <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Honey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON>, two freelance reporters based in <LOCAT