<FIRST>r i AM-Locusts     03-24 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Locusts,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countries Coordinate War Against `Tidal Wave' of Locusts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Billions of locusts are moving across <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in the worst plague since 1954, blotting out the sun and settling on the land like a black, ravenous carpet to strip it clean of vegetation. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> have put aside political differences to fight the locusts, with help from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said Thursday it may not be possible to save the food supply. As many as 250,000 of the insects settle on each acre whent the horde alights. They devour 100,000 tons of crops and other vegetation at each stop, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency based in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. Wind currents pushed the insects into northeastern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> from their breeding grounds, The <ORGANIZATION> FAO </ORGANIZATION> said. They fly in waves of up to 50 million per square kilometer over 400 square kilometers, which means as many as 20 billion covering an area of 160 square miles. `` We are facing a very dangerous situation, which may affect <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s food production for years to come,'' said <PERSON> Lukas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brader </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> FAO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Locust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are not optimistic that the situation can be effectively controlled.'' He said the current infestation is worse than the 1950s plague, which lasted more than 10 years. Breeding has been aided by abundant rains and heat in the area, <PERSON> Brader </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Saouma </PERSON>, director-general of the <ORGANIZATION> FAO </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement: `` We are in a state of general alert. Swift and decisive action is needed to avoid a major regional food crisis later this year.'' <PERSON> Brader </PERSON> said $ 30 million had been donated by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and others to finance the spraying of pesticide on infested areas. He said at least $ 150 million will be needed to fight the plague, which he said may peak in late summmer. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> has sprayed more than 494,000 acres of land and <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> has been treating about 62,000 acres a day. No figures were available for <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>. Published reports in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> say more than 40 aircraft have been provided by <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to spray crop and pasture land threatened by locusts. Spraying has been hampered by inadequate and outdated pesticide and equipment, the presence of nomads in some infested regions and the difficulty of detecting locusts in areas of sand, rock and scrubland, officials said. No estimate was available of the total damage to crops. Specialists say the locusts originated near the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, invading <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> and then swarming through the Sahel countries below the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> before moving north `` in a tidal wave.'' <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> also are threatened. To coordinate logistics the Algerian agriculture minister, <PERSON> Noureddine </PERSON> <PERSON> Keddara </PERSON>, visited <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> on Wednesday and <PERSON> Driss </PERSON> <PERSON> Basri </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s interior and information minister, was in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. Until about two weeks ago, a long-standing territorial dispute over the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> had stymied the exchange of information between <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> about the common danger.
