<SECOND>AM-Mideast Study,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Urge Next Administration To Put Mideast Peace on Front
Burner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A panel of <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> experts on Thursday urged the next <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration to place <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks high on its foreign policy agenda and to include negotiators approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` A prolonged impasse in the peace process could endanger <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> national interests,'' the panel of 19 academicians and former <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials said in a report issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsored the study. `` We would like to see a steady, high-level commitment of American resources to the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> peace process,'' the report said. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who served as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from 1978 to 1985, said the panel `` has a very strong sense that it's going to take a protracted investment by senior levels to achieve even partial success.'' Speaking at a news conference, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace plan offered in 1982 by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lacked sufficient preparation, while the one currently being proposed by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> may be the victim of bad timing. Any future <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan must be presented at a time when both Arabs and Israelis are ready for peace talks, he said. The Palestinians may be too `` eupohoric'' over their success in the 3 -LCB- - month uprising against the Israeli occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> to be ready for the compromises each side must make in negotiations, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Quandt </PERSON>, a senior research fellow at Brookings and the project's coordinator, said the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace issue has not been high on the U.S.-Soviet agenda so far. It should be explored in that framework further to see if it can yield some solutions, he added. The report's authors agreed that <LOCATION> Israeli-Arab </LOCATION> peace talks should be conducted within an international framework, although such a forum would not be empowered to impose solutions. The <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plan contains a similar proviso. `` Palestinians should be represented in any negotiations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by spokesmen of their own choosing, whether in a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation or in some other configuration,'' the report said. The <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plan envisions Palestinian representation as part of a <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> delegation in peace talks. `` The tone, though, seems to be that <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> can choose the Palestinians,'' <PERSON> Quandt </PERSON> said. `` Palestinians are unlikely to come forward to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> without having the implicit endorsement of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>,'' the report said. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refuse to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> directly. <PERSON> Quandt </PERSON> said panel members differed on whether the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> should be included in negotiations, and also could not agree on whether Palestinians should be given an independent state. Some argued that inclusion of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and the establishment of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state would be `` irritants'' that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would reject, he said. The experts believe substantial preparation is needed to get the parties `` to be willing to make hard choices'' before bringing them to the negotiating table, <PERSON> Quandt </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and other officials have conducted preparatory talks with Israeli and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> leaders since January, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is pressing for negotiations to begin by May 1.
