<HEAD>Drivers Start Returning Cash Spilled from Armored Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of honest citizens showed up at police stations across the city Thursday to return thousands of dollars in cash that fell out of an armored truck, police said. `` We have a lot of very honest people here,'' said Inspector <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>. On Wednesday night, however, money-grabbing chaos erupted on <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s Gardiner Expressway after the rear door of the armored truck flew open and spewed a blizzard of bills that blew onto windshields and covered the highway. Drivers stopped their cars in the middle of the road in the rush for cash, and traffic was tied up for miles. A guard in the <ORGANIZATION> Loomis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> truck eventually had to pull his gun to halt the free-for-all. Two bags that each contained $ 75,000 _ worth about $ 60,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> _ were scooped up by drivers who threw the booty into their cars and sped away and have not been returned, <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said. A third bag holding the same amount broke open, spreading the cash in the air. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said auditors were counting up how much was returned. Under Canadian law, the cash belongs to <PERSON> Loomis </PERSON> and not whoever finds it. One cab driver was charged with theft for grabbing some of the money.
