<HEAD>Detroit's Black Mayor Tones Down Criticism of Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, long at political odds with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, is striking a more conciliatory tone toward the Democratic presidential candidate this year. `` I'd be a fool not to recognize the massive contribution <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> has made to the electoral process, and putting some color _ finally _ in the rainbow,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. `` Obviously ... that's not enough to win, but it's an important beginning.'' Young still argues that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s candidacy represents wasted votes, political polarization and help for the Republicans. But he also credits <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> for reaching some whites with his more mainstream Democratic candidacy this year, and expressing surprise at his degree of support from blacks. Young is supporting <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s chief rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s statewide caucuses Saturday. He says his is not so much an endorsement as a statement of whom he supports _ a distinction <PERSON> Young </PERSON> says means the political organization that has served him for 15 years as mayor of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> is free to do as it wishes. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> has a tremendous emotional appeal to the black community in this city,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in an interview Wednesday in his office with several out-of-town reporters. `` I think that the chief objective ... is to win the White House.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is airing radio ads featuring Young's support, targeted at black audiences in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. He is bidding to win delegates in the city's two largely black congressional districts, the 1st and 13th, which requires winning at least 15 percent of the vote in those areas. Young maintained that he has `` truly'' released his organization to go as it pleases and says he's not asked key supporters to report back on whether they are siding with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or another candidate. Some politicians are n't so sure, however. State House Speaker <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ypsilanti </LOCATION>, backing <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said he understood <PERSON> Young </PERSON> was `` coming down hard'' on his supporters to produce for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, particularly in those key congressional districts. In announcing his support for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a week and a half ago, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said, `` Anybody who respects my opinion will do likewise.'' And <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s top political aide, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, said last week that <PERSON> Young </PERSON> would ask his staff members to inform him of their actions in the presidential campaign. <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who has seen his city's optimism decline with the fall in federal urban aid under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, said a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> victory in November is his paramount concern and his reason for supporting the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, he said, has the best chance to win. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, he said, `` ca n't win.'' Young finds fault with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s lack of government experience, but said no black candidate could be elected this year or in the immediate future because of white resistance. `` I think it's rooted in race _ I do n't have to look anywhere else,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. Even if he should win <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s caucuses, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would achieve at best a plurality of the Democratic vote, not a majority. `` The great majority of the black votes will follow <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> off to one side, whereas the great majority of the white vote will be split among the other candidates,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. `` That is the essense of polarization. `` I think the overall thrust of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign might very well be to help the Republicans,'' he said. Young endorsed <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in 1984 over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and he has remained apart from <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> this year even as some other black leaders who were cool toward <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> four years ago have been won over. While there may be political risks for himself, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said he thinks voters' attitudes toward him wo n't be affected. `` I'm trying to preserve the unity _ I do not want to be responsible for creating any disunity in the black community,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said.
