<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> today called the Nicaraguan cease-fire agreement `` an important step forward'' and said there is `` no excuse'' for any additional Soviet bloc weapons deliveries to the Sandinista government. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> reacted with cautious optimism to the agreement while <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> hailed it as `` a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn country.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to immediately approve additional humanitarian aid to the Contra rebels while they negotiate terms for a definitive cease-fire with the Sandinista government. He said the agreement would not have been possible without years of sacrifice by the rebels. `` Their strength and perseverance have created this opportunity for peace and freedom,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` We consider this agreement to be an important step forward.'' Under questioning, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he feels the agreement may be a ploy on the part of the Sandinistas to disarm the Contras. He said that if the Sandinistas do n't carry out their promises under the agreement, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would have to reevaluate its policies. Both the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> promised to seek quick action on a humanitarian aid package for the Contra rebels. `` We're glad that it occurred,'' the <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, when asked whether the administration was embracing the plan. `` There is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and I'm trying to balance those two off,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` We're beginning the process. We need to watch it. We've seen processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. `` This seems like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be hopeful. But I do not want to play down the skepticism side of it either because we are skeptical.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said he would meet Monday with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republicans and representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to begin drafting a bill to send food, clothing, shelter and medicine to the rebels before Easter. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, too, hopes an aid package can be passed `` on a bipartisan basis'' before the recess. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the precise form of the aid package remained to be worked out, but that it would have to conform to the cease-fire agreement announced Wednesday night in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, after three days of talks. That agreement calls for `` exclusively humanitarian aid'' to be channeled through a neutral, international relief organization. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> refused to speculate on whether there would be <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> demands to include in the package some standby procedure for authorizing new military aid for the rebels should the peace process become derailed. Republicans, contending Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> can not be trusted to fulfill his promises without such a threat, have insisted on such a provision in previous debate on the issue. `` I think it would be counterproductive to talk about it,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told reporters. `` We do n't want to rekindle the war.'' He said he envisioned quick action on `` some minimal something that both sides -LRB- Democrats and Republicans -RRB- can wholeheartedly embrace.'' `` For heaven's sake, if the Nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, then surely Republicans and Democrats can agree,'' he said. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> began discussing ideas for an aid package on Wednesday in conversations with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., and White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> But he said no deals had been made. `` The cease-fire talks have made it possible, by entering into an entirely new era, to bury our hatchets in the same trenches where they're burying their machetes in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. The aid bill likely would be similar to a $ 30 million package rejected by a narrow margin on March 3, although <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., said it was unclear whether the dollar amount would be the same The rebels' last <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid expired on Feb. 29. Earlier, interviewed on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> television, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is wracked by poverty and needs to begin diverting its slender resources to educate, feed, and clothe its people. `` Both sides were war-weary but were ready if they could to find an accommodation to guarantee the integration back into their society of these people who have been estranged from it,'' he said. Problems remain, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, but `` there is a disposition on both parts to enter into a more peaceful society and a more democratic society in which freedom of the press and of expression will be guaranteed and the rights of those who formerly made war against that government will be fully protected.'' `` Those of us in our <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are anxious to do whatever we can to encourage the fulfilment of the democratization of that country,'' he said. Meanwhile, Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Feighan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said three officials from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> were leaving for <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> today to track the disposition of small arms, ammunition, jeeps and other materials that were brought to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops sent last week to respond to a Sandinista incursion. `` My concern is that the deployment of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops and weapons to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> could in fact be another diversion of arms to the Contras,'' said <PERSON> Feighan </PERSON>, who requested the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> investigation.
