<SECOND>PM-US-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,450</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Vogel quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 West German opposition leader <PERSON> Hans-Jochen </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> today praised President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s arms-control advances and said the atmosphere had greatly improved since their last meeting five years ago. <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters after a 20-minute meeting with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at the White House that he and the president had discussed arms control, the economy and human rights. `` We had a very friendly and constructive conversation with the president,'' he said. `` I ... said, remembering five years back, we are very impressed especially by the INF -LRB- Intermediate Nuclear Forces -RRB- treaty, by the cooperation which developed with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said he told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> he hoped he and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also would be able to agree soon on reducing long-range nuclear forces. He said the president `` seemed to be satisfied about the work, what has been done in the last two or three days. They worked very hard, they worked very -LRB- thoroughly -RRB- through the details.'' He was referring to a visit by Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, who has been meeting with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week. `` Remembering my visit five years ago, it is a remarkable change. It was a relaxed conversation. There are still some points of different views and different opinions, but there are points which we join and which we agree -LRB- on -RRB-.'' `` In'83 we were in the middle of the argument about the deployment of Pershing II and there have been some other fields of different opi