<HEAD>Anti-smoking Bill Introduced in Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill introduced in Parliament on Thursday would allow Britons to demand to be segregated from smokers at work. The measure lacks the support of the Conservative government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and was given little chance of passage, but it reflected a growing anti-smoking campaign. `` Smoking must now be treated like any other industrial heath hazard,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Foulkes </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, who introduced the Health and Safety at Work Bill in the House of Commons. He said there was `` overwhelming'' public support to ban smoking at work except in designated areas. The bill would not require companies to set up non-smoking areas in offices, but it would forbid them from firing or disciplining any worker who refused to work alongside a smoker. Smokers are rarely segregated in British restaurants and other public places, although smoking has been banned in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> subways and the number of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> cars where smoking is permitted has been reduced from 25 percent to 20 percent. The Independent newspaper said a private survey of 1,000 companies found that almost half had either a voluntary or formal agreement on no-smoking areas. In a report released Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smoking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> said passive smoking, or non-smokers' exposure to smoke, may cause several hundred lung cancer deaths a year. It said passive smoking increases the risk of lung cancer by 10 to 30 percent. In government reaction to the report, <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> minister <PERSON> Edwina </PERSON> <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> said, `` The government accepts the thrust of the report, which reflects established policies of voluntary arrangements.'' The state-funded <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> launched a $ 457,000 advertising campaign Thursday with full-page advertisements in major newspapers urging non-smokers to stand up for their rights. The ads say, `` If you're a non-smoker who works with smokers, you probably suffer in silence. Yet everybody has the right to a healthy working environment.''
