<HEAD>National Program of Cholesterol Testing Set for May 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of hospitals will offer free blood cholesterol testing May 4 in the first national screening for the fatty substance that is a leading contributor to heart disease and strokes. The program, organized by the Voluntary Hospitals of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, was outlined Thursday at a news confrence. Officials said they were announcing the national program well in advance to give people plenty of time to learn where they can go for testing. About 400 not-for-profit hospitals that are members of the association have agreed to participate, and organizers estimate 400,000 Americans will get the test. While most will do the test free, a few will charge $ 3. A public service television spot promoting the program, called `` CountDown <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' will begin airing next week. It includes a toll-free telephone number _ 800-634-9541 _ for people to call weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. -LRB- EST -RRB- to find out which hospitals in their areas will offer the testing. `` We want every American adult to know his or her cholesterol level and if it's high, do something about it,'' said Dr. <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, professor of medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION> and Surgeons and a member of the staff at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Presbyterian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. Blood cholesterol levels below 200 milligrams are associated with a low level of coronary heart disease. Levels over 240 milligrams double the risk. Twenty percent to 25 percent of Americans have cholesterol levels in this range, the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> says. <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, who heads the hospital organization's screening effort, said one valuable bit of information researchers hope to gain is insight into which people respond. `` We really do n't know who will come to be screened,'' he said. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnwine </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Voluntary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, acknowledged that the estimate that 400,000 people will be tested is little more than a guess. `` If 4 million show up, it may be the third or fourth day before we can get to everyone, but we will try to serve them,'' <PERSON> Arnwine </PERSON> said. The screening program was developed in association with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION>, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> to assure uniformity from city to city.
