Conference of Mayors. SUBS 8th graf, `Alexander would ...,' to add
surrender date and Alexander to be sent to medium-security federal
prison.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Mayor <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was sentenced to 10 years in prison today for extorting $ 1.5 million in kickbacks from businessmen during his years as the city's top elected official. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, 60, pleaded guilty Jan. 6 to charges of racketeering, conspiracy to obstruct a government investigation and tax evasion in connection with what federal prosecutors called one of the biggest public corruption cases ever uncovered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. At his sentencing, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, who once served as president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, also was ordered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McAvoy </PERSON> to pay $ 100,000 in restitution to the City of <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> in lieu of a $ 100,000 fine recommended by federal prosecutors. `` I've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said before sentence was pronounced. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said his demise occurred when an effort to build a political war chest was `` allowed to grow into a cancer.'' Before <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s 10-minute speech to the judge, his attorney, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Boreanaz </PERSON>, made an impassioned plea for leniency. <PERSON> Boreanaz </PERSON> rebutted statements made by prosecutors that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> had not fully cooperated with the government's efforts to identify and turn over his assets. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> would be eligible for parole after serving a third of his sentence. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Scullin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> must surrender by April 14 and would serve his sentence at a medium-security federal prison that has yet to be determined. The former mayor faced nearly seven centuries in prison after being named in a 40-count federal grand jury indictment that accused him of 65 separate acts of extortion. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> earlier surrendered to the government more than $ 1.4 million in assets the government has linked with the extortion-kickback scheme he admitted running during his four terms as <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive between 1970 and 1986. The former mayor was to have been sentenced on March 10 but questions by the government about whether <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> had withheld any assets caused <PERSON> McAvoy </PERSON> to delay sentencing until today. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> met with government attorneys for more than 20 hours and submitted to at least two polygraph tests during the past two weeks. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> was indicted July 16, 1986, by a special grand jury investigating public corruption in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> initially denied the charges, but the the overwhelming and highly detailed evidence, including testimony from <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s pick-up men and other co-conspirators, caused him to seek a plea bargain.
