<HEAD>Religious Activists Appeal For Ouster of Patriarch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six religious activists seeking greater religious freedom in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> called Thursday for a new Russian Orthodox Church leader to replace the ailing Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>. The activists, led by the Rev. <PERSON> Gleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON>, sent an appeal to the 78-year-old <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> asking that he step down because senility and poor health make him incapable of fulfilling his duties. The group, who met with reporters, said they have noted some encouraging changes in official tolerance of religion and believe it is time for a change at the top. They also sent their appeal to the church Synod that meets next week, <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said, in the event <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> does not choose to leave. The Synod is responsible for making church appointments. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> acknowledged that it would be unprecedented for the church hierarchy, which is subordinate to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government, to oust the church leader against his will. `` On the shoulders of the church leader rests the heavy weight of spiritual and historical responsibilities,'' the appeal reads. `` You, Your Supreme Holiness, are not up to bearing this weight.'' <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>'s office recieved the appeal, church chancery director <PERSON> Irina </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsyganova </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I ca n't say whether it will be discussed by the Synod or not,'' she said. `` I rather doubt it as the Synod's business agenda has been determined for a long time.'' She said <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>, who is widely reported to be in poor health, was not available for comment. `` I doubt he will leave of his own accord,'' <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said. `` But we sent the letter with the hope that those around him who assist him in carrying out church duties will be able to influence him.'' Religious activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Bessmertny </PERSON> said <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> rarely appears in public and his crucial role as liaison between the Russian Orthodox church and the government is filled by an unknown cast of supporters. `` He has been seen by foreign visitors to ask his deacons where he should go and what he should do,'' <PERSON> Bessmertny </PERSON> said. `` He has to be led around like a very old man.'' <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> and fellow priest <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Gainov </PERSON> said they were not appealing for any particular church official to succeed <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON>, who was imprisoned for six years because of religious activism in the 1970s that authorities considered to be dissident behavior, was restored to the ministry last year after 20 years of exclusion. More than 200 churches have been reopened recently for the observance of the 1,000 th anniversary of the coming of Christianity to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> Whether that trend will continue after the formal observances in June is not clear, the activists said. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> also said church activists have found it easier now to receive religious materials from foreign affiliates, including Bibles and magazines that once were deemed anti-Soviet. The appeal to <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> also noted the positive trends, although it criticized the dearth of monasteries, seminaries, churches and priests. `` Paradoxically, it is not the church but the government that is taking the initiative in drawing believers into the social mainstream,'' the appeal to <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> said. `` Society has survived a spiritual crisis and the Russian Orthodox Church can play a significant role in its recovery.'' While there have been encouraging signs of change, none of the laws instituted in 1929 to break the church's influence with the peasantry has been repealed, <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> said. Those laws prohibit charitable work by churches as well as religious education, arguing that such work violates the principle of separation of church from state. The religious activists said 54,174 churches were open at the time of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, and now there are about 7,000. The number of Russian Orthodox priests has declined on a similar scale.
