<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Del., thin and full of good cheer, left the hospital Thursday saying `` I feel good'' despite a setback that has delayed a second operation on an artery in his head `` I've asked you all to come today because I've decided to announce that I am re-entering the race for president,'' the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> senator joked to reporters waiting outside <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> where he had spent the last 11 days. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> dropped out of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> campaign last Sept. 23. He had undergone surgery to correct an aneurysm in an artery that supplies blood to the brain on Feb. 12 and was scheduled to have a second artery similarly repaired early in April. But on March 13 he re-entered the hospital for a suspected blood clot in his leg. It turned out the clot had lodged in <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s lungs, where it dissipated and was absorbed by the body To prevent more such clots, which occur frequently after medical intrusion into the artery, doctors last Friday implanted a tiny, umbrella-like filter in a large vein that conveys blood to the right atrium of the heart. The arterial surgery now probably will be the end of May. `` They do n't want me working, but do want me walking,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said. `` The most disturbing part of the intermediate step I've had is the delay of the second operation for a month or so. The second operation should be a relatively easy piece of cake.'' He said he wo n't be back in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> until he recovers from that surgery. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> looked thin and said he is now down to a 34 inch waist. `` I probably do n't look very hot, but I feel fine,'' he said. He declined to talk politics, saying that `` if you are out of the loop more than a couple of days in this race, you are really out of the loop.'' And of the race, he said: `` I think it would be much better if I were still in it.'' The senator wore a baseball cap with the letter `` D.'' He had worn the same cap on his first hospital release and said he'd gotten mail asking why he was a <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> fan `` This is a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> baseball hat,'' he said. `` I hope this will put an end to the most serious problem I've confronted in the last six weeks. And, added the senator, who is nearly bald, `` the reason for the hat is that they kind of took some of my hair off and I did n't have a lot of hair to begin with.''
