<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> has handled hazardous waste materials in a sloppy and potentially dangerous way, the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulation </ORGANIZATION> reports. The DER told the company it would be fined $ 174,399 unless it can show that the violations are not as serious as the state agency contends. `` It looks as if they -LRB- Disney supervisors -RRB- do not have good control of their hazardous waste,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gionis </PERSON>, enforcement section manager for <ORGANIZATION> DER </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> district. A two-day inspection of the 43-square-mile tourist attraction in January found nine violations, seven classified as major. The DER wants the company to test for possible groundwater contamination in two of the nine areas inspected. Disney spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreyer </PERSON> said Thursday the company had `` always tried to comply with DER regulations, and we will make whatever improvements are deemed necessary.'' The inspection was conducted after the DER received an anonymous complaint. Much of the criticism involved a maintenance yard in the Epcot Center section, where toxic paints, solvents, pesticides and other chemicals are stored. The DER described the maintenance yard as an `` uncontrolled, unsupervised, unmanaged and unposted site.'' State inspectors said they found steel drums stored indiscriminately and filled with waste and unknown chemicals. Many drums were unlabeled, rusty, open or lying on their sides, with their contents running off a concrete slab where they could contaminate groundwater. There were no precautions to guard against fires, explosions or spills, the inspectors said. Such dangers, plus a possible contamination of groundwater, `` could threaten human health or the environment,'' according to the report. Inspectors found only one employee that had received training in handling the materials, and the DER asked that <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> set up a training course on hazardous-waste management. The park passed similar inspections in 1984 and 1985. No inspections were made in 1986 or 1987. In 1981 and 1983, it was cited for minor violations. Disney officials have 10 days to meet with the regulatory agency to set up a plan for correcting violations and negotiate penalties. It could take months or even years to make some of the changes requested, <PERSON> Gionis </PERSON> said.
