<HEAD>Fifth Crack House Set Ablaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire officials on Thursday investigated a blaze at an abandoned house used by crack cocaine addicts, the fifth such fire which officials said may be the work of anti-drug vigilantes. `` I do n't have a gut feeling whether it's the same person,'' said fire Lt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. `` It could be one person or four different people. I do know that whoever it is is not serving the community.'' As in the other cases, police found little evidence to aid their investigation of the fire which broke out Tuesday in a working-class neighborhood, according to fire spokeswoman <PERSON> Cristy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickman </PERSON>. Investigators believe the blaze may be related to fires that gutted three houses March 17 and another house two weeks ago near <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>, a suburb of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Hickman </PERSON> said Thursday. One firefighter suffered a heart attack during one of the fires last week and is still hospitalized, she said. Six other firefighters and one civilian have also sustained minor injuries. The latest fire was confined to a small area of a vacant two-story house and appeared to involve a flammable liquid. No injuries were reported. Although not in the same neighborhoods, the fires have all involved vacant buildings that were hangouts for vagrants and crack users, and all involved a flammable liquid, fire officials said. `` People seem to know where they are,'' <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> said of the crack houses. `` Police know where they are, too. They try their best but as soon as they close someone down, someone else moves in.'' <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> is concerned that more people could get hurt, or even killed, and that copycats may prompt more fires, especially since avenging arsonists are gaining prominence around the country. Two men who recently set fire to a crack house in their <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> neighborhood were featured on thr