<FIRST>r a AM-MeteoriteAnalysis     03-24 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meteorite Analysis,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Analysis May Be Revolutionized By Method Tested On
Meteorites</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have used lasers to identify organic chemicals in meteorites, and say the new technique may revolutionize analysis of certain pollutants, oil-bearing rocks and other chemicals. The procedure is much faster than standard chemical tests, requires only a tiny sample and does n't destroy the material, said a statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION>. The technique was developed by chemist <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zare </PERSON> and colleagues at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Its use to identify organic compounds in six meteorites was outlined in a study, published in Friday's issue of the journal Science, by <PERSON> Zare </PERSON> and his colleagues at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> and by <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bada </PERSON>, a marine chemist at <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION>, which is part of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, located in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jolla </LOCATION>. `` The problem with standard chemical techniques for doing organic analyses of meteorites and other rare materials is that they are laborious, destroy the sample and require one to 10 grams of the material to be tested,'' <PERSON> Bada </PERSON> said. A gram is about one-30th of an ounce. `` Our method can reduce the analysis time from a month or more to just a few minutes, and we need only one millionth of a gram to do the test,'' he said. `` In addition, the technique does not require the use of solvents that can contaminate the sample, and is non-destructive to the sample.'' The new method may be used widely to analyze meteorites, cosmic dust, environmental pollutants and oil-bearing sediments, the <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> statement said, adding that the technique `` may revolutionize the way certain chemical compounds are analyzed.'' The study found wide variation in the content and relative amounts of organic substances known as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, or PAHs, in the meteorites that were tested. Scientists believe meteorites are remnants of the young solar system, and analyzing their contents may provide clues as to why life arose on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> but not elsewhere in the solar system. The researchers placed tiny amounts of meteorite samples on a Teflon-coated probe, then inserted the probe into a vacuum chamber. Each sample was hit with a 10-millionth-of-a-second burst from a carbon dioxide laser, which heated the samples to about 1,000 degrees Fahrenheit. The heat released molecules of the samples into the vacuum chamber, where they then were struck by an ultraviolet laser beam. That electrically charged the organic compunds in the meteorites so the chemicals could be separated and identified by matching their masses with masses of known substances.
</TEXT>
