<HEAD>Gulf Sources Report Apparent Iranian Attack; Ship Captain Denies
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with captain saying ship not hit
by Iranians, ADDS identity of ship. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The
executives...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A supertanker put out a distress signal in the southern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> today and appeared to be the victim of an Iranian attack, but the captain denied it had been hit, maritime salvage executives said. The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the 267,589-ton Friendship L reported in a radio contact that its engine room was on fire. The captain did not say what caused the fire. In a later contact, the captain denied his vessel had been the target of an Iranian raid. The Iranians have launched nine attacks on neutral shipping in the southern gulf since Friday. The ship attacks are part of the so-called tanker war, an offshoot of the 7 -LCB- - year-old Iraq-Iran conflict About 500 ships have been attacked by both sides, according to the London-basec <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>, which monitors worldwide navigation. Salvage tugboats rushed to the Friendship L, which gave its location between the southern gulf emirates of <LOCATION> Ajman </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ras </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Khaimah </PERSON>, close to the <ORGANIZATION> Strait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hormuz </ORGANIZATION>, said the executives. The strait is the sole entry to the gulf. There was no immediate word on the extent of damage. The executives said the vessel in distress was in almost the same area where a Cypriot freighter, the Odysseas H, was attacked by two Iranian gunboats on Wednesday. Eight other attacks on freighters and tankers of different nationalities were hit by the Iranians in the past week, all in the same vicinity. Salvage tugboats were still struggling to contain a blaze in the crew quarters of the Odysseas H, 24 hours after the attack. No casualties were reported on board. Strong winds were whipping up the flames and impeding the salvage operation, the executives said. Reports indicated the vessel was being steered in the direction of Omani waters for shelter where the salvage operation would be completed.
