<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS style on Du Pont. Note style incorrect in keyword
line.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plans to end production of chlorofluorocarbon compounds, the most potent destroyers of the earth's ozone shield, the company said today. But the company's chairman, in a letter to several senators, did not say when the production would cease. <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON> told Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, R-Vt., that the company decided on `` an orderly transition to the total phaseout'' of the compounds following a report last week that they probably were responsible for a 2.3 percent decline in the thickness of the earth's ozone shield from 1969 to 1986 The ozone shield, generally 15 to 25 miles high, blocks harmful ultraviolet rays from the sun that can cause skin cancer. The compounds are used for refrigeration fluids, plastic foam blowing agents and cleaning solvents, and aerosol propellants outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ended aerosol use in 1978, which caused worldwide production to dip, but production resumed its upward climb in the early 1980s. In 1985, the nations of the world produced 2.28 billion pounds, about 30 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The report, by a panel of scientists assembled by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, constitutes `` important new information'' justifying <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>'s reversal of its previous position that an end to <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production was not justified, <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON> said. The letter was made available by <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>'s office. Similar letters were given to Sens. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>. `` It's a very responsible <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> must now press their industry colleagues'' for similar action, <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON> said in a statement. The three senators challenged <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> on Feb. 22 to live up to the company's mid-1970s pledge that it would end production of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds if a threat to health were demonstrated. <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON> wrote back on March 4 repeating the pledge but adding, `` At the moment, scientific evidence does not point to the need for dramatic <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> emission reductions.'' Today's letter said <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> was encouraging other producers to `` join us in pursuit of this goal,'' and would `` urge all nations to treat this new scientific information seriously.''
