<HEAD>U.S. Now Has More Than Doubled Security Personnel in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> moved 250 more military police into <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> this week, more than doubling the number of security personnal assigned to the strife-torn country since March 14, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Pentagon spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the latest deployments brought to 670 the total of extra security personnel airlifted to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, `` and that's it.'' `` At least, that's it for the interim,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` This was part of a general, supplemental deployment of military policemen, and that supplemental deployment has now come to an end. So I do n't expect it to go any higher. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, which is headquartered in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, had about 600 security personnel assigned to it before the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stepped up its campaign earlier this month to oust strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The new deployments thus more than double the number of security personnel in the country. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, asked why the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> thought it needed to airlift additional personnel when there were already 10,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen in the country, said the concern was having sufficient `` people who are trained as military policemen. ... They're trained to handle riot control and all sorts of things. And this has to do with the physical security of our military installations, housing areas and the like due to civil unrest and potential for civil unrest in the country.'' Capt. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> LaLuntas </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said Thursday the latest group of approximately 250 MPs had been drawn from the <ORGANIZATION> 503rd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battalion </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. Earlier this week, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced it had dispatched about 212 soldiers from that unit to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, at the time bringing the `` security augmentation'' to 420. Although no moves have been reported against American servicemen or their dependents, defense officials are said to be concerned that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> might lash back at the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by attacking or sabotaging facilities there.
