<HEAD>Prosecution Rests on Second Count Against Mecham</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with prosecution resting on
second charge, picking up 7th graf, `Asked by ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prosecution rested its case today in the second of three impeachment allegations against Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> being tried before the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. After the prosecution called its last witness, presiding officer <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> denied a defense motion to dismiss the charge that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> misused $ 80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. The defense called as its first witness <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagadorn </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> vice president who said he had loaned money to members of the <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> family for decades and none had ever defaulted. Earlier today, Sen. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> said the allegation that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> loaned public money to his auto dealership is serious and could have been the subject of a criminal investigation. West spoke as former state Attorney General <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> LaSota </PERSON> testified that he believed the $ 80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund was illegal `` Your testimony, if accurate, is either a nuclear explosion or at least devastating,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. A criminal charge that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> misused public money would be a class 4 felony carrying a penalty of up to $ 150,000 and five years in prison, the senator said. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Colville </PERSON>, a developer and mortgage banker, testified today that there were three previous liens totaling $ 3.7 million on the <LOCATION> Mecham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> property, in addition to the deed of trust for the $ 80,000 loan. The property was appraised at $ 3.35 million a year earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Colville </ORGANIZATION> ssid. In the event of a foreclosure, the previous liens would have to be paid off before the $ 80,000 loan could be repaid, he said. However, defense lawyer <PERSON> Jerris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> questioned whether the appraisal was low as part of a general industry practice. Asked by prosecutor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckstein </PERSON> if he would have made the $ 80,000 loan to <LOCATION> Mecham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> based on that information, <PERSON> Colville </PERSON> said, `` I would have to answer no.'' The prosecution has contended the auto dealership needed the money badly, and that the $ 80,000 loan was not simply a business deal intended to benefit the protocol fund as the defense said. <PERSON> LaSota </PERSON>, who was attorney general under the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> governor's predecessor, Democratic Gov <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, testified Wednesday that the loan violated several state laws. Earlier, an accountant who examined the records of the dealership said it would have been overdrawn at its bank had <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> not borrowed the $ 80,000 on July 17, also contradicting the governor's previous testimony. `` Unless these funds had been paid from the protocol fund, <LOCATION> Mecham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> would have had an overdraft the following Wednesday in excess of $ 60,000,'' said accountant <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorensen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s lawyers contend the protocol fund, created with fund-raising proceeds from the governor's inauguration, is private money and the loan was merely a good business deal intended to provide a higher interest rate to the fund. The prosecution, however, says the protocol fund is state money since it is intended for the purchase of ceremonial state gifts and other means of promoting <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s image. In January, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> testified before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> impeachment committee that his dealership did not need the money to pay its bills. However, <PERSON> Sorensen </PERSON> said his analysis of the dealership's records showed that it paid <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> $ 81,309 owed for six cars on the day it received the $ 80,000 from the protocol fund. Defense attorney <PERSON> Jerris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> suggested the dealership could have had other assets which could have been converted to cash, but <PERSON> Sorsensen </PERSON> said he had found no such assets. <PERSON> LaSota </PERSON> testified that he had examined the way the protocol fund was set up and the applicable state laws and concluded it was public money, even though it was not officially turned over to the state treasury. The $ 80,000 loan violated state laws against loaning state money, failing to keep the fund intact until it was properly disbursed and transferring money when not authorized by law, <PERSON> LaSota </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governor to be impeached in six decades, also has been charged with obstructing the investigation of an alleged threat and concealing a $ 350,000 campaign loan. The first-term governor also faces an April 21 criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan and a May 17 recall election. A two-thirds vote of the 30-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is required to convict <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> in the impeachment trial.
