<HEAD>Dispute Flares Over Postal Cuts, Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration clashed Thursday over who is at fault for recent cuts in postal services and what future would be best for the embattled mail system. Federal budget director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> sought to place blame for the postal cutbacks on one another _ with both sides calling the accounting process `` smoke and mirrors.'' The Postal Service curtailed some window hours and halted Sunday collections and some sorting after the federal budget reconciliation bill required it to reduce spending without increasing revenues. Postage rate hikes slated for April 3, boosting a first-class stamp price to a quarter, are unrelated to the dispute. In addition to finding fault with one another for the agency's budget crisis, disagreements flared over proposals by <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and others to `` privatize'' the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> by making it a private firm and opening mail delivery to business competition <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said that plan would cut costs, imoprove efficiency and probably result in better service and lower costs for consumers. But <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on postal operations that, in his opinion, all <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> wants is to destroy the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Privatization is only political jargon for `` profitization,'' <PERSON> Biller </PERSON> said, terming the idea `` the tale of an idiot, full of sound and fury, signifying nothing.'' Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said he believes that instead of improving service, turning postal services over to private hands could well destroy the service. The prime bone of contention, however, was delegating blame for the federal budget process last December that ended with the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> being directed to cut spending as part of overall reductions in the federal budget. The Office of Management and Budget is not seeking to manage the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and did not impose the cuts, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> told the congressmen. He said that the decision was made by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> themselves. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he only agreed that the cuts would reduce the federal deficit, because the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is counted in the federal budget. `` I did not advocate it,'' he said. `` Who did?'' asked <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, contending that the `` heavy hand'' of the budget office was felt at the session where decisions were made, because that office refused to approve other proposals that had been made instead of the postal cuts. <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, both said they are now supporting a bill to take the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> out of the federal budget so it would not become involved in this type of problem in the future. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, an independent federal agency, was not counted in the overall federal budget until 1985. `` I think the Postal Service should be placed off budget,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who has long opposed the idea, told a momentarily stunned audience. Then, he added: `` By making it part of the private sector.'' `` You take a very crass and insensitive approach to things,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said, stating that he is concerned that privatization would lead to a loss of federal jobs and to the opportunities for minorities that the post office has long provided. `` Why do you think that would end if it were transferred to the private sector?'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> shot back, `` You want to break it up and sell it off and those people who are buying do not necessarily believe in affirmative action. Your administration does not believe in affirmative action.''
