 Teen-age AIDS victim <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> will attend `` Ryan White Day'' activities this week in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, and also will visit Council Bluffs, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, 16, and his mother, <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, will visit Father <PERSON> Flannigan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Boys </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> on Friday in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> before speaking at a forum on AIDS and AIDS education, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. In Council Bluffs, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> will visit a children's home. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s efforts to attend school even though he carries the AIDS virus divided the community of <LOCATION> Kokomo </LOCATION>. In spite of national health officials' assurances, school officials and worried parents were n't convinced that other children would be safe sitting next to <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, who contracted AIDS through infected treatments for hemophilia. The fight eventually drove <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> and his family from <LOCATION> Kokomo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cicero </LOCATION>.
