<HEAD>Officials Say Security Improvements Will be Attractive as Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to delete reference to $350,000 estimate,
which source now says in error</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says the White House will be a safer place and have a better-looking sidewalk in front of it when a million-dollar-plus construction project is completed in July. The project, a compromise between security requirements of the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and aesthetic standards of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, has gone through several changes since it was first proposed. The first proposal was a 42-inch-high concrete wall, with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s existing ornamental iron fence on top of it, according to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON>, administative officer of the arts panel. `` It would have made the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> look even more like a fortress,'' <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON> said. The commission must approve design changes affecting federal buildings and momuments in the central are of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. After the terrorist attack on the Marine barracks in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1983, which killed 241 American servicemen, low concrete walls called jersey barriers were erected around the White House and many other public buildings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` That was always regarded as a temporary measure,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON>. After the wall was rejected, there were discussions between the arts commission and the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, with advice from the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, resulting in the present plan. It consists of 274 bollards, or thick cement and aggregate posts, each 38 inches high, placed four feet apart and joined by chains, along 832 feet of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> sidewalk. `` We, of course, would have hoped that they would be farther apart,'' <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON> said of the bollards. `` They're actually awfully close together.'' The Secret Service, however, determined that this spacing was the most effective way to stop a vehicle of a certain size, going at a certain speed, from crashing into the White House. `` We certainly agree that the first order of business would be the protection of the president at any cost, and if the aesthetic element has to be compromised, so be it, sad as that may be,'' said <PERSON> Atherton </PERSON>. `` I think the Secret Service feels that we now have a system that will do the job physically and at the same time we hope will be more acceptable to look at. It certainly, I think, will be more acceptable than the original scheme.'' <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which is in charge of the White House grounds, dealt separately with the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the commission. `` You play one against the other,'' he said. `` If you work hard at it, you can usually find a solution.'' The first phase of the project is scheduled for completion in July. <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON> said the security work will cost $ 670,000 and the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is spending an additional $ 365,000 to replace the sidewalk with a more decorative granite walk with trees and tree boxes. A second phase is expected to be completed about the end of July, but <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON> said the cost has not been determined.
</TEXT>
