<HEAD>Chief, Officers In Small Town Feud Other Over Incident Involving
Girl</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT Horne to Hensley.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>APOPKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The police department in this <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> community is in turmoil over allegations by lower-ranking officers that a captain took a teen-age girl along on a confidential stakeout and kissed her against her will. The alleged incident last month resulted in the demotion of Capt. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON>, 42, to lieutenant and has led to a state investigation and several internal investigations. <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> had supervised an investigation last month on similar charges against the officer who relayed the latest allegations. The chief of the 45-member force is suspicious. `` I have n't been able to prove that it's a setup yet,'' Chief <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` Sooner or later, I'll find out. Some officers may be running scared right now.'' The officers who investigated the captain and had pictures taken of him and the 16-year-old girl deny any setup. <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> declined comment. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said the problems began when <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> asked the girl, who lives with a roommate and works as a waitress, to join him on a stakeout at the local high school on Feb. 26. The girl said this week she was interested in police work but was `` half afraid'' of <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> because of his flirtatious comment that it would be cold and she might have to keep him warm. She said she told officer <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> about the invitation. <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> passed the girl's comment on to Sgt. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Ujcic </PERSON>, who then notified his lieutenant, <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>. Last month, <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> was the target of an internal investigation, supervised by <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON>, into accusations that he was dating another teen-ager. <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ujcic </PERSON> enlisted former police officer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Granttham </PERSON> to take pictures when <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> picked up the girl at the restaurant. Also in the parking lot was a carload of the girl's friends, whom she had asked to follow her. <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> realized he was being followed and gave them the slip, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` What disturbed me the most is that this was supposedly a confidential mission'' to catch suspected burglars, <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> said. `` This special operation was no longer a special operation. Everybody and their brother knew about it.'' The chief is n't happy that his nightshift officers started investigating a fellow officer on their own. He is investigating <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>'s role. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>'s family has befriended the teen-ager, and she has complained to the state attorney's office that two officers pressured her to withdraw her complaint about <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON>. The chief is angry that the officers got civilians involved _ <PERSON> Granttham </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Horne </PERSON> family. `` I do n't need their help,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` I can take care of my own shop. I will take them to court if they slander my name.'' State Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, `` We're looking at a matter involving the police up there. We're taking statements from witnesses.''
