<HEAD>Honduras Protests Alleged Sandinista Incursion, Nicaragua Denies
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Honduran protest. Pick up
3rd graf pvs: ``It's a...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-Nicaragua Talks, Bjt
^By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> said today it filed a protest with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> over an alleged incursion by Sandinista soldiers in the same spot where Nicaraguan troops fought Contra rebels last week. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> denied its troops crossed the border. A Foreign Ministry communique said a total of nearly 460 <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> crossed the border late Tuesday. An `` energetic protest'' was filed with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> over the incident, it said. It said 300 heavily armed <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> entered about 8 p.m. Tuesday in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andres </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bocay </LOCATION> region in <LOCATION> Olancho </LOCATION> province, where Sandinistas chased Contras back across the border last week. It is about 150 miles east of this capital city. At the same time, 50 Nicaraguan soldiers entered at the village of <LOCATION> Pico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Espanol </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> province. The village is about two miles from the Nicaraguan border. The statement, read to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone, did not say if there were any confrontations in the areas or whether the troops were still believed to be inside the country. In <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the Nicaraguan capital, a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman was asked about the report. `` That's negative,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. A Honduran military official had reported the new incursion on Wednesday. `` We do n't know the purpose of this new entry and violation of our country, but the situation is being studied by the high command,'' the official said. `` It's a matter of small armed groups of Sandinistas. Because of that, the state of alert continues for all combat units of the armed forces,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The location was given as the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andres </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bocay </LOCATION> region in <LOCATION> Olancho </LOCATION> province, but no other details were available. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a government source speaking on condition of anonymity, said there had been unconfirmed reports that an estimated 300 Sandinista soldiers had entered <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The reported incursion did not affect peace talks then under way between top Sandinista and <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, even though both sides said their forces would stop fighting during the talks. Late Wednesday, the talks produced an accord calling for a 60-day cease-fire beginning April 1. Earlier Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had said that unless the military situation in Honduran changes, the approximately 3,200 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops sent to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> last week would return home early next week. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops were ordered to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> as a show of force after 2,000 Sandinsta soldiers allegedly chased Contra rebels from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>.
