<HEAD>Educators Decry Trend Toward Standardized Testing in Kindergarten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two education associations called for an end Thursday to what they called the growing practice of subjecting kindergarten children to standardized tests to determine promotion to first grade. The groups said the same tests are being used to determine whether a youngster is admitted to kindergarten or advised to spend another year in preschool. `` Our children are being tested too early and failed too soon, and parents should ask for what purpose,'' said <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Bredekamp </PERSON>, accreditation director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION>. Her group was joined by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Early </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Childhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Specialists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Departments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> calling for an end to mass standardized testing of children before the third grade. They said they did not object to testing of individual children whose teachers or parents suspect they have a learning or developmental problem. But for most children, they said, `` Parents should trust their own instincts and the observations of trained and experienced preschool and kindergarten teachers.'' Leaders of the groups said at a news conference they do not know how many schools are resorting to standardized placement or promotion tests for 4 -, 5-and 6-year-olds But <PERSON> Bredekamp </PERSON> said that in some areas, `` it is not unusual now for 20 percent or more of young children to be advised to wait a year before entering kindergarten, or to ` flunk' kindergarten, or to be assigned to a special track called ` readiness,' ` transitional' or ` developmental' kindergarten.'' <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> recently became the first state to require standardized testing of kindergarten children. The city of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> began testing kindergarteners in 1984 on basic math and reading skills, and has been holding back 10 percent of the children, most of them minorities. But last September the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> legislature voted to discontinue mandatory standardized tests for first and second graders. <PERSON> Asa </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilliard </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> child psychologist and professor at <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the tests are being used to hold children back or track them into remedial programs or special education, despite a lack of evidence that such steps improve their schooling. He said the tests have `` a disproportionate impact on those children who need school the most, the minority children.'' <PERSON> Bredekamp </PERSON> said testing `` narrows and misdirects the curriculum.'' `` The most important things to learn in kindergarten, such as self-esteem, social competence, confidence, self-discipline, desire to learn, can not be measured on standardized tests,'' she said. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> <PERSON> Ames </PERSON>, co-founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Gesell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which produces a widely used screening test, said it was `` discouraging that these groups have taken this political position.'' `` Our position is that if there are 25 children in a classroom, all acting at 5-year-old maturity level, the teacher still has to individualize the curriculum to different ability levels. But if you put children together at different maturity and ability levels, then you have differences you ca n't possibly span,'' she said in a telephone interview from the institute's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, headquarters. <PERSON> Bredekamp </PERSON> said the testing issue `` is part of the bigger issue of pushing academic subjects at too early an age.'' The association's president is child psychologist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Elkind </PERSON>, author of `` The Hurried Child'' and the leading critic of that trend. The association has 60,000 members, including teachers and others involved in preschool, kindergarten and early elementary education.
