<HEAD>Bed Shortage Related to Drug Epidemic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After closing hospital beds in recent years, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> faces a crisis because it did n't foresee the virulence and consequences of the narcotics epidemic, according to a study released Thursday. From 1985 to 1987, time in hospitals increased for drug users and for victims of the side effects of narcotics use _ AIDS patients and babies born too puny to go home. Psychiatric admissions not related to drugs also increased, but all other categories of patient care followed the predicted downward trend. `` Had it not been for the growth in psychiatry, substance abuse, AIDS and neonatal services, inpatient hospital use in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> would actually have fallen roughly 5 percent between July 1985 and July 1987, as was expected by planners and regulators who oversaw the closure of 1,800 hospital beds citywide during that period,'' the survey preparers said in a statement. They described the hospitals knotted in a `` medical gridlock'' in which `` literally hundreds of patients needing acute care services spend each night in emergency rooms because no beds are available on inpatient services.'' `` Various forms of social pathology visible, but inadequately addressed, in many parts of the community are coming home to roost within the city's health care facilities,'' the study said. The study, prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Bigel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, was based on data from 69 of the city's 81 municipal and voluntary hospitals. It covered about 89 percent of the approximately 35,000 certified hospital beds in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Medical authorities are divided on what must be done, said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s position is we need another 1,500 to 2,000 beds in this city fast,'' said <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON>. Others, including Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Axelrod </PERSON>, the state health commissioner, and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON>, dean of social policy graduate studies at <LOCATION> Brandeis </LOCATION>, suggest a mix of community-based services, nursing care and special housing. During 1985-87, hospital stays grew by 44 percent for acquired immune deficiency syndrome patients, 15 percent each for psychiatric and substance abuse patients and 14 percent for newborns, the study found. The increases have been concentrated in low-income communities, another indicator that the hospital occupancy crisis is grounded in what <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON> called the `` general socio-economic disintegration of parts of the city.'' <PERSON> Vladeck </PERSON> said crack, a form of cocaine, accounted for a large part of the problem. In addition to admissions traceable to crack-induced psychosis, `` there's a lot of crack-related respiratory illness _ people literally burn out their lungs smoking crack,'' he said. `` Obviously, a lot of those low-birth-weight newborns are to crack-using mothers.''
