<HEAD>Agreement Could Mean Post-Contra Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cease-fire agreement signed by the Nicaraguan government and resistance forces appears to signify the onset of the post-Contra era in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and an entirely new political dynamic in that country. The administration was officially upbeat about the agreement but the Contras, with little prospect of receiving more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid, were forced to drop virtually all the concessions they had been seeking earlier this year. The agreement clearly falls short of the administration goal of an `` irreversible'' democratic process in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as its price for suspending aid to the Contras. Achievement of that objective is apparently dependent on Sandinista good will coupled with whatever diplomatic and economic pressures the industrialized democracies can muster to prod the Nicaraguans in that direction. In theory at least, the Nicaraguan war could be revived if upcoming talks break down. But the short-term prospect is for the dismantling of the Contras accompanied by a number of gestures by the Sandinistas, including a phased release of prisoners, permission for political exiles to return, participation of Contra representatives in a national dialogue and guarantees of free expression. All of this was agreed to in the <LOCATION> Sandinista-Contra </LOCATION> cease-fire talks this week. Still, the Contras have relatively little to show for their six-year effort, particularly when compared with their goals as recently as late January. At the time, they still were receiving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military supplies and were cautiously optimistic about the prospects for more aid when that issue came to a congressional vote in early February. But Contra aid foes prevailed on that vote. The Contras' settlement terms in late January called for the implementation of 17 democratic reforms during a proposed 30-day cease-fire period. They demanded gradual disarmament of both sides, the repatriation of Soviet bloc military advisers, formation of a single `` apolitical'' national army, suspension of compulsory military service and the disbanding of the Sandinista militia. These demands received no attention at all or were dismissed with no more than vague references in the communique signed Wednesday night. Assuming that the Contras are dismantled, several questions arise: Will President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> pursue with vigor the communization of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, as administration hardliners fear? Will he strengthen his ties to the leftist insurgency in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>? Will he proceed with plans to acquire MiG jet fighters from the Soviets? Will he build up the Nicaraguan armed forces to 600,000, as his defense minister suggested? Will he move toward a uniquely Nicaraguan system, which is neither modeled after <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> nor his democratic neighbor, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>? Or will there be a genuine national reconciliation in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, as <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> suggests? Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> outlined in generally positive terms the administration's reaction to the cease-fire agreement, calling it an `` important step forward.'' Other officials, asking not to be identified, said they preferred not to offer their own assessments of the agreement even on an anonymous basis because to do so would undercut <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. This suggests continued skepticism within the administration about the terms the Contras agreed to and continued anger with the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for letting the rebels down. Ever since the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> peace agreement was signed last Aug. 7, the administration had been steadily scaling back on its expectations in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Last fall, the administration was asking the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for $ 270 million in Contra aid. Faced with congressional opposition, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> lowered that figure to $ 36.2 million, with only 10 per cent of that earmarked for military aid. That proposal was defeated seven weeks ago and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> mandated an end to all aid deliveries by Feb. 29. Slightly more than three weeks later, the Contras settled with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>, accepting terms that they would have rejected out of hand not long ago.
</TEXT>
