<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly half a million 1985 cars and light trucks made by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> must be recalled because they fail to meet federal air pollution standards, the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. A faulty thermal vacuum switch is part of the reason the vehicles' exhaust contains excess carbon monoxide and evaporated gasoline, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. The vehicles affected by the recall are equipped with 5.0 liter -LRB- 305 cubic inches -RRB- and 5.7 liter -LRB- 350 cubic inches -RRB- engines, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. They were sold as the <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Impala </ORGANIZATION>, Caprice Classic, Camaro, <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camino </ORGANIZATION>; the Pontiac Firebird, <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION>, Grand Prix and <LOCATION> Parisienne </LOCATION>; and the <ORGANIZATION> GMC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caballero </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Models sold in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which are built to stricter standards, are also included. `` Earlier, we offered to recall the vehicles to replace the thermostatic vacuum switch,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Mott </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` We will review the order and determine how best to respond.'' Such recall orders by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> are rare and generally indicate the agency and a manufacturer could not agree on something, such as the cause of the problem, its scope, the necessary repair, terms of the recall or something else. Most recalls are made voluntarily. Ms. <PERSON> Mott </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> it believed replacing the switch on the vehicles would be sufficient to bring emissions into compliance with federal standards. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, however, said its tests showed that `` replacement of the -LRB- switch -RRB- alone will not completely remedy the problem and that additional repairs may be necessary.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the order, or to submit a repair plan for <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s approval before notices are mailed to owners. The company last year recalled more than a million vehicles from the 1982 and 1983 model years for similar problems.
