<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Losses,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>1987 S&amp;L Losses Highest in Half-Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The savings and loan industry, drained by insolvent institutions in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, last year recorded its worst loss since the Great Depression, the government said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said a $ 3.2 billion loss in the last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's red ink for the year to a record $ 6.8 billion. That was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-Depression record of $ 4.6 billion, set in 1981, when the prime lending rate soared above 20 percent. `` I hope it's the worst we'll ever see,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insitutions </ORGANIZATION>, the industry's largest trade group. The nation's 3,147 federally insured <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls lost $ 1.8 billion in the third quarter of last year and $ 1.9 billion in the spring. They earned $ 100 million in the first three months of the year and had a modest $ 132 million profit for all of 1986. In contrast, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said earlier this month that the nation's 13,700 federally insured commercial banks earned $ 3.7 billion in 1987. Still, it was their lowest profit since 1933. Despite the overall loss for the S & amp; L industry, 66 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls earned money in the fourth quarter. The $ 1.3 billion earnings of 2,089 S & amp; Ls partly offset the $ 4.5 billion losses of the remaining 1,058 institutions. For the year, the profitable two-thirds of the industry earned $ 6.6 billion, which was more than wiped out by the $ 13.4 billion deficit of the money-losing S & amp; Ls. The percentage of institutions earning a profit has declined steadily for two years, from 81 percent in the first quarter of 1986 to 66 percent at the end of last year. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Barth </PERSON>, chief economist of the bank board, said <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L losses were heavily concentrated in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, which is dependent on the ailing oil and gas industry. <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> said the worst 20 institutions _ most of them in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> _ lost a total of $ 2.1 billion in the final quarter of last year, accounting for two-thirds of the overall industry loss. An unprofitable instituion is not necessarily insolvent. An S & amp; L is considered insolvent when its loans and other assets are worth less than what it owes to depositors and other creditors. The bank board said 345 S & amp; Ls were insolvent at the end of 1987 under regulatory accounting principles, 109 of them in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> alone. There were 510 insolvent S & amp; Ls under the stricter accounting principles that will be used beginning next year. By another measure of health, return on assets, savings institutions' performance was not quite as bad as 1981 and 1982. The return was negative 0.56 percent last year, compared with negative 0.73 percent in 1981 and minus 0.65 percent in 1982. <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> said some of the overall industry loss in 1987 can be attributed to a decrease in the corporate tax rate. He said some S & amp; Ls decided to push profits into 1988, when the top tax rate is 34 percent, rather than take them in 1987, when the rate was 40 percent. <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> said he believed the industry's problems have `` plateaued out'' and that `` there is some light at the end of the tunnel'' in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> A. Regalia, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, warned that most economists believe interest rates will edge higher and said <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> real estate shows no sign of a sharp rebound. Regalia said the performance of the thrift industry this year will depend on how quickly the bank board resolves problems at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> institutions. `` You have to be as expeditious as possible at getting them closed down. So far I think -LRB- the bank board -RRB- has recognized the problem. Now it's time to get out and do it,'' he said. Lack of money to pay depositors had forced the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which insures deposits to $ 100,000, to keep many insolvent S & amp; Ls open. Now that money is flowing into the fund from a $ 10.8 billion recapitalization authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in August, the bank board is moving to close ailing institutions or merge them with healthier S & amp; Ls. Last month, the bank board announced a plan to spend $ 6 billion to $ 7 billion in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> over the next several years, but it does n't anticipate announcements on specific S & amp; Ls before early April
