<TEXT>
 Former national security adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> testified for three hours Thursday before a federal grand jury investigating Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>'s ties to a $ 1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline. <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON>, who declined to comment during a break in the grand jury proceedings, became involved in the pipeline project in the spring and summer of 1985 through contacts with <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, longtime <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> friend <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s client, Swiss oilman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>. <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> was accompanied to the federal courthouse by legal counsel, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, who said his client is a witness in the grand jury investigation. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> is investigating whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> may have violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in connection with the pipeline project. In a September 1985 memo to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> relating <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s conversations with <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said a portion of up to $ 700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of then-Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has said he does n't recall reading the reference to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> payments in the memo, which was found in the attorney general's files at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last year in connection with <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s investigation. <PERSON> McKay </PERSON