<HEAD>Iranians Pull Out of Islamic Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chemical Weapons, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> angrily left an Islamic conference Thursday after fellow Moslems decried its failure to heed cease-fire calls in its war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and accused it of instigating rioting in the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> said the withdrawal proved the `` loneliness'' of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s stance toward the Islamic world. The Iranian envoy to the meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Taskhiri </PERSON>, flew out of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> at the head of his five-man delegation. `` We were not happy,'' <PERSON> Taskhiri </PERSON>, his voice quavering with anger, said in a telephone interview. He said his group boycotted meetings Wednesday night and Thursday. `` The conference is taking place only to serve the interests of a certain country,'' he said, referring to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. `` Therefore, we do n't see why we should stay at this meeting.'' <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and other Arab countries were drafting a resolution on the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> conflict to submit to foreign ministers of the 46-member conference. Sources close to the conference confirmed that the draft denounces <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s failure to heed last July's <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution 598, which calls for a cease-fire in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war The sources, speaking on condition they not be identified further, said the draft also criticizes <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s purported leadership of the violence in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, and calls for future `` security measures'' to protect Moslem pilgrims. In a statement to the <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> government announcing its withdrawl, the <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> delegation specified it was unhappy with the draft `` resolution on the gulf war ... and the resolution on the holy places.'' The text of the statement was provided by one of the sources. The conference sources also said the draft of the final communique, likely to be issued by Friday, also called for: _ An immediate Soviet withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>; _ Support for the 15-week-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>; _ Guaranteed rights for Moslem minorities in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and other countries where they might suffer persecution; _ Unspecified measures against air piracy. <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> said `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s withdrawal demonstrates its loneliness'' in the ranks of Moslem countries. `` They wanted to express their voice, or better, their lies, to the organization, but they did not find ears.'' Egyptian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Esmat </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Meguid </PERSON>, whose country was the target of Iranian criticism earlier in the conference, echoed <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>, saying: `` The voice of the Iranian representative is an odd voice and it represents the loneliness in which <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> lives.'' The Iranians attended the meeting after boycotting last year's summit of Islamic heads of state in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> accuses of aiding <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s war effort <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which is Persian and not Arab, sent a low-level delegation to the <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION> meeting. <PERSON> Taskhiri </PERSON> is head of the foreign relations department in <LOC