<HEAD>FEC Decides to Grant Matching Funds to LaRouche</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday declared fringe presidential candidate <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> eligible for federal matching funds, even as a former aide was testifying elsewhere of being pressured to wring donations out of people for <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s 1984 campaign. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> is standing trial in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> federal court on a charge relating to alleged irregularity in his 1984 campaign. While the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was certifying <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> to receive federal funds for his 1988 campaign, former aide <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> testified at the trial that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> solicitors were warned in 1984 that that falling short of daily fund-raising quotas was `` the moral equivalent of treason'' and would result in the collapse of Western civilization. The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION>, on a 5-1 vote, said that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> has fulfilled the requirements for eligibility to receive matching funds. But the commission also said special review procedures would be undertaken to evaluate each of his submissions for matching funds, in light of irregularities found in his first submission. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> said the ruling was `` terrific.'' She noted the campaign had `` no problem with the conditions'' the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> imposed. In voting with the majority, Commissioner <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said, `` Presidential candidates and campaigns can come in many different shapes and colors.'' `` Overall it does look like there is substantial support for a presidential campaign from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens for Mr. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>,'' he said noting that <PERSON> Larouche </PERSON> has raised more than $ 2 million from contributors. But Commissioner <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Aikens </PERSON> opposed the majority, saying an <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> survey of <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> contributors raised `` a question of patent irregularity'' in fund raising. A survey by the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION>'s audit staff had indicated that 6 percent of 713 LaRouche contributors contacted had not intended their checks to go to his campaign. The survey was undertaken because some contributor checks had the letters `` LDC,'' presumably for <ORGANIZATION> LaRouche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, written over `` SDI'' as the payee. And some checks contained memo notations regarding AIDS or SDI _ the first referring to the disease and the second referring to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative _ suggesting the donors may not have intended to give money to a presidential campaign, but to one of those causes. <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> auditors said many people who responded to the survey `` described instances where he @ she 1. felt pressured into making a contribution, 2. made contributions believing that the contribution was for a specific purpose other than furthering <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s presidential nomination campaign, 3. made loans to the campaign, and 4. had contributed to a number of <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s interests, while making all checks The auditors had recommended that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> be found ineligible for matching funds, but the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> legal staff had said `` patent irregularities indicated by the survey results do not justify an unfavorable eligibility report.'' Instead of the usual five-day approval period, a review period of 25 days will be allowed in which the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> staff will check for irregularities in the checks he submits to be matched. In addition any checks written out simply to <ORGANIZATION> LDC </ORGANIZATION>, or those with memo notations `` indicating lack of donative intent'' will not be matched, the commission said. To be certified for matching funds, a candidate must raise $ 100,000 across 20 states in individual contributions of $ 250 or less. After becoming eligible, the candidates can receive matching funds for each contribution of $ 250 or less that they raise privately. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> is on trial in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, charged with conspiracy to obstruct a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud and other irregularities in his 1984 campaign.
