<HEAD>Reagan Praises `Free-Market' Trend in Rewarding Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Thursday lauded a trend toward `` free-market principles'' in education that provide incentives for teachers who achieve superior performance. Joining Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> in a visit to <ORGANIZATION> Oakton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> just outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said recent tours of this sort `` have strengthened my confidence in our country's future.'' But the president said much work still lies ahead if the nation is to bring about the sort of educational reforms called for in a 1983 government report, `` A Nation at Risk.'' The president said he expects a status report on American education, which he is to receive next month from <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, to `` tell us what things we still must do'' as well as what progress has been made. He also said that interest in teaching has increased in recent years, partly because `` we've begun to introduce free-market principles like incentivies and accountability to education.'' He praised <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in which <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> is located, for initiating a plan in which `` career ladders, performance-based pay and other initiatives help to keep good teachers in the profession.'' But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said no improvements in the caliber of instruction or the quality of teachers will be helpful `` if a school has a drug problem.'' `` If students are using drugs, then no education reform can work,'' the president told several hundred students and teachers in the school auditorium. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> made several light-hearted references to his boyhood school days, saying he was n't a particularly good student, and telling how he'd been called to the principal's office once. `` It was n't an invitation,'' he quipped. When a student asked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> whether he could attend the seniors' high school graduation June 15, he smiled broadly and said he did n't know if he could make it `` Some people think I'm the most powerful man in the world,'' he said, -LRB- but -RRB- `` every day they hand me a piece of paper that tells me everything I'm going to be doing every 15 minutes.''
