<HEAD>Markey Plans To Draft Market Reforms Without Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> finance subcommittee said Wednesday he will write legislation reforming the nation's financial markets without waiting for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to resolve disputes among warring regulatory agencies `` For the investors of this country, justice delayed is justice denied,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass. At a four-hour hearing of his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on finance, <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> sharply criticized the creation of an administration working group to coordinate recommendations on what should be done to prevent a recurrence of the Oct. 19 stock market crash. The panel, headed by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, has the job of trying to resolve a turf fight among the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> over regulating the various financial markets. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed an order last Friday creating the panel and gave it 60 days to report back to him. His spokesman, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, warned that the issues `` may not be resolved quickly or without considerable reflection.'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, however, complained that the recommendations delivered in Janaury by a presidential task force headed by former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> should have been enough for the administration to make up its mind. He complained that waiting two more months would make it increasingly difficult to pass legislation this year, adding, `` In my judgment <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must act this year.'' `` The greatest danger facing our financial system is the safe course of delay,'' he said. <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> responded that his panel, which will include representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and the commodities commission, is not conducting another study. `` We are anxious to create action from this, not simply more discussion,'' he said. <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said his committee, with the help of <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, would proceed on a `` parallel track'' without waiting for <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>'s group to formulate a position. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s commission called for giving the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> the power to coordinate regulation of the stock, options and futures markets. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates stocks and options, also wants jurisdiction over stock futures, which currently are overseen by the commodities commission. That agency opposes jurisdictional changes, and the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has rejected taking on the additional responsibility recommended by <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> has called for one regulator over stocks and stock futures, but did not say which agency should get that power. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, who agreed to help <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> write his bill, said he did not agree that the creation of the Gould group would unduly delay action and said he did not see why <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration could not work simultaneously. Meeting with reporters after the hearing, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> moderated earlier remarks on the urgency for reform. In a line that has become much quoted, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> had compared the markets to a gun and said, `` We are looking down the barrel of the same gun, and it is still loaded.'' But on Wednesday, he said, `` I did n't say anybody was going to pull the trigger.''
