</PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash., a sponsor of a Contra aid package that includes such a guaranteed vote `` It's a recognition that there is still lots of skepticism, maybe even suspicion, all the way around,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` People have been at each other's throats, and that's not going to dissipate easily.'' But of such suggestions, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said: `` I think it would be counterproductive to talk about it ... We do n't want to rekindle the war.'' House Majority Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., said compromise on language about future Contra aid was possible `` We are willing to talk to the Republicans about anything, but we are not willing to set up a process that the Nicaraguans could interpret as allowing for more military aid,'' <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said. `` It looks like there may be a pretty good possibility of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> getting together on something the administration could buy,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` We have n't had a strong voice for American policy in Central America in five years'' because of partisan divisions over the administration's Contra policy,'' he said. `` We would finally be sending a clear message.'' `` For heaven's sake, if the Nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, surely Republicans and Democrats can agree,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. The promises of quick action on a new aid package for the rebels contrasted sharply with the inaction of recent weeks. The issue had been stalled since the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> narrowly defeated a $ 30 million humanitarian aid package on March 3, and the rebels have been without <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance since Feb. 29. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said lawmakers had been intentionally moving slowly on the issue since March 17, when <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leaders called <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s office and said they were optimistic about achieving a cease-fire in the talks that began Monday and asked that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hold back on voting for new aid
