<HEAD>Taiwan Reminded By US On Nuclear Non-Proliferation Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman said on Wednesday that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has been `` repeatedly'' reminded to stick to a pledge against building nuclear weapons, but he declined to comment on a report the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pressured the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nation to stop work on a plutonium processing plant. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> halted work on the secret plant, which could have processed plutonium, a key component of nuclear weapons, and shut its largest civilian research reactor at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> insistence, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. It was not clear whether the planned installation, which could have extracted plutonium from spent reactor fuel, indicated a decision to build a bomb or just an attempt to keep open a nuclear option, according to unnamed officials quoted by newspaper. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> would neither confirm nor deny the report, but he acknowledged that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has expressed concerns to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> about the proliferation of nuclear weapons. And his comments suggested that if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did indeed use pressure to stop the Taiwanese program, the pressure worked. `` We've repeatedly conveyed the importance that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including both the administration and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> places on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s adherence to its non-proliferation commitments, and we are confident that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> understands this,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` It is our belief that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> is not engaged in activities which are inconsistent with its commitments,'' he said. He noted statements by Taiwanese leaders that they have no intention of developing nuclear weapons. Also, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has undertaken obligations of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, in which countries agree to let international inspectors monitor programs to make sure nuclear material is not being diverted to use in weapons. `` All nuclear materials on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> are subject to safeguards applied by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` We are not aware of any violation of those safeguards.'' According to officials quoted by the Times, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> learned of the project from Col. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> Hsien-Yi, a top-level informant at a Taiwanese research institute who left <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> a few months ago with the help of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, deputy director of the nuclear energy research center at the military-run <ORGANIZATION> Chungshan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, has been missing since January. Taiwanese newspaper reports said he might have fled to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with documents showing that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> planned to make nuclear weapons. His whereabouts is unknown. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the effort to build an installation capable of plutonium extraction violated <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s secret commitment to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that it would not undertake research to develop atomic weapons, the Times reported.
