<HEAD>Major Maker of Ozone-Destroying CFCs Agrees To Stop Their
Manufacture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, producer of one-quarter of the chemicals destroying the Earth's ozone shield, plans to stop making them because of new research showing decay of the ozone, the company said Thursday. The company gave no deadline for ending manufacture of the `` fully halogenated chlorofluorocarbons,'' or CFCs. These non-toxic, non-flammable compounds that <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> helped develop in the 1930s are widely used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning solvents, plastic foam blowing agents and, outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as aerosol propellants. `` I do n't see it in the near term,'' not for five years, but at the end of such a period policymakers and the chemical industry should know `` how rapidly the transition can take place,'' <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Steed </PERSON>, environment manager in <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Freon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> division, said in an interview. `` Our intention is to move as smoothly as possible from these compounds into alternatives,'' <PERSON> Steed </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> announced in January it had developed a substitute foam blowing agent. Also, <ORGANIZATION> Petroferm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has announced a replacement solvent for CFCs, and other chemicals are in the works at several companies. On Thursday the company began notifying customers, competitors, employees and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of its new policy. Environmentalists were quick with praise, hailing <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>'s `` courage'' and `` leadership. As recently as March 4, <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> said a proposal from three senators that the company immediately stop making CFCs was `` unwarranted and counterproductive.'' The senators _ <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Vt </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont; and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn. _ had written <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON> calling on him to redeem the company's mid-1970s pledge to end CFC production if a threat to health were shown A March 15 report of scientists convened by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> found a 2.3 percent decline in ozone at mid-latitudes between 1969 and 1986, most probably the result of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> accumlations high in the atmosphere. That is `` important new information,'' <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON> wrote members of the subcommittee on which the three senators serve. `` I hope it's clear that it's the science of last week we're responding to,'' <PERSON> Steed </PERSON> said <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON>'s letter said the company believes `` the short-term risk to health and the environment from CFCs is negligible'' but `` additional actions should be taken.'' Ozone, a pollutant at ground level, at high altitudes blocks ultraviolet rays of the sun that cause skin cancer. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has estimated that a 1 percent decrease in ozone thickness _ it would be only 3 millimeters thick if it were at sea level _ causes a 2 percent to 3 percent increase in ultraviolet and a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in the most common skin cancers. Last fall in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, major producers agreed on a treaty, now signed by 31 nations but ratified only by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, agreeing to cut <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production 20 percent in 1992 and another 30 percent in 1998. The Environmental Defense Fund has estimated that the two cuts could amount to only 35 percent instead of 50 percent if all the exemptions are used. The treaty was accelerated, many experts acknowledge, by a 1985 finding that over <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, ozone declines sharply each spring _ by 50 percent last year. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> plans `` to urge all nations to treat the new scientific information seriously, accelerate ratification of the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> protocol, and then immediately initiate the protocol's assessment process to consider further global limitations,'' <PERSON> Heckert </PERSON>'s letter said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON>, chairman of the trade group <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> for a Responsible CFC Policy, said in a statement President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should `` personally contact the heads of government'' of participating countries asking that they ratify the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> agreement. `` This is a sterling example of corporate environmental leadership that ought to be emulated worldwide,'' and shows that `` technology can solve environmental problems,'' in this case by coming up with substitutes, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudek </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. About 2.3 billion pounds of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds are made worldwide each year, with more than 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> employees producing about 25 percent from plants in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The company says it gets $ 600 million annually from <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> sales, about 2 percent of total sales revenue. <PERSON> Steed </PERSON> said that `` Over the long term, it's our goal'' that jobs making replacement compounds should offset lost <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> jobs. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants are in <LOCATION> Antioch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Montague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; and Deepwater, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>.
