<HEAD>US Belittles Soviet Technology For Spotting Nuclear Missiles On
Ships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> belittled Soviet technology for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an invitation this week to see the process before the May 29-June 2 summit meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Thursday. During three days of pre-summit talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> offered to let the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> participate in an experiment to test the system in April. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> hailed the system as a technological milestone in missile detection that would help the superpowers achieve their goal of a summit agreement to cut long-range nuclear arsenals. The senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, however, `` we're not interested'' because the system does n't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise missiles, as the Soviets claim. `` The Soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell us more than we already know,'' the official said. `` Such technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.'' It could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships, the official said. `` Our people know a great deal about the ideas that the Soviets have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official said. When they agreed in principle last December to hold a springtime summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50 percent. With little progress _ notably on the verification issues _ during <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for three days this week, neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time. The senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, moreover, that until the negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types of weapons involved, they wo n't know which ones will be covered in a treaty. Another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on such explosive issues as <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and human rights warned against expecting `` easy solutions'' to U.S.-Soviet problems. The official described the most recent talks as `` grueling,'' notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> sought to dispel suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on substantive accomplishments During <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` we made enough progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters. During the talks this week both sides `` faced all the tough problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he said. The summit `` will be well prepared; there will be substance to discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He added that `` there will be a number of important and substantive and meaningful issues to be resolved and all of those things will occur at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. It meets all the criteria that needs to be met.'' `` I think this summit will be quite productive, well defined, well prepared,'' the spokesman said without citing any specific areas of agreement.
