<HEAD>Iowa Quietly Continues Democratic Delegate Selection Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six weeks after the precinct caucuses that put <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> in the national spotlight and provided the first test of Democratic candidates' strength, Democrats here are quietly proceeding with the next step in their delegate-selection process. The conventions in the 99 counties this weekend are the second step in the complex process of choosing 52 of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s 58 delegates to the Democratic National Convention. The field has shifted dramatically since Feb. 8, when the much-publicized precinct caucuses were held. Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> congressman who won the Democratic contest, has gone on to weak showings elsewhere. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> have surged to the front of the Democratic pack. Supporters who put <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> on top last month probably wo n't flee his sagging candidacy for other Democratic candidates in county conventions this weekend, Democratic leaders said Wednesday <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters are making a low-key effort to lure supporters from other camps, but working hard to keep their expectations low. `` It's informal,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>. `` I'm sure all of the campaigns are trying to lobby.'' At the precinct caucuses, party activists elected delegates to the county conventions, based on the proportion of support for the various presidential candidates. At the county conventions, delegates will be elected to congressional district conventions later in the spring. Despite <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s slide, <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> backers wo n't be making a major effort to convince his delegates