<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Kremlin laid out an 8-year plan Thursday night to pacify a <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> region shaken by ethnic strife. At the same time, army helicopters were reported circling over the Armenian capital to prevent further unrest. The carrot-and-stick approach seemed aimed at cooling feelings inflamed by a noisy Armenian campaign to annex the region of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> from neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and to warn Armenian activists to end their protests. Activists have said specifically that government efforts to improve poor economic and social conditions of Armenians in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> mountain region near the Soviet border with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would not meet their demands. Armenian newspaper editor <PERSON> Regyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarkisyan </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and scene of mass pro-annexation demonstrations in February, was being patrolled by <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopters and soldiers. He said no violence was reported. <PERSON> Sarkisyan </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview that most Armenians were showing patience in awaiting resolution of the issue. On Feb. 28, rioting broke out in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, and officials said 32 people were killed. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, which is smaller than <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, has a population that is 75 percent Armenian but has been a part of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> since 1923. The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's highest government body, rejected as `` intolerable'' Wednesday the campaign for annexation of the region, indicating it would not bend to pressure from mass protests. The Presidium, meanwhile, ordered ministries to solve `` pressing problems of the economic, social and cultural development'' of the region. The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> made public details of their proposals Thursday. The plan for 1988-95 calls for stepping up the pace of construction of schools, hospitals, apartments and roads in the region and for increasing the publication of Armenian literature. `` Work will also be completed to ensure a steady reception of the national television program, as well as ... telecasts of Armenian and Azerbaijani television,'' the officia <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said in a report on the Politburo meeting. The plan calls for increasing by 50 percent the industrial output of the region. The plan approved by the Politburo was formulated by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s policy-making body, and the government <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. It said the Politburo deemed it `` essential to resolutely discourage the slightest manifestations of nationalism or disrespect for national sentiments of members of various ethnic groups.'' Last week, a prominent Soviet journalist writing in the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News weekly said residents of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> suffer cultural and economic disadvantages. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Khachaturov </PERSON> said people there have difficulty getting books in their native language and officials have not made good on pledges to build a sports complex and children's institutions. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> dissident <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Senderov </PERSON> said Thursday that a correspondent for an unofficial human rights journal called from