<HEAD>Former Israeli Nuclear Worker Convicted Of Treason, Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former nuclear technician who claimed he revealed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s atomic secrets for the good of humanity was convicted Thursday of espionage and treason and could be sentenced to 20 years in prison. <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON>, 34, was found guilty by a three-judge panel after a trial that had been closed to the public since it began in September. His lawyer said the <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> would appeal the verdict to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> is very disappointed,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Avigdor </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON>. `` The court decided that he was a traitor, and he had hoped to be seen differently. But he is not broken. He is looking ahead to the appeal.'' The conviction carries a maximum sentence of death. However, prosecutor <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chasson </PERSON> said he would ask the court for a sentence of life imprisonment, which in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is limited to 20 years. Sentencing is set for Sunday. <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON>, who worked nine years at the nuclear facility in <LOCATION> Dimona </LOCATION>, was charged for revealing details of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s atomic capacity to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> in October 1986. The newspaper said <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON>'s information showed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had stockpiled the world's sixth-largest nuclear arsenal. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> never has responded directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to introduce such weapons into the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> has insisted he made his revelations to alert the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons. The state argued he intended to harm <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security. He was kept under heavy security during the trial, which was closed to the public because authorities feared an open hearing would harm state security. <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> has been held in near isolation for the last 18 months and has been permitted to see only his attorney and family. The precautions were taken after <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> managed to flash a message to reporters at a pre-trial appearance by scribbling it on the palm of his hand. In the message he said he had been kidnapped in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, presumably by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> agents, and brought to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for trial. <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> was fired from the <LOCATION> Dimona </LOCATION> nuclear center in 1985 and went to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, where he became acquainted with a priest and converted to Christianity. He later traveled to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, but disappeared in October 1986, just days before <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published his revelations. Israeli officials acknowledged several weeks later he was in custody in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Details of <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON>'s journey back to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> were revealed by his brother, <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON>, who said <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> was lured from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> by an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> woman named <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>, who promised him sex. In <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, he was abducted by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> agents and spirited home, <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> said. During the trial, <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON> argued <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> did not hurt <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security because information about <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s nuclear capacity was available in the academic world He said <PERSON> Vanunu </PERSON> had in fact helped state security because allegations of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s nuclear strength served as a deterrent to Arab enemies.
