<HEAD>House Panel OKs Senate Bill To Protect Historic Shipwrecks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation pushed by archaeologists to save historic shipwrecks won <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee approval Wednesday despite complaints from recreational divers that the bill could block their enjoyment of the undersea landmarks. The bill is designed to clear up the murky legal status of shipwreck jurisdiction by giving states authority over certain downed vessels in state waters, preventing salvage operators from destroying historic remains. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> put aside a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version of the measure and passed 29-10, largely along party lines, a bill sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed in December. Democrats led by Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., who has advocated a shipwreck preservation law for a decade, said they agreed with an amendment proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shumway </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., mandating that states make shipwrecks accessible to But <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> and others noted that an amended bill would need <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval again, and they were afraid the measure would die there as it has in past years. This is the first time the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has approved a shipwreck bill. `` Do n't kill this bill by making it perfect,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> urged. `` I'm afraid it's going to be a better corpse.'' <PERSON> Shumway </PERSON>, pointing to vocal opposition from sport diving groups, said the legislation should spell out guarantees for divers. `` I think this bill can be vastly improved,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> retorted that `` if you do n't pass this bill, there wo n't be any shipwrecks to dive on. Rep. <PERSON> Claudine </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>, who said she is a recreational diver, agreed, joining Democrats in defeating the Shumway amendment 25-14. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said later that he expected easy passage on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration supports the measure. The committee agreed to place in a report that accompanies the bill language stating that it is the intent of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for states to make shipwrecks accessible to divers. Under the legislation, states would have jurisdiction over historic shipwrecks within their three-mile state limits. They would be charged with establishing protective areas, allowing recreational exploration and overseeing public and private salvage efforts. Under admiralty laws, discoverers of wrecks can salvage abandoned vessels. Those laws are at odds with many state statutes.
