<HEAD>Embassy Demonstration for Soviet Jews Tests New Supreme Court
Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of Soviet Jews tested a new <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling Wednesday that knocked down rules banning peaceful demonstrations within 500 feet of foreign embassies in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The dozen demonstrators, accompanied for a time by Sens. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., gave speeches on the sidewalk in front of the Soviet Embassy Then seven of them sat down on the sidewalk, prayed and sang. Some taunted Soviet officials as they moved freely in and out of the embassy gate. The police, whose numbers rivaled those of the demonstrators, did nothing to impede the protest. They quietly ensured that the driveway and embassy gate remained clear and they steered pedestrians through the maze of protesters and the accompanying phalanx of reporters and photographers. Police made no move to arrest anyone. In fact, they stopped traffic on busy 16th Street so the demonstrators could move back and forth to the embassy. `` They ca n't block the driveway,'' said Sgt. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> police. `` They ca n't block free passage of the sidewalk.'' Rabbi <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the chairman of the Student Struggle for Soviet Jewry, was a leader of Wednesday's demonstration He has been arrested several times for violating the limits on protests near the Soviet Embassy. `` There are those who say the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- ruling takes away the dramatic tool of arrest,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said before the demonstration began. But he warned, `` If the necessity arises that we'll have to sit peacefully in front of the gates, then that's something I'd be willing to do.'' In Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling, Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, writing for the court, said police may disperse groups of three or more congregating near embassies when they `` reasonably believe that a threat to the security or peace of the embassy is present.'' Banning such gatherings `` does not prohibit peaceful congregations,'' she wrote, adding that the ban `` is limited to groups posing a security threat.'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said the court's ruling `` allows a far greater voice for Soviet Jews specifically at a time when so many have been duped by ` glasnost.''' Glasnost is the Russian word for `` openness.'' He condemned an upcoming trip by <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secretary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> and some 500 business executives to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` There can not be an increase of trade, an increase of loans without a concession on human rights on the other side,'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said. As the demonstration commenced in front of the embassy, a dozen Soviet officials sat in the patio on the other side of the gates, enjoying the suddenly springlike weather, chatting amongst themselves and occasionally gazing at the demonstrators. As the protestors sang at one point, a Soviet official walked into the front gate, barely suppressing a smile.
