<HEAD>Motorola To Pay $16.7 Million In Fines For Navy Mischarges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s electronics group has agreed to pay the government $ 16.7 million and to plead guilty to a criminal information accusing it of mischarging for labor and materials on <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> satellite and missile contracts, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. In documents filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, was accused of inflating costs for a component of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> satellite communications and mischarging $ 2.5 million in labor, materials and other costs The money actually was spent on other work, the government said. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, relying on the inflated amounts, paid some $ 5 million more than it should have on a second contract for the satellite communications system, said the government. <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's top 50 defense contractors, agreed to plead guilty to three counts of making false statements. The firm said in a statement from <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Schaumburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, that `` it is now clear in retrospect'' that the electronics group's `` systems were not adequate to ensure total compliance with applicable laws and regulations.'' `` The conduct of the employees involved in these programs failed to conform to <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION>'s own internal standards,'' the statement added. The electronics group `` has greatly expanded its compliance efforts'' with reforms which `` are now an integral part of the way GEG does business.'' Under the agreement, which still must be approved by a court, the government has agreed not to prosecute the company further on the contracts, but reserves the right to prosecute individuals. The court documents also say the firm mischarged labor costs for work on 10 contracts involving production of target detecting devices for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Standard missile. The third count in the criminal information said <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> mischarged labor costs on a contract for the production of targeting detecting devices for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> missile. <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 16.7 million in criminal fines, restitution and civil penalties. The company already has paid $ 6.8 million to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The pleas result from an investigation into labor and materials charging and pricing practices by <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> from 1979 to 1984.
