<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, pressing on with his hard-line trade stance, on Thursday denied statements from aides that he would shut down his campaign for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination if he does not win Saturday's <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses. Amid turmoil over reports that <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> was a do-or-die state for him, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> delivered a speech here and denounced a `` dogmatic and outdated'' free trade theology that has cost the nation jobs. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> brushed aside questions about the future of his campaign, but aides spoke privately of a decision hinging on the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucus outcome. Plans are in motion for the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> congressman to file for re-election to his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat by the Tuesday deadline, said the aides, if <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> does not give him his first victory since the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> primary on Feb. 23. `` That's right. He will be out if does n't win in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>,'' said a campaign aide who would not be quoted by name. Asked if that aide's comment was accurate, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> told reporters: `` No. I'm running for president and I've doing very well here in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. ... I'm going to win in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. I'm going to continue and do well.'' `` My mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time. That's what I'm trying to do,'' he added `` Rather than trying to guess all the different hypotheticals of what might happen, I just think we have to be patient, wait to see the outcome and then decide what other steps should be taken.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> aides said publicly that nothing has changed in the past 48 hours, that it has been understood since Super Tuesday that <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> would end his race if he does not win here. The candidate's wife put it this way on Thursday: `` I think <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race, because at some point if you do n't do well here, it becomes difficult to raise money,''' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> WTVB </ORGANIZATION> radio. `` <PERSON> Dick </PERSON>'s message will be very popular in the industrial states, but if we do n't do well here, we will not be able to continue.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> is running third in the polls in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, behind <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Later Thursday, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> mimicked <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' claim of turning around the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> economy, adapting it to his campaign by saying `` This Saturday we're going to have a miracle in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> _ the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> miracle.'' Tuesday is the deadline for <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> to file for re-election for his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat. A meeting has been scheduled this weekend for the Democrats who have filed for the seat. One reason for the withdrawal _ and the congressional race _ would be to take care of any debts left over from the presidential bid. `` Only as Rep. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> can he raise the money to pay off the debts'' from the presidential campaign, one aide said. But <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> denied the campaign had a big debt and said that is not a factor. One of <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s problems was inadvertantly emphasized by the presence of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSO