<HEAD>Meese Says Bork Was Victim of `Character Assassination'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> was a victim of `` political muscle and character assassination'' who would have fought excesses by the judiciary had he been seated on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nomination was turned down 58-42 in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 23 by `` those partisans who would impermissibly seek to reshape the Constitution into a vehicle for their own limited political beliefs,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said in remarks prepared for delivery Thursday night to the <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Story </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative lawyers' group A copy of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s remarks was released at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` No one ... deserves a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> more than <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said of the appeals court judge who drew strong opposition for his conservative views on the role of the judiciary and other constitutional issues. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said the forces opposed to <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>'s nomination `` used political muscle and character assassination to thwart the appointment of a most deserving person.'' <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> and legal scholar <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>, who were being honored at an awards banquet of the society, have fought unwarranted judicial activism which has been `` advocated by those forces who like to be called ` progressive,''' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said. `` But ... their version of modern progressivism has passed democracy by, leaving it to today's conservatives to do what yesterday's progressives did: defend democracy,'' the attorney general said. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> cited as an example of judicial activism a federal judge's ruling in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> ordering additions to the facilities of local schools, and `` a doubling of the property tax rate to pay for them. He also criticized the ruling of a judge in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> who decreed a busing scheme for schools and vowed to require higher property taxes to pay for it if the voters failed to do so. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said judicial activism forecloses opportunities for local expression and leaves `` a drastically reduced scope for the institutions that are representative of citizen views.'' `` The pattern here is a subtle but dangerous transformation of the Constitution, such that it becomes less a plan of government and more an instrument for the regulation of potentially every personal action or policy decision _ regulation that the people themselves become powerless to control,'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> said.
