<HEAD>Highlights of Sandinista-Contra Truce Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are the key points of the cease-fire agreement reached between <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Sandinista government and the Contra rebels and some of the issues that remain unsettled:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 SETTLED: - A 60-day cease-fire begins April 1, with a temporary truce in effect until then _ Rebels move into specified zones in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> during the first 15 days of April _ Creation of a truce verification commission headed Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Roman Catholic leader, and the secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, Ambassador <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> _ Contras will stop taking military aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ Contras will be represented in Sandinista talks with internal opposition known as the national dialogue and will take part in the electoral process _ Amnesty for political prisoners, return of political exiles, release of 1,400 jailed Contras and 1,800 former National Guardsmen imprisoned since the 1979 Sandinista revolution _ Government guarantees freedom of expression without restrictions, in accordance with a regional peace plan signed last August by President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the presidents of four other Central American countries
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 UNSETTLED: _ Details of a permanent truce Negotiations begin April 6 in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. _ Location of the rebel zones Negotiations begin Monday in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. _ Laying down of <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> arms _ Military conscription This will be discussed as part of the national dialogue between the Sandinistas and the opposition, including the Contras. _ Contra delegates to the national dialogue _ Which neutral organizations will channel humanitarian aid to the Contras _ Precise dates for prisoner releases The government agreed to free 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday. Half of the remaining 1,300 will be freed after rebels are in specified zones. The other half and the former guardsmen will be freed after a permanent truce is in place.
</TEXT>
