ues conference, said he had discussed with <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on Wednesday a $ 48 million, one-year aid package that provided an expedited vote on further aid in June, although the rules for that vote remained to be worked out. Added Republican Whip <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> Lott </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>: `` The Contras are still in the field. They still have got to exist ... in case this thing collapses.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said terms discussed Wednesday before the cease-fire agreement was concluded _ including the $ 48 million figure and any process for a quick later aid vote _ would have to be reviewed in light of the Sandinista-Contra accord. `` I think that can be worked out,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. `` It looks like there may be a pretty good possibility of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> getting together on something the administration could buy,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` We have n't had a strong voice for American policy in Central America in five years'' because of partisan divisions over the administration's Contra policy,'' he said. `` We would finally be sending a clear message.'' `` For heaven's sake, if the Nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, surely Republicans and Democrats can agree,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. The promises of quick action on a new aid package for the rebels contrasted sharply with the inaction of recent weeks. The issue had been stalled since the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> narrowly defeated a $ 30 million humanitarian aid package on March 3, and the rebels have been without <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance since Feb. 29. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said lawmakers had been intentionally moving slowly on the issue since March 17, when <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leaders called <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s office and said they were optimistic about achieving a cease-fire in the talks that began Monday and asked that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hold back on voting for new aid
