<DATELINE>ABOARD USS SAMUEL B. ROBERTS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speeding through stiff winds and heavy seas early Thursday, we closed in on an Iranian landing craft that served as mother ship for speedboat attacks on neutral ships in the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. The decks were lashed by 15-foot waves and winds gusting to 50 knots but Cmdr <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON>, skipper of this 445-foot guided missile frigate, covered the the 45 miles to the Hengham-class landing craft and halted his pursuit 4,600 yards from his quarry. While there was no actual confrontation, not even a radio exchange, the presence of the American warship appeared to distract the landing craft Tomb from its mission. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers said that mission apparently was to serve as a floating base for speedboats that attack ships with machine-gun and rocket grenade fire. `` He now knows we know where he is. We can come back now and find him any time we want,'' <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON> told reporters in a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> news pool aboard the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. Increasingly, warships such as <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Fast Frigate No. 88 are closely monitoring the activities of Iranian warships in the southern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Their purpose apparently is to discourage Iranian attacks on neutral shipping in the waterway, where <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been at war since September 1980. Such missions may reflect a subtle but potentially significant shift in <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> policy under Rear Adm. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON>. Less, who took command of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> and its gulf component last month. American officers say there is no change in the `` rules of engagement.'' Those permit <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships to offer `` humanitarian assistance'' to neutral ships in distress that request help but prohibit them from interceding to stop an attack on a ship not flying the Stars and Stripes However, with the success of its primary mission to escort convoys of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers through these hazardous waters, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> may be adopting a more visible role to deter Iranian attacks. <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON>, a 40-year New Yorker who now lives in <LOCATION> Summerville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, parried questions about any new mission. His instructions concerning Iranian activity remain clear, he said: `` Do not close -LRB- on -RRB- him; do not harass him; leave him alone.'' The first sign of a shift in approach comes at a time when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have resumed attacks on gulf shipping. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> uses warplanes to strike shuttle tankers carrying Iranian oil through the gulf. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> retaliates with raids by speedboats and larger vessels on neutral shipping. Nearly 500 ships have been damaged since the war began and more than 300 sailors have been killed. After the dash to draw within close range of the Iranian craft, <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON> said it tried to turn the tables by approaching to within 1,200 yards of the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> soon after dawn Thursday. The American warship abruptly changed course, wheeling on the approaching Iranian, and it altered course. The Tomb kept to a parallel course as the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> sailed into the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, the narrow southern gate to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, and joined its sister ship <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and the frigate USS Bagley. They sailed westward into the teeth of a continuing shamal, a gulf storm that blows from the northwest and typically lasts about 24 hours. Winds exceeded 25 knots most of the day. Seas ran more than 15 feet, rolling the ships on their beams. Under clear skies, the roaring winds churned the relatively shallow <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> into a white-capped maelstrom. Waves crashed over the bows of the warships and their hulls were exposed to view as they hobby-horsed up the Hormuz. Although routine for the 202 crew members, pursuit of the Iranian vessel had considerable minute-by-minute drama. The Roberts combat information center, its computer screens aglow like a video arcade, tracked a variety of unidentified air and sea `` contacts'' as the ship headed south. <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON> ordered his second gas turbine engine fired up to help drive the ship at up to 26 knots, then varied speed as the Tomb became a visible light in the distance. Huge waves were illuminated by phosphorescent plankton and jellyfish, glowing like submerged flashlights of green, blue and white. The 4,200-ton <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> rolled as much as 35 degrees during the dash down the gulf, causing equipment not lashed down to clatter across the decks, tipping over chairs in the officers' wardroom and spilling some off-duty sailors from their berths. The seas became so rough that the lookout stationed in a chair on the ship's `` bullnose'' was pulled in for fear he might be washed overboard.
