<HEAD>Study: Long-Term Use Does Not Increase Long-Term Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Long-term use of birth-control pills, even by women who began taking them as teen-agers, does not increase the risk of breast cancer, a new study of more than 9,000 women concludes. The findings were reported in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Previous studies disagreed over whether the pill increases the risk of breast cancer for women through middle age. Some researchers have suggested the conflicting conclusions might be the result of a long-term latent effect from early use. `` But we found no direct human evidence for such a latent effect,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON>, one of the study's authors. <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON> was at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> when the study was conducted and now is with the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, Md. `` This was a very, very large study ... and these data are immensely reassuring,'' he said. `` Nonetheless, everyone in the field believes additional large studies should be conducted in the 1990s, when the women we interviewed will be in their mid-60s.'' Early and prolonged use were defined as using oral contraceptives for at least six years before age 25, according to <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON> and his colleagues, who were from the <ORGANIZATION> Uniformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, Md. Researchers collected case histories and interviewed 4,714 women through age 54 who had developed breast cancer, then matched them with a control group of 4,540. `` We looked at many different facets, and broke the subjects into many different groups to isolate other factors,'' said <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON>. `` But the thing we consistently found is that women who used the pill for a long time, whether they were young when they began ... the relative risks were the same when compared to women who never used the pill when young.'' The study did not examine the effects of short-term use. For women in general, the risk of developing breast cancer during one's lifetime is about one in 10, <PERSON> Stadel </PERSON> said. More than 50 million women worldwide are on the pill, he said.
