<HEAD>US Belittles Soviet Technology For Spotting Nuclear Missiles On
Ships</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 10 grafs after 2nd graf to add U.S. proposals
regarding space-based weapons systems; Picks up 4th graf pvs bgng:
The senior ..., editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> belittled Soviet technology for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an invitation this week to see the process before the May 29-June 2 summit meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Thursday. During three days of pre-summit talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> offered to let the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> participate in an experiment to test the system in April. Meanwhile, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> offered some new proposals of its own regarding space-based weapons systems. One was the exemption of spy satellites from treaty restrictions, an idea that the Soviets apparently found interesting. `` We think they're useful to our security,'' a senior administration official said Thursday. `` They think they're useful to theirs.'' The other idea was that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators make a special effort to define space-based testing and deployment. `` Then we could also work on the idea of having confidence-building measures or what we call predictability measures which could reduce the difficulties between the two sides with respect to other types of systems that might be tested or other kinds of devices,'' the official said. Details of that proposal have not been settled, but officials said the most likely approach would be to allow only a limited number of space weapons prototypes to be tested in a region of space where they would have little value in an actual missile defense. The two proposals were intended to resolve the contentious battle over the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION>, known also as Star Wars, which is possibly the biggest obstacle to reaching agreement to cut long-range nuclear weapons. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Wednesday that the two issues would be negotiated separately but that agreements in the two areas should be `` completed more or less at the same time so the two things move in parallel.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has long said that the two issues should be handled separately. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, meanwhile, said Wednesday night that `` of course there is'' a linkage between resolving the defense in space issues and the treaty to reduce long-range strategic weapons. `` There will be no treaty on the 50 percent reduction in strategic offensive arms if there is no observance of the ABM treaty, at least for an agreed period of time,'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said. The Soviets, as well as some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, say SDI would violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> hailed the system to detect nuclear missiles on ships as a technological milestone in missile detection that would help the superpowers achieve their goal of a summit agreement to cut long-range nuclear arsenals. The senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, however, `` we're not interested'' because the system does n't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise missiles, as the Soviets claim. `` The Soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell us more than we already know,'' the official said. `` Such technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.'' It could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships, the official said. `` Our people know a great deal about the ideas that the Soviets have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official said. When they agreed in principle last December to hold a springtime summit in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50 percent. With little progress _ notably on the verification issues _ during <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for three days this week, neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time. The senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, moreover, that until the negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types of weapons involved, they wo n't know which ones will be covered in a treaty. Another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on such explosive issues as <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and human rights warned against expecting `` easy solutions'' to U.S.-Soviet problems. The official described the most recent talks as `` grueling,'' notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> sought to dispel suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on substantive accomplishments During <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` we made enough progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters. During the talks this week both sides `` faced all the tough problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he said. The summit `` will be well prepared; there will be substance to discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said.
