<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly all of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>'s police officers and firefighters called in sick Thursday to protest a 2 percent pay raise, then ignored back-to-work orders from a judge and the City Council. Less than an hour before an emergency council meeting Thursday afternoon, <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> issued a temporary injunction ordering firefighters to work immediately and police to report at their next scheduled shift. The missing police officers did not report for the 3 p.m. shift, however, and firefighters also refused to report. `` We just want an honest living,'' said Fire Department Lt. <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavender </PERSON>, who was on duty at the city's station No. 1. `` We're going backward in pay. The `` blue flu'' in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s capital and largest city began Wednesday night when officers began refusing to show up for work. At the 6 a.m. shift change, 16 of 17 uniformed police officers and 42 of 44 firefighters scheduled to report failed to show up. Firemen and police officers who were on duty overnight were retained on overtime, giving the fire department a full complement of men, and process servers took return-to-work orders to the absent personnel Thursday afternoon, said Mayor <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> declared a state of civil emergency earlier in the day, saying the policemen and firefighters must return because `` the safety of the citizens of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> is not a bargaining chip.'' Police Chief <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Garnett </PERSON> told an emergency meeting of the city council that only 13 officers, covering all grades, showed up Thursday morning, `` most of them supervisors.'' He said only three cars were on patrol Thursday morning, with two officers in each car. <PERSON> Garnett </PERSON> also told the council members that since Wednesday night 68 officers and 42 firemen had called in sick as of 9 a.m. The city budget, approved Monday night, includes appropriations for 165 policemen, 147 firefighters and 10 paramedics for the city of 63,000. <PERSON> Garnett </PERSON> said the firefighters who were on the job had been there since 8 a.m. Wednesday and were tiring quickly. `` I do n't know how long they can stay there,'' he said. The council unanimously suspended the city's sick-leave policy, meaning that any more officers calling in sick would have to have a doctor's excuse to get paid for any additional days absent from work. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, facing his first crisis since taking over as mayor four months ago, said it was n't illegal to call the council into emergency session on less than four hours' notice and suspend sections of the city code. The code requires two days' notice of emergency meetings. No police or firefighters picketed Thursday, but about 20 police wives marched in front of City Hall and carried signs. Passing motorists honked their horns in support and some _ aware that patrols were down _ took the opportunity to run red lights. `` We have several police officers that qualify for welfare,'' said police wife <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockard </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Kanawha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said his department would provide assistance to the city only `` if there's a murder or something.'' `` We do n't have the manpower to work the city,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. State police Superintendent W.F. <PERSON> Donohoe </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> had asked the governor for state police help. `` We will answer calls on a priority basis to the very best of our ability,'' <PERSON> Donohoe </PERSON> said. The police officers believe their 2 percent raise will be eaten up by a higher deductible on their health insurance and an increase in the city's incinerator fee from $ 30 to $ 85. `` It's not easy to raise the incinerator fee. But without a raise in the incinerator fee, we did n't have money to increase salaries,'' said <PERSON> Councilwoman </PERSON> <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON>. Under the budget approved this week, salaries for uniformed police officers range from $ 27,673 for a captain with 20 years' experience to $ 18,589 for a patrol officer with three years' Mayoral Aide <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Esposito </PERSON> said that no raises had been given this year but that police and firefighters had received a 3 percent raise in the 1986-87 fiscal year and raises totaling 8 percent over the past five years. By comparison, at the <ORGANIZATION> Kanawha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, where deputies have gotten raises totaling 25 percent over the past 3 -LCB- years, a deputy with three years' experience will make $ 21,720 as of July 1, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. City firefighters' pay ranges from $ 27,673 for an assistant fire chief with 20 years' experience to $ 18,409 for a first-year firefighter.
