<HEAD>NMSU Professors Say Documents Show Villa Was Targeted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> history professors said Wednesday that government documents indicate <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> intelligence officers attempted to kill <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> revolutionary <PERSON> Pancho </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> by poisoning in 1916. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON> presented the findings in a paper submitted at a monthly meeting of the Latin American studies forum at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> State. They said the attempt came during an American expedition into <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in pursuit of Villa and his men. The expedition followed a raid by Villa on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> community of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> that left 17 American soldiers and civilians dead. The attempt was made in the town of <LOCATION> Jimenez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, four months after the raid on <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. The plot called for two Japanese men who were employed as secret agents for the American government to put poison in a cup of coffee intended for <PERSON> Villa </PERSON>, the professors said. The two agents posed as peddlers and wanted <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> to think they were sympathetic to his revolutionary cause. Villa foiled the assassination attempt by pouring part of the coffee into another man's cup, the professors said. The fate of the man into whose cup Villa poured the coffee was not known, the professors said. The poison was supposed to be odorless and tasteless and cause death three days after ingestion. Historians consider the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> raid a turning point in the Mexican revolution because it rallied American public opinion against <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> and his men. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pershing </PERSON> led the retaliatory expedition. `` We ca n't prove it but there is no doubt in my mind that he knew'' of the plot, <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON> said. The professors said that while there were official inquiries into the alleged plot, <PERSON> Pershing </PERSON> denied any knowledge of it. The assassination attempt, according to the professors, was covered up.
