<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     03-24 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rashomon' Revived Tellingly off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The telling and retelling of a story of rape and murder from various points of view makes for little suspense, but good acting and direction keep up interest in an off-Broadway revival of the 1959 stage version of `` Rashomon.'' The play by <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanin </PERSON> is based on the 1951 Japanese movie of the same name and on stories by <PERSON> Ryunosuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Akutagawa </PERSON> published in 1915. It is the story of a samurai and his wife who encounter a bandit in the forest. The wife is raped and the samurai is found dead. But the circumstances vary depending on who does the telling. Knowing the rape and death will be depicted several times, the audience can focus on how each person tells the story to paint himself or herself to best advantage. The husband's ghost, conjured up in a courtroom, tells of suicide, while the bandit and the wife both confess to murder. The bandit figures he'll be executed anyway; the wife thinks she'll be pardoned. It would shame them more to be publicly revealed as lacking in the personality they've presented to the world than to proclaim that they were driven to kill. The final version, told by a woodcutter who witnessed the encounter from a hiding place, is hilarious as husband and wife bicker and the honorable samurai and daring bandit are afraid to fight. The entire cast is <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> in this first major revival of the play since it played on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> in 1959 starring <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON>, <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Willman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Homolka </PERSON>. The cast includes <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Saito </PERSON> as the bandit who turns somersaults during swordfights; <PERSON> Kiya </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, who can take on many womanly aspects depending whose story she is acting; <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, who usually is bound and gagged as the husband; <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, the woodcutter, and <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sesma </PERSON>, a priest. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leong </PERSON> expertly directed fights and movement. <PERSON> Mina </PERSON> <PERSON> Albergo </PERSON>'s setting is a forest clearing, alabaster with bamboo-leaf tracings, with the Rashomon Gate at one side. The set enhances the openness with which director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalfin </PERSON> places this `` Rashomon'' before the audience. The play will run through May 8.
</TEXT>
