<NOTE>For Release Friday PMs, March 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Progeria Victim Beating the Odds at Age 15</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At age 15, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON> has appeared in a feature-length movie, has learned to hunt and to ride an off-road motorcycle, and has traveled and made a lot of friends. `` If I die today, I feel like I've had a good life,'' says the boy, who suffers from progeria, a rare condition that has caused his diminutive body to age far beyond his years. Most children with progeria die before reaching their teens, usually of a stroke or heart-related cause. Experts say the condition strikes one in 8 million children, and only about 70 cases have ever been reported. Only 15 or so people are alive today who suffer from the disease, thought to be caused by a genetic pituitary disorder, according to <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s Dr. <PERSON> Geoff </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON>. And yet, except for the fact that he does n't go to school, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> tries to be a typical teen-ager. His life is an ongoing defiance of the odds and medical convention about his condition. `` When they first told my parents about progeria, they said I would n't live more than a month,'' <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> says of the time at age 4 when doctors finally put a name on the condition that had hardened his skin and caused his hair to fall out. `` They keep pushing it back. When I was 5, they said 7. When I was 7, they said 10. When I was 10, they said 12. Now I'm 15, and they say 18.'' It's gotten so that <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> does n't listen anymore and visits a physician just once a year for a checkup. `` I feel fine. I feel great,'' he said in a recent interview in his rural <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION> home. Two years ago, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> suffered congestive heart failure brought on by progeria, but now his only disability seems to be that sunshine or other bright light hurts his eyes. Still, he did n't let the sun keep him from going on a church-sponsored youth trip to a water park in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, 100 miles away, or from being outside with friends. He simply wears a cap. As he nears his 16th birthday on June 30, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> looks forward to a rite of passage: obtaining a driver's license and a pickup truck _ `` a jet black <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> hardbody,'' he says. Extenders attached to the controls of his mother's van helped <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON>, who is only 3 feet tall, learn to drive. But like many of his friends, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> drives his own four-wheel motorcycle through the piney woods that surround his home. `` Just about everybody has motorcycles and four-wheelers,'' <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> explains. `` There's a hill everybody goes to called ` The Mountain.' It's the highest point in <LOCATION> Gregg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and from there you can look down on <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION>. It's real nice.'' Over pizza, two of <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON>'s friends, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Head </PERSON>, talked about rock concerts they've attended with him in <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. They teased him about new cowboy boots and about not attending school. `` I'd stay in school just to be around everybody,'' <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON>, who would be in 10th grade, does n't attend classes: `` I quit after seventh grade. I got in too much trouble. I did n't like being told to shut up. When his friends are in school, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> spends his days working on his four-wheeler, hunting in season -LRB- he has bagged five deer and 16 raccoons -RRB-, watching soap operas, listening to pop musicians <PERSON> Tiffany </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Whitesnake </ORGANIZATION>, and playing with his toddler brother, <PERSON> Jared </PERSON>. He mows yards for neighbors and occasionally works in his mother <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON>'s income tax preparation office and his stepfather <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON>'s business machine outlet. `` There's always a way to make money,'' <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> said, adding that his favorite way would be to work in show business again. He played a gentle old visitor from space in `` The Aurora Encounter,'' a 1985 feature-length movie, and now envisions a part in a credit card commercial: `` Do you know me?'' he would ask. `` I'm not an alien who visited <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in the 19th century just to be killed by a frightened <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Ranger. That's just a movie role I played.'' Because of the movie part, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> says he became `` somebody'' rather than `` somebody different.'' `` People before always used to notice me as somebody different,'' <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> said. `` Now I go somewhere and people recognize me as <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>, someone who played in a movie.'' The role is one of two experiences in recent years that <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> said built his self-esteem. The second was meeting <PERSON> Fransie </PERSON> <PERSON> Geringer </PERSON>, the progeric son of a South African coal miner, in 1982. It was the first time either boy had met someone else with progeria. They met at <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> later visited <PERSON> Fransie </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Orkney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Now, the two have linked with about 15 other progeric children and many of them started attending an annual reunion a few years ago. Of the progeric children who attend, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> said he is the oldest and possibly the healthiest. A Canadian girl, six months older than <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON>, died recently, according to his mother. `` <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> and I have had a nice life, but there are times when you start feeling sorry for yourself,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON> said. `` If someone says, ` I know how you feel,' well, it's nice, but at the reunions, other parents really do know how I feel.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON> takes pictures of <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> as an infant, when he looked like any normal baby, to the reunions to show the other parents. `` They look at <LOCATION> Mickey </LOCATION> and I and see what's ahead. They really ca n't imagine what their children will be like. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> being so outgoing gives them hope.'' Progeric children should consider themselves very lucky if they live to age 20, Dr. <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> said. Still, when the conversation turns to mortality, <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> speaks without hesitation of his Baptist upbringing. `` I think I'll live as long as God wants me to live. Everybody's got to die sometime.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, March 25</NOTE>
