<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv02-03   03-24 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 02-03,0985</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv02-03</NOTE>
<HEAD>Advance for Weekend Editions, April 2-3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jeep Cherokee Limited Is Luxurious Off-roader</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> legend has turned luxurious. Just look at the 1988 Jeep Cherokee Limited 4-Wheel-Drive. While it carries the Jeep name _ for years synonymous with ruggedness, versatility and a certain wilderness-military strength _ this compact model has many of the same features of expensive European cars. There are the leather, wingback, front bucket seats with six-way power adjustment _ standard equipment. There is the 18-ounce carpeting, tinted glass and three-spoke, leather-wrapped steering wheel _ all standard. And yes, there is the $ 22,000-plus price tag for the two-door model, $ 23,000-plus for four doors. Designed with image-conscious buyers in mind, this is no ordinary Jeep. But then, in a comforting sort of way, it is. Once in four-wheel-drive, the Jeep Cherokee Limited eagerly takes on snow, ice, mud, whatever, giving the driver that confidence and peace of mind that have given Jeep its American legend reputation and left other vehicles in the ditch. The Cherokee, which comes in many versions besides the Limited, has won several awards since its debut in the 1984 model year. At that time, it was the first vehicle to be a simultaneous winner by three four-wheel-drive specialty magazines, Four Wheeler, 4Wheel & amp; Off Road and Off-Road. For the 1988 model year, Cherokee was picked Four Wheeler of the Year in the sport utility segment by <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheeler </ORGANIZATION> magazine and 4x4 of the Year by <ORGANIZATION> 4Wheel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Off Road magazine. It marks the first time a vehicle has repeated as a 4x4 award-winner. With a lineup ranging from a $ 12,538 four-wheel-drive version to the upscale Limited, the Cherokee has been a hit with buyers, too. Sales of the four-wheel-drive Cherokees plus four-wheel-drive Wagoneers _ a larger, top-of-the-line Jeep _ reached a third consecutive record in the 1987 model year with 110,962 sold. That's up from 109,929 in the 1986 model year and 97,802 in the 1985 model year Jeeps are built in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and are heading for record sales in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which last August bought Jeep-maker <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. American buyers of Cherokees have median age of 37-41 with household income of $ 50,000 - $ 55,000, said <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, manager of Jeep public Sixty percent are college educated. The top three reasons buyers give is the four-door availability, the off-road capability and its alternative to a family car, she said. Jeep is the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nameplate to offer a four-door sport utility vehicle. Increasingly, women are the owners and principle drivers of the vehicles, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> said, noting a 1987 survey found females accounted for 40 percent of Cherokee buyers-major drivers. Women like the option of going from two-wheel to four-wheel-drive and not having to fear getting stranded, they like the interior and they appreciate the good visibility from the Cherokee's tall profile, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> explained. The test model was impressive in both two-wheel and four-wheel-drive. A shift lever on the trasnmission console allowed the driver to choose which was appropriate for road-off-road conditions. The standard, electronic fuel-injected, 4-liter six-cylinder engine was peppy, mated with the standard four-speed automatic transmission. The engine is rated at 177 horsepower at 4,500 rpm and is the most powerful engine of its size in the light-duty truck market, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said. There was a trade-off in handling, however. While the vehicle performed superbly off road, the same design that permits such driving also made for a sometimes bouncy, jostling ride on pavement, especially at highway speeds on roads where expansion cracks were uneven. Drivers should be aware that sport utility vehicles such as the Cherokee handle differently from cars. There have been complaints of rollover accidents, and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> warns in the owner's manual that the vehicle's higher center of gravity and narrow track affect handling. Drivers should not make sharp turns or abrupt maneuvers that could lead to loss of control. But being seated up high also is advantageous. I could see over and around most other vehicles and was able to spot traffic bottlenecks well before I came upon them. On the down side, I had to hike up straight skirts to climb into the Cherokee and it was difficult to emerge gracefully. I wound up taking a flying leap from the driver seat. The rear liftgate was well-designed with washer-wiper that kept the rear view clear and a door that went up easily, leaving a flat opening so I did n't have to heave items up and over the back of the vehicle. The leather seats were comfortable and seating, front and back, was spacious. There were amenities such as front map reading lights, tilt steering and power antenna. But the front vent windows on the test model took a lot of effort to open. The key would not always come out of the ignition after I put the shifter in park and turned off the engine. Often, I had to slam the shifter forward again to free the key. And the cruise control, on the turn signal stalk, sometimes wound up in the `` on'' position when it was n't activated. Another point: Consumer Reports' survey of owners shows Cherokees in the 1984-6 model years ranked much worse than average than other cars and trucks in having problems and needing repair.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, executive business editor of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 2-3</NOTE>
