<HEAD>Moore McCormack Announces Recapitalization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hostile takeover target <ORGANIZATION> Moore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McCormack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has unveiled a $ 400 million recapitalization plan and says it is holding talks with unidentified parties over a possible alternative buyout. The company, target of a hostile $ 35 a share, or $ 441 million, buyout offer from Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday its proposed recapitalization would pay shareholders a special dividend valued at more than $ 33 per share in cash and securities. But <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> acknowledged that it would abandon the dividend payout if it received a buyout offer that `` produces higher values'' for shareholders, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tregurtha </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive. In trading Wednesday on <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> rose $ 1.62 -LCB- to close at $ 38.75 a share. Under terms of a plan approved by the company's board of directors, shareholders would receive a cash dividend of $ 26.60 per common share and a newly created, 15-year subordinated debenture with a face value of $ 6.62. In addition, the board instructed management `` to begin immediately implementing a program that will maximize cash flow, ... reduce costs, and raise cash through the sale'' of the company's oil and gas operations and certain other assets, <PERSON> Tregurtha </PERSON> stated. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> last month rejected the initial bid of $ 31-a-share, or $ 391 million, from <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION>, a cement and energy company. <ORGANIZATION> Southdown </ORGANIZATION> sweetened its offer to $ 35 per share, but <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> McC