<HEAD>Honolulu Mayor Leads Assault Against Japanese Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent wave of Japanese purchases of everything from farmland to memberships at prestigious country clubs has sparked a backlash from residents peeved at a resulting rise in property taxes and longer lines at the golf course. The Japanese have been investing in the Hawaiian islands since statehood, but have drawn criticism because of recent high-profile acquisitions made at premium prices. Many economists and local officials oppose the latest round of `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> bashing,'' calling the foreign-based investment a boon to the state and a sign of Japanese confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. But others, including <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON>, want to limit Japanese investment here. `` They just about own downtown,'' <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> has proposed state legislation to prohibit the sale of residential, agricultural or preservation property to anyone who is not a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen, has no plans to become a citizen or would not live on the land at least half the year. The proposal, based on similar statutes in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, would not affect the sale of commercial, resort and industrial land. It has little chance of being considered by the state legislature because it was submitted late in the session. <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> blames the Japanese for skyrocketing property taxes resulting from rising home prices as well as longer waits for tee-off times at the <ORGANIZATION> Honolulu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, where Japanese nationals pay $ 150,000 for memberships. But he denies his proposal is racist. `` All I'm trying to do is stop the speculators from doing here what they've already done in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' which is price out the average buyer, <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> said. Earlier this week it was announced that a Japanese real estate firm paid a record $ 280 a square foot _ about $ 14 million total _ for a parcel of land in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kapiolani </LOCATION> business district. Japanese investors have paid a total of $ 99 million for property along <LOCATION> Kapiolani </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION> since 1986. Another Japanese investor sparked protests last month over his plans to evict an elderly couple from the agricultural land they had leased for 10 years so he could build a golf course. A Japanese real estate firm recently paid $ 21 million for `` <LOCATION> Casa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blanca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mar </LOCATION>,'' the highest price ever paid for a private home in the exclusive southern <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION> beachfront area of <LOCATION> Waialae-Kahala </LOCATION>. The average value of homes in the neighborhood has risen between 30 percent and 100 percent under the latest city property assessments, mostly because foreign investors have been snapping up houses at high prices. Area residents say they have received unsolicited offers in their mailboxes and been offered millions of dollars in cash for their homes. <PERSON> Wali </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON>, associate economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>, said the strength of the Japanese yen and the ability to borrow against high-priced <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> properties allows the Japanese to pay more than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> buyers. `` What the Japanese are doing is perfectly logical,'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said. `` They would be foolish not to take advantage of the strength of their yen.'' The Japanese have invested heavily in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> since the 1960s. <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said the latest surge _ about $ 3 billion invested since 1986 _ attracted attention only because so many properties were purchased in a short time. `` Maybe they put in a little too much money a little too fast,'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said. `` But $ 3 billion is a small portion of the total assets in the state.'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON>'s proposal ignores the rights of the seller and discriminates against the Japanese. `` People have been selling their houses to the Japanese for twice as much as they could get elsewhere,'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said. `` They've been getting rich What about their right to sell to whoever offers the highest price?'' <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Cayetano </PERSON> dismisses <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON>'s plan as political rhetoric. `` The man's running for re-election,'' <PERSON> Cayetano </PERSON> said. `` But he's a hypocrite On the one hand he's telling the Japanese to pour in their money for business development and then he's saying they ca n't invest in houses here.'' <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> has proposed that Japanese firms be allowed to build a convention center here and that they help finance a light rail rapid transit system. <PERSON> Cayetano </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> was fueling an anti-Japanese attitude that could cause a backlash against Japanese-Americans _ who make up about 25 percent of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s population _ and Japanese visitors, who have invigorated the state's tourist industry. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vistors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, about 20 percent of the 5.7 million people who vacationed in the islands last year were from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. They accounted for 33 percent of vistor expenditures, more than triple the share of their counterparts from the mainland and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON> -RRB- is doing what is politically popular at the moment,'' <PERSON> Cayetano </PERSON> said. `` But here, where the Japanese are so important, it's especially insulting.'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said that if <PERSON> Fasi </PERSON>'s proposal was rejected, the current wave of anti-Japanese sentiment should blow over, as it had in the past. `` This is n't the first time politicians have used this tactic,'' <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> said. `` But we are n't about to become a colony of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and people who think so are just overreacting.''
</TEXT>
