<SECOND>PM-Canada-Hyundai, Bjt,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Assesses Impact of Hyundai Victory in Canadian Dumping
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S. unless otherwise noted.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> warned of future job losses and free-trade problems after a Canadian tribunal dismissed their claims of damages from the sale of inexpensive <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cars from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribunal </ORGANIZATION> ruled Wednesday that it found no evidence of material injury to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries because of the cut-price compact cars that <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> has sold in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> since 1984. The three-member government panel ordered a halt to anti-dumping proceedings against <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> and a refund of some $ 8 million in bonds the company had posted. Wednesday's ruling has implications for all <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> car makers: the Canadian auto industry is linked with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations under a 1965 trade agreement treating the continent as a single market. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> was forced to post the bonds when Revenue <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the government tax collector, upheld the dumping complaint last November and imposed preliminary import duties averaging 26 percent. Dumping is the practice of exporting goods at a price below what they cost in the domestic market. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> accused <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> of introducing its Pony, Stellar and Excel models in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> at below-cost prices to get a foothold in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. They complained they lost profits when they had to slash prices and offer rebates to remain competitive. At hearings that ended March 10, <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged its aim was to gain a path to the lucrative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. But the company denied harming <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> or the Canadian auto industry. <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car giants did not make subcompacts in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and contended <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> was making handsome profits here. Furthermore, both companies have business links to other South Korean carmakers, <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> noted. The Canadian government's <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> intervened on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> to say the company had fostered competition in the small-car market and kept prices down. Within a year of introducing its $ 4,500 Pony hatchback, <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> cornered 7 percent of the Canadian car market. It then expanded to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> where it sold 264,000 Excels last year. But recent Canadian sales were depressed because of the dumping case. If upheld, the duties would have added $ 800 to the price of a new <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION>. The Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Importers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> called the decision a `` triumph'' for consumers, while <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement from <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> welcoming the decision. Whatever the outcome of the case, the South Korean conglomerate had pledged to proceed with plans for a $ 259 million manufacturing plant in <LOCATION> Bromont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, and a parts factory in <LOCATION> Newmarket </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> have 10 days to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>. They said they would decide after receiving the tribunal's detailed explanations next month Both companies warned that unfair foreign competition could lead to job losses in the Canadian industry, which employs 140,000 workers directly and another 400,000 indirectly, mostly in southern <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>. `` It has been and remains our contention that continued unrestrained dumping by <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> will result in lost jobs and investment in the Canadian auto industry,'' stated <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Peapples </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON> complained of flaws in Canadian trade law and said the case set a bad precedent for the Canada-U.S. free trade agreement due for ratification by the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> later this year. <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> said the law forced the tribunal to look at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> production and sales only in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, where small-car output has been phased out, instead of examining <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s integrated operations throughout the continent. `` We're alarmed by the implications today's decision has for other industries which may become rationalized under the free-trade agreement,'' <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> said. He said the shortcoming must be fixed in the first years of the free-trade treaty or more industries will come in for `` predatory dumping.''
