<HEAD>Beazer Makes Higher Koppers Proposal; Koppers Workers Demonstrate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2 of March 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The investment group pursuing <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has proposed a negotiated buyout at $ 60 a share, topping its current hostile offer of $ 56 a share, while hundreds of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> employees demonstrated against the ongoing takeover attempt. The new proposal has an indicated value of about $ 1.68 billion, compared with $ 1.57 billion for the alternative hostile bid. It was made in a letter sent late Wednesday to <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON> from British investor <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> has teamed with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banker, in its attempt to acquire the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> building materials, paving services and chemical company. The hostile tender offer remains in effect, said <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Gara </PERSON> said the company had no immediate comment on the latest proposal. <PERSON> Kopper </PERSON>'s board of directors has rejected <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 56 a share offer as inadequate, and reiterated it was exploring a possible defensive recapitalization that would include a one-time payment to shareholders. `` We believe we are able to offer greater value to your stockholders than any plan you are presently considering,'' <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> stated in his letter to <PERSON> Pullin </PERSON>. `` If you have a recapitalization plan that provides your stockholders and employees with more benefits than we are prepared to provide, we, and your other stockholders, are anxious to see it.'' Separately, about 250 of the company's employees cut up an estimated 175 charge cards from <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 60 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, during a downtown protest. `` We're damn mad,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Beidler </PERSON>. `` We want <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> to know that this gathering is just the tip of the iceberg.'' Management also has canceled its <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> account, through which the company had been buying about $ 1.5 million per year in goods and services, said <PERSON> O'Gara </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> has accused <PERSON> Shearson </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> of offering to defend the company from hostile takeovers at the same time that it was plotting its attack with <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's quite a deal, and we're saying no,'' <PERSON> Beidler </PERSON> said. `` We're going to send our cards back to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> in pieces.'' <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> also have come under fire from state officials for their role in the hostile bid.
