<HEAD>Delay In New Software Depresses Lotus Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s stock could remain depressed for some time following the company's announcement of a six-month delay in the release of a new version of its high-selling 1-2-3 software, industry watchers say. Wall Street analysts this week scaled back their earnings estimates for the company after it delayed the new Release 3 software. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> executives sold off large blocks of stock and a top executive resigned. `` I think the stock is going to underperform until we get closer to the release date on shipment of the 1-2-3 Release 3,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Readerman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> fell $ 3.50 a share to $ 25.25 a share in over-the-counter trading Wednesday, a 12 percent drop in market value. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON> sold 250,000 shares of company stock, and several vice presidents sold between 12,800 shares and 95,800 shares. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Digate </PERSON>, senior vice president in charge of software development, left the company last week. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> said some of the stock sales occurred because executives exercised stock options last August and had to wait six months before selling to meet tax payments. But <PERSON> Readerman </PERSON> said: `` The timing of the sales just raises a credibility issue. That is as much a reason why the stock is down. If it was just the product slip date, I do n't think you'd see the stock where it is.'' Analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> is trailing its competitors in developing new spreadsheet programs and said they expected some of the 3.5 million Lotus 1-2-3 users to defect to other brands. `` For some reason <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> just has n't kept pace with the industry in bringing out new products,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlund </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They've been long on promise in announcing new products but short on delivery.'' Analysts cut <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' 1988 earnings per share estimates to between $ 1.55 and $ 1.65 from about $ 1.95. They also trimmed revenue forecasts for the year to about $ 400 million from $ 465 million. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> last year reported net income of $ 72 million, or $ 1.58 per share, on revenue of $ 395.6 million. The upgraded 1-2-3 software originally was expected in June. The company said the new program, which promises to print better graphs, work faster and combine many spreadsheets, will be available in the fourth quarter. Analysts said the delay would give <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, a chance to gain market share with new software products designed to compete with 1-2-3. Last November, <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> released its Quattro spreadsheet, which has been praised as better than 1-2-3, and <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>, the leading personal computer software maker, released its Windows Excel software. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' investor relations director, said the company needs more time to make the new 1-2-3 programs small enough to work with personal computers. `` We obviously are concerned about the delay,'' <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON> said. `` Any time a product slips it's not good. -LRB- But -RRB- we think it's going to be worth waiting for.'' The new 1-2-3 will cost $ 495, same as the old one. People who have an authorized copy of the current 1-2-3 can upgrade for $ 150. Analysts project $ 100 million to $ 150 million in sales in the first 12 to 18 months of its release. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday named <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a former vice president of development for <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s personal computer division, to replace <PERSON> Digate </PERSON>.
