<HEAD>Warhol-Art Label Goes On Limited Edition Wine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The wine in the $ 3,200 bottle was an acclaimed 1984 merlot, but there was something even rarer about the <ORGANIZATION> Cuvaison </ORGANIZATION> magnum that <PERSON> Texan </PERSON> <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> bought at a recent <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> charity auction. The grape art label on the <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> wine was believed to be the first work designed for wine by the pop art pioneer <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>, who died last year in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at age 58. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> donated the art to the <LOCATION> Cuvaison </LOCATION> winery in the late 1970s. It is a striking, bias-cut piece based on a stylized vision of what <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> thought nature should have made grapes look like: the six grapes are in hues of red and deep green. The overall label, which was placed on just 84 bottles, has <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s name cut in above the art. It was designed and completed last year by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> graphic artist <PERSON> Channing </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON> under commission by <ORGANIZATION> Cuvaison </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Esser </PERSON>. Said <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON>, `` The label was at first considered to be very strange,'' but, like the wine, the work improved with age and came into increasing favor. <PERSON> Esser </PERSON> finally ordered the art made into a finished label, and <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON> readied it for reproduction in a week. `` <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> did many commercial things, but basically <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> was a fine artist,'' said <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON>. `` He was a painter who experimented with silk-screening and avant-garde techniques. I tried to do the same thing, only convert it into something marketable.'' Still under wraps are <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s creations for two other labels, one for white wine, the other for rose. No plans for them have been announced. As a memorial to <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s talent, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>'s industrialist <PERSON> Schmidheiny </PERSON> family, which owns <ORGANIZATION> Cuvaison </ORGANIZATION>, ordered the current labeling limited to 84 bottles. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christina </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidheiny </PERSON> were friends of <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s, and thought to use his work to evoke a fine-arts theme for special wines. `` We intended this label to be one of a series of artist's labels for <ORGANIZATION> Cuvaison </ORGANIZATION>'s special bottlings,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Schmidheiny </PERSON> said `` When the 1984 <ORGANIZATION> Cuvaison </ORGANIZATION> merlot was released, we decided to use his label only on 84 magnum bottles on the occasion of the 15th anniversary of the winery.'' `` As it turned out, the wine itself was very well received ... hopefully a small memorial to Mr. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s great talent.''
