<HEAD>Dollar Steadies at Lower Levels, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar steadied at lower levels early in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today after a sell-off during Asian trading. Gold prices rose. Traders said the dollar was driven downward in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> by trading benefitting the yen and British pound. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators due later today, including personal income for February, were not likely to move the market since an upward revision of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product for the fourth quarter was disregarded Wednesday, dealers said. The growth rate was revised to an annual rate of 4.8 percent, up from the previously reported 4.5 percent. `` There is still room for the yen and the pound to strengthen,'' said a trader in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. That means the dollar could fall a little lower during the course of the day, he said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 126.00 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.6858 West German marks, down from 1.6915; 1.3940 Swiss francs, down from 1.3990; 5.7305 French francs, down from 5.7450; 1.8943 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9005; 1,248.95 Italian lire, down from 1,253.25; 1.2440 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2434. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound was quoted at $ 1.8425, compared with $ 1.8358 Wednesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 452.40 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 453.00. At mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 453.90. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 453.25, up from $ 450.40 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 3.34 to close at $ 455.40 an ounce. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London