<HEAD>Boesky's Home: 700-Man Prison with Slaughterhouse, Boccie</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with prison confirming Boesky's
arrival, picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Our people ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Convicted stock speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who made millions trading on inside information, would earn a maximum of 44 cents an hour at tasks ranging from landscaping to milking cows as an inmate in the prison recommended by his sentencing judge. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, 51, arrived Wednesday afternoon at the <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, prison camp, to begin serving his three-year term, the prison said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasker </PERSON>, who sentenced <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> on Dec. 18, had given him until today to surrender. The <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION> facility, a 700-inmate minimum security facility about 150 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast, is located on about 44,000 acres of heavily forested countryside and contains a dairy, slaughterhouse and furniture factory. Inmates sleep in a former army barracks. <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION> warden <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rison </PERSON> said in a telephone interview last week that if <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> would have no special privileges or cushy prison jobs. `` Our people are assigned based on where our needs are,'' said <PERSON> Rison </PERSON>. `` He could be in the slaughterhouse, he could be in the landscape crew, he could be working in the dairy operation. He will be required to work a fulltime assignment.'' <PERSON> Rison </PERSON> said the pay scale ranged from 11 cents to 44 cents an hour for a 40-hour week. As in other federal prison facilities, the money is credited to an account at the prison commissary, where inmates can buy toiletries, cigarettes and candy. During off hours, <PERSON> Rison </PERSON> said, inmates can play tennis on a single concrete court, lift weights, roll boccie ball, shoot billiards or watch cable television at a half-dozen sets placed around the facility. Inmates have access to eight telephones but <PERSON> Rison </PERSON> said there's a 15-minute limit on calls. <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION> has been home to some other famous convicts, including former <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration aide H.R. <PERSON> Haldeman </PERSON> and fireworks magnate <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moriarty </PERSON>, who was convicted in a major government-bribery and influence-peddling scandal. Convicted spy <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> was incarcerated in <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION>'s maximum-security section but escaped and led authorities on a chase for several months before he was seized in the Northwest. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, formerly one of Wall Street's best known speculators, stunned the financial world in November 1986 when he paid the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> a record $ 100 million fine to settle civil charges of insider trading, the misuse of confidential information to profit in securities deals. Since then he has cooperated extensively with federal investigators. In exchange, he was allowed to plead guilty to a single criminal count of conspiracy to lie to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>'s revelations reportedly have led to death threats against him, and there was speculation he had sought federal custody early because he feared for his life. Last month, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> friend and fellow speculator, was arrested on charges he threatened to kill <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>'s former head trader, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidoff </PERSON>, who also has pleaded guilty to securities fraud and is cooperating with investigators.
</TEXT>
