<HEAD>U.S., Japan Positions Toughen on Beef, Citrus Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> seeks an agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the end of March on opening the Japanese market wider to American beef and citrus fruit, but there still are conflicting opinions in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on the issue, a government official said Thursday. The current agreement on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s quotas on those items expires March 31. Separately, a senior aide to Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> left for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Thursday for talks aimed at a political solution to a dispute over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s construction market. On the agricultural issue, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said this week the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants all quotas dropped by April 1, or it will take the issue to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an international forum for settling trade disputes. <PERSON> Yoshifumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday, `` Our interest is to have a coordinated result, an agreement between the two governments by the end of the month.'' Asked how far <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was willing to go to compromise short of total liberalization, he said there were conflicting opinions and the government was not ready to make a statement. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refuses to negotiate unless <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> sets a clear timetable for liberalization, something <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has been unwilling to do. Members of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal-Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have expressed strong opposition to liberalization. `` <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> is a good place to fight this out,'' said <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hata </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> LDP </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, after arguing in a meeting Wednesday that producing beef and oranges is essential to domestic farmers, and these must be protected. `` A country should be able to produce basic food items on its own,'' said <PERSON> Mitsuru </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Livestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a very big country and so can produce a lot. But <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is very small and thus needs to protect itself.'' While farmers and many consumers fear liberalization will destroy the domestic beef and citrus industry, leading to unemployment and a dangerous dependence on foreign sources of food, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> commented: `` If it did mean some structural adjustment, that's the price we pay for a free and open trading system. We've had some adjustment, too. Last month, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official predicted that imports of beef would be liberalized within two years, with a lifting of restrictions on citrus fruit even sooner. Tentative moves to appease foreign critics include proposals announced Thursday by an advisory council to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, Forestry and Fisheries for a revision of the upper and lower ceilings on domestic beef and pork price supports, said a ministry official who requested anonymity. Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Ichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON>, who is traveling to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to discuss agricultural issues, is scheduled to meet with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Commerce Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. An aide to <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON> declined to specify what new offers, if any, <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON> would make to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in an attempt to settle the dispute. Following the failure of working-level negotiations earlier this month, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials gave <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> two weeks to come up with a satisfactory proposal to end the dispute. Otherwise, they said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may invoke a law calling for compensation from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.
