<FIRST>r f PM-GMRecalls 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Recalls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0422</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 4 grafs, GM also is, on other GM recalls.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has ordered <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to recall almost half a million 1985 cars and light trucks sold under the Chevrolet, <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> and GMC nameplates, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said today. The cars exceed federal standards for carbon monoxide exhaust emissions and for evaporated gasoline, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Such orders are rare and are generally a sign the agency and the manufacturer could not agree on something, such as the cause of the problem, its scope, the necessary repair or terms of the recall. Most recalls are made voluntarily. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office said the company would have a statement later. The company has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the order, or to submit a repair plan for <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s approval before notices are mailed to owners. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the affected vehicles are equipped with 5.0-liter -LRB- 305 cubic inches -RRB- and 5.7-liter -LRB- 350 cubic inches -RRB- engines and were sold as the <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Impala </ORGANIZATION>, Caprice Classic, Camaro, <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Camino </ORGANIZATION>; the Pontiac Firebird, <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION>, Grand Prix and <LOCATION> Parisienne </LOCATION>; and the <ORGANIZATION> GMC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caballero </ORGANIZATION>. Models sold in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which are built to stricter standards, are included. The excessive emissions are in part the result of defects in a thermal vacuum switch in the evaporation control system, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. But the agency said simple replacement of the switch may not completely remedy the problem and further repairs, which it did not specify, may be necessary. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> recalled more than a million vehicles from the 1982 and 1983 model years for similar problems. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> also is recalling about 4,900 1988 Chevrolet Corvettes to fix defective wheel welds that could cause the wheel center to separate from the rim during braking or cornering. The automaker said Wednesday it is also recalling about 460 1987 GMC and Chevrolet full-size vans to correct fuel tank filler pipes that could cause fuel to leak during refueling or turning. No accidents or injuries have been linked to either problem, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. Vehicle owners are being notified of the recall by dealers, who will correct the problems at no charge, the company said. The Corvettes, all equipped with 17-inch wheels, may be missing a weld on some wheels, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. The condition could result in partial loss of steering control and a sudden changed in vehicle direction, the automaker said.
</TEXT>
