<HEAD>Other Airlines Seen Reluctant to Follow Northwest on Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 15th graf bgng `It's a...' to include
passenger and flight attendants' reaction; pick up 16th pvs, `The
new ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines have no immediate plans to match <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' bold new move to ban smoking on most of its flights, and some industry analysts say the carriers are unlikely to do so. Northwest, the nation's fifth-largest airline, announced Wednesday it will prohibit smoking on all its domestic flights except those to and from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and on some foreign routes. The ban makes Minneapolis-based Northwest the first major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline to mandate a smoke-free environment in the air. It goes beyond federal regulations that will outlaw smoking on all domestic flights of two hours or less beginning April 23. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> said its prohibition was a response to passenger and employee requests. A.B. `` Sky'' <PERSON> Magary </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president for marketing, told a news conference in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that while the policy is not without risk, `` we believe more nonsmokers will switch to Northwest than smokers will leave.'' Wall Street seemed unimpressed by <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s smoke-free innovation. The airline's stock closed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> at $ 45.75 a share, down 12 -LCB- cents from Tuesday. Some analysts believe <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> risks chasing away potential passengers, and other big airlines appear reluctant to follow the carrier's lead. `` We have no plans to follow that move,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for No. 2 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Recent surveys conducted by American indicated a significant segment of people who want to smoke on planes, despite a growing demand for smoke-free areas, she said. American and several other big airlines contacted Wednesday stressed that they planned to establish no-smoking policies in line with the new federal law. Under those rules, passengers who insist on lighting up will face civil fines of as much as $ 1,000, and fliers who tamper with smoke alarms in airplane lavatories face up to $ 2,000 in penalties. `` We are ready to implement our no-smoking policy ... in line with the federal law,'' said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>. United, the nation's largest airline, has had a smoking ban in place since Jan. 1 on all its flights within <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, in accordance with a state law. Fourth-ranked <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> has garnered a lot of support for its own <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> smoking ban, spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s reaction to <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s move was `` really tough to call,'' but did not rule out further action by his airline. `` We will of course take a look at what <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> is doing and see if we want to make an adjustment to our program,'' <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said he did not expect the other carriers to match <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s policy. `` It's a gutsy move and most airlines do n't make gutsy moves,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` It could alienate some people.'' Three smokers, who were waiting to depart on <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> flights Wednesday from Minneapolis-St. <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, said they do n't object to the carrier's new smoking ban `` It's probably a good idea,'' <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> real estate broker, told the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>. `` I can get by without smoking.'' Even some <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants, who are smokers, told the newspaper the new policy might help them quit smoking. The new policy, called `` Northwest Clears the Air,'' will take effect April 23, the same day as the new federal regulations. It will apply to flights within the contiguous 48 states and flights to and from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five hours, according to the airline. About 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic flights and about 20 percent of all domestic flights last more than the two-hour duration covered by the new federal smoking regulations Northwest flights to and from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and overseas will continue offering smoking sections because those flights `` carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the issue,'' the airline stated. `` We still have -LRB- foreign -RRB- competitors that are handing out cigars to passengers on board,'' <PERSON> Magary </PERSON> said. But even that could be changing. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.K. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a small British airline that flies to destinations in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, is banning smoking on all its flights effective next Sunday. And a spokesman in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, one of the world's largest airlines, said the carrier was looking `` quite seriously'' at the possibility of banning smoking on both short and long flights. The trend also has appeared in <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Government-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Singapore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> unveiled plans Wednesday to introduce the first no-smoking commercial flights in the region next month. Smoking will be barred on four of the 14 daily shuttle flights between <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>, the capital of neighboring <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, starting April 4. The trip takes about 45 minutes.
