<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the British brewing company, said Thursday its earnings more than quadrupled in 1987 due to extraordinary items. <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> said it earned 474 million pounds, or $ 867 million, up from 113 million pounds in 1986. The company attributed the increase to one-time gains of 217 million pounds, including 29 million pounds of unauthorized payments relating to the April 1986 takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Sales fell 9 percent to 2.82 billion pounds from 3.1 billion pounds. Police have charged six people, including former <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, for alleged offenses related to the Distillers takeover. On Thursday, police arrested British stockbroker <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Parnes </PERSON> in connection with the Guinness scandal when he voluntarily returned to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after being held in a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> jail for six months for extradition proceedings. <PERSON> Parnes </PERSON>, 42, who was arrested at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport, faces 19 charges including aiding and abetting the theft of money from the brewing company. He is accused of setting up and operating an illegal share support operation during the Guinness takeover bid for <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> has admitted it paid outsiders millions of pounds to buy <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> stock to make the brewer's cash and stock offer for <ORGANIZATION> Distillers </ORGANIZATION>, a gin and whisky maker, more attractive than a rival bid. The company did not break down its quarterly or six-month results. Corporations are not required to do so under British law.
