<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Baker Opposes Disclosure of Foreign Investors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday that disclosing names of foreign investors would damage the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Proposals for some disclosure are in trade bills now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` If enacted, the ... provision would have a chilling effect on foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ thereby costing jobs, raising interest rates, lowering productivity, closing off opportunities for technological and managerial improvements, and undermining our efforts to liberalize investments abroad,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. His opposition was in a written statement sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Sponsors of the proposal, Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, came to a committee hearing and said they were sorry <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> did not appear in person. `` Not one of the G-7 countries -LRB- <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> -RRB- has a publicly available national register of foreign investments of the type prescribed by <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> wrote. `` Not one discloses to the public ongoing information about the status of specific private investors and their investments; not one requires systematic reporting by foreign investors or domestic firms for this purpose.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s views were challenged by <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, though he did not refer to <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> said most countries require more information than his bill is seeking, and in addition require their governments to clear investments in advance. His proposal does not seek that kind of clearance. `` Even <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> keeps a public registry of Swiss companies with foreign ownership,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s preclearance process seems one of the most stringent, in part because it is the most explicit ... <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> flatly prohibits foreign ownership of more than 25 percent in any of its high-tech companies.''
