 <ORGANIZATION> Rolls-Royce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the airplane engine maker privatized by the government last year, on Thursday reported a 12 percent increase in its net profit for 1987. Strong gains in the group's civil aviation division more than offset a sharp rise in research and development costs, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Rolls-Royce </ORGANIZATION>, which is a separate company from the luxury car maker, reported 1987 net profit of 134 million pounds, or $ 247 million, up from 120 million pounds, or $ 221 million a year earlier. Per share earnings came to 20.1 pence, or 37 cents, compared with 18.9 pence, or 35 cents, a year earlier. Sales increased 14 percent to 2.06 billion pounds, or $ 3.8 billion, from 1.8 billion pounds, or $ 3.3 billion in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Rolls-Royce </ORGANIZATION> Chairman Sir <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tombs </PERSON> said: `` Our order book is strong and our wide stable of competitive engines gives us an excellent opportunity to consolidate our existing customer base and secure some of the attractive new sales opportunities which are appearing around the world.'' The company did not break out quarterly or six-month results. It is n't required to under British law.
