<FIRST>r f AM-Tax-Lawsuit     03-24 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax-Lawsuit,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Fighting Suit That Could Cost $140 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court challenge to a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> tax on insurance premiums and annuities will decide whether the Department of Revenue owes out-of-state insurance companies $ 140 million in refunds. The companies do n't like the way the state currently assesses taxes on money that consumers pay to insurers _ a 2 percent tax on premiums and 1 percent tax on annuities. The tax is paid only by out-of-state companies, not by Florida-based insurers. The out-of-state companies say that is n't fair, and many of them have asked for refunds The law was changed last year to require all insurance companies, including those based in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, to pay the premium insurance tax, but that change wo n't take effect until July 1. The state targeted one case _ <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ to be a test case in circuit court. `` If -LRB- the case -RRB- comes down in our favor, we'll be all right financially,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, an attorney in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>, one of three state agencies in the case. `` If not, there's a lot of money involved.'' New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> sought a refund of $ 1.5 million that it paid in taxes in 1983, 1984 and 1985. It is one of 210 companies that have filed for a total of $ 140 million in refunds _ an amount roughly equal to the entire budget for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's substantial,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, which is handling the case. In its refund claim, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> argued that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in 1985 that such disriminatory taxing policies were unconstitutional. According to the state comptroller's office, out-of-state insurance companies have filed claims to recover taxes paid as long ago as the mid-1970s. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> argued on the state's behalf that the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> tax law should be considered legal until courts rule on its constitutionality. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> also claimed that the out-of-state insurance companies passed along the tax to consumers through its premiums and refunding the money would unjustly enrich the companies. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> is involved because the comptroller rules on requests for tax refunds. The Department of Revenue both collects the tax and makes the refunds, while the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> regulates the insurance industry.
</TEXT>
