ded its compliance efforts'' with reforms which `` are now an integral part of the way GEG does business.'' Under the agreement, which still must be approved by a court, the government has agreed not to prosecute the company further on the contracts, but reserves the right to prosecute individuals. The court documents also say the firm mischarged labor costs for work on 10 contracts involving production of target detecting devices for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Standard missile. The third count in the criminal information said <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> mischarged labor costs on a contract for the production of targeting detecting devices for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> missile. <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 16.7 million in criminal fines, restitution and civil penalties. The company already has paid $ 6.8 million to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The pleas result from an investigation into labor and materials charging and pricing practices by <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> from 1979 to 1984.
